<!-- pp. 1-20 -->

## Note to the 2010 edition

### Context and Relevance

- Book first published 1975, when price comparisons with 1920s had limited value
- By 2010: currencies merged, diverged, depreciated, or disappeared; costs and wages risen/fallen without uniformity
- Statistical calculations show 1923 pound sterling = £623 in 2010; 1923 dollar = $220 in goods/services
- **Numerical designations preserved from Weimar period**: milliard = 1,000 million, billion = million × million, trillion = 1,000,000 cubed

### The Lesson Remains

- **No advanced economy is immune** from severe inflation approaching post-Imperial Germany levels
- Sobering lesson for 21st century: **folly of choosing soft options** when nation's economy needs protection
- Waiting until politically expedient but economically too late = suicidal policy

### Quantitative Easing Warning

- Money may no longer be physically printed in 1923's voluminous quantities
- **"Quantitative easing"** = modern euphemism for surreptitious deficit financing in electronic era
- Assault on monetary discipline regardless of reason for deficit (necessity, profligacy, unwillingness to tax, blindness to expenditure)
- Postponing reckoning doesn't prevent higher unemployment or deeper recession
- **Alarming**: respected bankers/economists in US and Britain still commend "printing press" as fail-safe, last resort
- Budget can be balanced that way, but at cost of citizens' savings, pensions, confidence, morals, and morale

### Historical Parallels to 1970s

- 1975 context: rocketing prices/wages, strikes, closures, unemployment, helplessness, hopelessness
- US inflation 8%, Britain rising 10-27% (still 18% in 1981 before Thatcher/Howe disciplines defeated it), Japan rose 30%
- Valid measures needed to restore equilibrium were fierce and long; scars of disease and recovery slow to heal

### Trust in Currency as Central Theme

- As trust evaporates, people spend faster, velocity of circulation increases, money does less work, prices rise, more money needed
- **Quantity theory of money**: finest object lesson was Germany after WWI
- Opinion divides: deflation or inflation or both; harsh State contraction or neo-Keynesian relaxation and quantitative easing

### German Determination Never to Return

- **Ill-judged philanthropic social experiments and ill-funded wars** should be included among causes
- Germany experienced this twice
- Weimar Republic's experience explains country's continuing determination, in or out of Euro-zone, **never to return**

## Prologue

### Literature Gap on Inflation's Human Impact

- When nation's money loses security, inflation becomes entire people's concern
- Natural to turn to history of societies who underwent this tragic, upsetting experience
- **Shortage in existing literature**: economic analyses ignore human element; historical accounts underestimate inflation as engine of upheavals
- Economic analyses (from economists who think inflations are deliberate fiscal policy acts) ignored human element in Weimar Republic and post-revolutionary Austria
- Historical accounts overlooked or underestimated **inflation as one of most powerful engines** of upheavals they narrate

### First-hand Accounts vs. Anthologies

- First-hand accounts/diaries invaluable for human aspect but have too narrow field of vision
- Battle from one shell-hole looks different from another
- 1923 financial extravaganza often recalled in general way that **underplays many years of misfortune** of which it was climax and herald

### Inflation as Pain

- **Agony of inflation like acute pain**: totally absorbing, demanding complete attention while it lasts; forgotten/ignorable when gone
- Strange divorce of Weimar inflation episode from contemporary incident
- Despite persistent, extended, terrible inflation and baleful consequences, **no study complete without continual reference** to this one obsessive circumstance

### Political Context Essential

- **Cannot give fair account** of German inflation outside context of:
  - Political subversion by Nationalists and Communists
  - Turmoil in Army
  - Quarrel with France
  - Problem of war reparations
  - Parallel hyperinflations in Austria and Hungary
- How gauge political significance or judge circumstances where **inflation takes root and becomes uncontrollable** unless charted side by side with political events?

### The Four Villains of 1923

- **Germany of 1923** = Germany of four grotesque figures equally representing villains of the play:
  - **Ludendorff**: soulless, humourless ex-Quartermaster-General, Thor/Odin worshipper, rallying point and dupe of reactionary forces
  - **Stinnes**: plutocratic profiteer who owed allegiance only to Mammon
  - **Havenstein**: mad banker whose one object was to swamp country with banknotes
  - **Hitler**: power-hungry demagogue whose every speech and action called forth all evil in human nature
- Re Havenstein alone description unjust; **but his sound mind made no difference to wreckage he wrought**

### No Real Villains?

- Or say there were **no real human villains**; given economic/political cues, actors would have come on to play parts circumstances dictated
- Many others as reprehensible and irresponsible
- **German people were the victims**
- Battle left them dazed and inflation-shocked; didn't understand how it happened or who defeated them

### Book's Approach: Forgotten Facts and Unpublished Opinions

- Presents few new facts, but **many forgotten facts and hitherto unpublished opinions**
- Most useful: those who could observe objectively because purses, health, security unaffected
- **British Foreign Office records**: most bountiful store of such material
  - Supplied by embassy in Berlin where **Lord D'Abernon** presided
  - One of most successful ambassadorships of the age
  - Amply augmented by consular service in every important German city
  - Reports from Allied commission members on reparations/disarmament
- **Public Record Office documents**: most important source available
  - British Embassy through D'Abernon in exceptionally close touch with Germany's senior politicians
  - US withdrawal from Paris in 1919 and almost complete interruption of Berlin-Paris communication rendered sporadic/superficial what might have been comparable value
- Supplemented by contemporary German material; drew fully on those papers

### Historical Sequence and Relationships

- Tried to keep actions, reactions, interactions in **proper historical sequence**
- Hope this obvious order is both new and enlightening
- Better to expose number of important but little-noticed relationships
- Special thread wound through Austria, Hungary, Russia, Poland, France: **effect of inflation on people as individuals and nations, and how they responded**

### Not an Economic Study

- **Not dared to draw hard/fast conclusions** about humanity and inflation based on this book
- Facts speak well for themselves
- **Not expounded economic lessons or indulged in theoretical explanations**
- Emphatically **not an economic study**
- Yet inflation is about **money as well as people**
- **Impossible to tell tale without introducing vast figures again and again**
- Vast figures = what people of central Europe were assailed by and bludgeoned with for years until they could bear no more

### Understanding the Mark's Value

- Value of mark in 1922 and 1923 in everyone's mind; **but who could comprehend figure followed by dozen ciphers?**
- October 1923: British Embassy in Berlin noted **number of marks to pound equalled number of yards to the sun**
- **Dr Schacht** (Germany's National Currency Commissioner): at end of Great War theoretically could have bought 500,000,000,000 eggs for same price as before war; five years later, only single egg procurable
- When stability returned, sum of paper marks needed to buy gold mark = **precisely equal to quantity of square millimetres in square kilometre**
- Far from certain such calculations helped anyone understand

### Notation Conventions

- Tried to avoid billions/trillions notation upon which custom confusingly divided
- When departed from practice, due indication given

### Language of Disaster

- **Harder to find simple epithets** to describe continuous, worsening succession of misfortunes
- **Mr Lloyd George writing 1932**: words like 'disaster', 'ruin', 'catastrophe' ceased to rouse genuine apprehension; fallen into common usage
- Disaster itself devalued: in contemporary documents word used year after year to describe situations **incalculably more serious** than time before
- When mark finally dropped out of sight and ruin all around, still Germans predicting **Katastrophe** for future
- Tried to **limit number of disasters, crashes, cataclysms, collapses, catastrophes** in text to digestible amount

### Currency Conversion Challenges

- Frequently necessary to give 1920s' sterling or dollar equivalents of mark sums to show scale of mark's depreciation
- Continuing inflation in all western countries makes conversion to present-day values unrewarding
- For lowest range: kept to £sd system of 12 pence to shilling, 20 shillings to pound
- Cost of living comparisons fairly futile
- **Middle of 1975**: necessary to multiply every 1920 sterling figure by about 15× to find equivalent
- Wage of £200 in 1919 might be worth £3,000 in 1975; ten shillings worth £7-8
- For dollars: multiplicator of 6-8× could be enough
- **Mark in 1913**: would buy almost pound's worth of goods/services in 1975 (some items much more expensive, others like labour much cheaper in real terms)
- Simple but rough conversion available for sterling readers: **£148,000,000 for postage stamp: for marks read pounds**

### Internal vs. External Depreciation

- **No constant rule** for coping accurately with later stages of inflation
- Until autumn 1921: internal depreciation of mark lagged far behind fall abroad — making Germany **haven for tourists**
- Later (from beginning 1922): as public confidence in mark dissolved, **domestic prices adjusted rapidly upwards** in tune with dollar rate
- At end prices even **heftily anticipating the mark's fall**
- One more phenomenon that fatally confused issue and exercised economists for years afterwards

### Moral Tale: Sound Money as First Bastion

> "This is, I believe, a moral tale. It goes far to prove the revolutionary axiom that if you wish to destroy a nation you must first corrupt its currency. Thus must sound money be the first bastion of a society's defence."

## 1: Gold for Iron

### Pre-War Currency Stability

- Just before WWI in 1913: German mark, British shilling, French franc, Italian lira all worth about the same
- 4-5 of any worth about a dollar
- End of 1923: possible to exchange shilling, franc, or lira for up to 1,000,000,000,000 marks
- In practice by then **no one willing to take marks** in return for anything
- **Mark was dead, one millionth of former self**
- Took almost ten years to die

### The Gradual Fall and Sudden Collapse

- Mark's fall began gradually during war years 1914-1918: foreign exchange value halved, and by August 1919 had halved again
- Early 1920: cost of living risen less than 9× since 1914, but mark had only **one-fortieth of overseas purchasing power** left
- Twelve months nervous fluctuation
- Then mark **sped downwards with gathering momentum**, dragging social misery and political disruption in wake
- Not until 1923 did Germany's currency finally **go over cliff-edge of sanity** to which it had clung for many months with slipping finger-tips
- Pursuing money of Austria and Hungary into abyss, **crashed there more heavily** than either

### 1923: The Year of Madness

- **Year 1923**: year of galloping inflation when **kind of madness gripped Germany's financial authorities** and economic disaster overwhelmed millions
- Year of astronomical figures, 'wheelbarrow inflation', financial phenomena never observed before
- Death of old mark in November 1923 = **merciful release**
- Events of preceding eight months ensured old mark could never recover
- Ensured Germany would have to undergo **appalling rigours of financial reconstruction** such as might otherwise have been escaped
- **Re-establishment of monetary sanity**: bankrupted thousands, robbed millions of livelihoods, killed hopes of millions more
- Indirectly **exacted more terrible price which whole world had to pay**

### 1923 as Historical Curiosity vs. Permanent Significance

- Inflation of 1923 so preposterous, end so sudden, story tends to be passed off as **historical curiosity** (which it also was)
- Than as **culmination of chain of economic, social, political circumstances** of permanent significance
- Matters little that causes of Weimar inflation unrepeatable; political conditions different, or almost inconceivable that financial chaos would be allowed to develop so far
- **Question to be asked — danger to be recognised**: how inflation affects nation: government, people, officials, society
- **More materialist that society, possibly more cruelly it hurts**

### Inflation's Destructive Power

- If what happened to defeated Central Powers in early 1920s anything to go by, then **process of collapse** of recognised, traditional, trusted medium of exchange, currency by which all values measured, social status guaranteed, security depends, fruits of labour stored, **unleashes such greed, violence, unhappiness, hatred** (largely bred from fear) as **no society can survive uncrippled and unchanged**

### Beyond Economic Catastrophe

- 1922 and 1923 brought **catastrophe** to German, Austrian, Hungarian bourgeoisie, as well as hunger, disease, destitution, sometimes death to wider public
- Yet any people might have ridden out those years had they represented **one frightful storm in otherwise calm passage**
- What most severely damaged morale: they were merely **climax of unreality** to years of unimagined strain of every kind
- **Financially, for nearly four years, ultimate cataclysm always just round corner**
- Always arrived, always worse one on way — again, and again
- Speeches, newspaper articles, official records, diplomatic telegrams, letters, diaries: all report month by month, year by year, **things could not go on like that any longer**: yet things always did, from bad to worse, to worse, to worse
- **Unimaginable in 1921 that 1922 could hold any more terrors**
- They came, were eclipsed, more than eclipsed with turn of following year

### Winter of Revolutions 1918-1919

- Ascribe despair entirely to inflation would be misleading
- In winter 1918-1919: all three underwent **political revolutions** following deprivations of wartime and crushing military defeat
- Conditions fundamentally unfavourable to any revival of national spirit not rooted in revenge
- Would have remained so even had peace treaties permitted losers to struggle however gradually to their economic feet
- **Not always clear** what events contributed to inflationary panic; or which were themselves directly/indirectly caused by ceaseless depreciation of currency and rise in cost of living

### Inflation's Universal Corrosion

- Undoubtedly, inflation **aggravated every evil**, ruined every chance of national revival or individual success
- Eventually produced precisely conditions in which **extremists of Right and Left** could raise mob against State, set class against class, race against race, family against family, husband against wife, trade against trade, town against country
- **Undermined national resolution** when simple want or need might have bolstered it
- Partly because of **unfairly discriminatory nature**, brought out worst in everybody:
  - Industrialist and worker, farmer and peasant, banker and shopkeeper, politician and civil servant, housewife, soldier, merchant, tradesman, miner, moneylender, pensioner, doctor, trade union leader, student, tourist
  - **Especially the tourist**
- Caused fear and insecurity among those who already knew too much of both
- Fostered **xenophobia**
- Promoted **contempt for government** and subversion of law and order
- Corrupted even where corruption had been unknown, too often where it should have been impossible
- **Worst possible prelude** (though detached from it by several years) to great depression; and thus to what followed

### Historical Setting and Limits of Analogy

- That is to put inflation of early 1920s back in historical setting
- From there, very probably, unwise to try too hard to rise it
- No one would argue strongly that **German inflation directly caused world depression**
- Nor even that it alone spawned Nazi Germany
- Unquestionably **made one more unbearable** and, as contributary cause, **made much easier coming of the other**
- Purpose in pages which follow: **not to predict by analogy similar destiny** for any industrialised, democratic nation in grip of severe inflation
- Rather, by recounting extraordinary story, to **present some evidence** of what inflation may do to people, and what in consequence they may do to one another

### Origins: Internal and External

- **Origins of German inflation**: in some ways fundamental, in some ways incidental, to this theme
- **Both internal and external**
- Even during war, Germany's financial arrangements such as to **permit grossest monetary excesses** by national banking system
- Eventually to **render post-war inflation uncontrollable**
- Nature and presentation of Entente's reparation demands — **indemnity for war** — encouraged activities of printing presses to **utter exclusion of other, more desirable policies**
- Nor may it be overlooked that **Germany's industrialists ruthlessly drove their Government** down road to monetary doom

### Public Misperception: "The Dollar is Going Up"

- Natural reaction of most Germans, Austrians, Hungarians: not to assume **money was falling in value** as goods it bought became more expensive in absolute terms
- Not that currency depreciating, but (especially in beginning) that **other currencies unfairly rising**, so pushing up price of every necessity of life
- Reflected point of view of those who **believe sun, planets, stars revolve with moon around earth**

### Erna von Pustau's Interview

- In lengthy interview many years afterwards with **Pearl Buck**, **Erna von Pustau** (whose father was small Hamburg businessman running fishmarket) made same point:

> "We used to say 'The dollar is going up again', while in reality the dollar remained stable but our mark was falling. But, you see, we could hardly say our mark was falling since in figures it was constantly going up - and so were the prices - and this was much more visible than the realisation that the value of our money was going down … It all seemed just madness, and it made the people mad."

### Politicians' and Bankers' Failure

- In other words, causes of mark's depreciation (which certainly escaped Germany's politicians and bankers as well) had **little enough to do** with how people, individually or collectively, reacted to it
- Most clung to mark, currency they knew and believed in, long after eleventh hour come round for umpteenth time
- Most had no choice; all **encouraged or bemused by Reichsbank's creed** of **Mark gleich Mark** (paper or gold, mark is mark is mark)
- If prices went up, people demanded not a stable purchasing power for marks they had, but **more marks to buy what they needed**
- More marks printed, and more, and more
- **Inflation, already in fourth year** when revolution overthrew old regime, added new, overwhelming uncertainty to many uncertainties attending birth of Weimar Republic

### The German Revolution's Economic Origins

- Although German revolution originated as **military mutiny** against bungling of Army's leaders, bent on getting rid of officer caste who brought military disaster upon country, it had **distinguishable economic origins** as well
- Support for **Soldiers' Councils** coming into being in every unit as war drew to end rested heavily on **personal financial calamities** so many soldiers and families already experiencing
- Frustrations eloquently aggravated by arrival at front in spring 1918 of **group of seasoned anti-war agitators** — leaders of factory strikes which ravaged country after Treaty of Brest-Litovsk with Communist Russia
- Ruthlessly annexationist terms of that treaty but another of **crass political mistakes** including unrestricted submarine warfare bringing US into battle, return of Lenin to Petrograd — made by **Great German General Staff** of whom Kaiser liked to regard himself war lord
- Through late summer 1918: defeatism and disaffection spread
- When defeat itself came, Army torn in two, **essentially between professional soldiers and conscripts**

### Supreme Command's Self-Exculpation

- Supreme Command lost no time **exculpating itself** in respect of losing war
- As Kaiser fled to Holland (at least week too late to save monarchy in any form), Ludendorff made off to Sweden
- **Odium of signing Armistice** placed firmly on head of civilian authority
- Month later, December 1918: **President Ebert** at Brandenburger Tor welcoming legions home with words:

> "I salute you, who return unvanquished from the field of battle."

### The Dolchstoss Myth

- Myth of **Dolchstoss** (stab in back of Army by craven politicians and treacherous intellectuals behind lines) thereafter cultivated to point when **democratic political evolution poisoned at heart**
- This was **heavy burden for new civilian government** to bear, thrown unprepared and with untried constitution into deep end of democracy
- Finding itself accepting responsibility for devastating defeat, weak in human and material resources, **miserably equipped** to set to rights financial and fiscal legacy of purely and arrogantly militarist establishment which had run war practically to exclusion of politicians and economists

### Right-Wing and Left-Wing Discontent

- Now new Republic saddled with **hatred of Officer Corps** as well
- Permanently generating **Right-wing discontent and disruption** during period when **Left-wing agitation** in wake of Russian revolution already as much as government could cope with
- German revolution, as that in Austria, was **comparatively tame affair**
- True, as Armistice commission completed task, Berlin in revolt, loyal troops going over to revolutionaries
- True too, all twenty-two of Germany's lesser royalty deposed even before Kaiser's formal abdication
- **Ludwig III of Bavaria** hustling from palace of Wittelsbachs out into fog and exile, four daughters at side, box of cigars under arm — **Soviet republic already declared** in his patrimony
- But revolution had **no other goals beyond expulsion of old order**
- Neither barricade to man nor gun-fire to march towards

### Officer Corps Turmoil

- Immediate turmoil therefore among **nobility and Officer Corps itself**
- Acutely aware of **loss of status** as result of war lord's departure
- Officers, who had once been race apart, still outside jurisdiction of civil courts, to remember revolution primarily as **popular outrage** in which nation's warriors were **repudiated and insulted** by those they had protected
- Perceived country close to chaos, social institutions for which they fought crumbling away, disorganisation, frustration, hunger and want everywhere
- Worse, **Bolsheviks infiltrating and subverting**, seemed to be taking over
- Clashes between Leftist forces and Army units at Aachen, Cologne, Essen and many other places
- In Braunschweig: **Soldiers' and Workers' Council**, greeting squadron of hussars returning from front, **ridden down** for its pains

### Critical Hours Before Armistice: The Ebert-Gröner Bargain

- Critical point in Army's fortunes came **few hours before Armistice signed**
- **Spartakists** (German Bolsheviks who were to become German Communist Party) already massing in streets of Berlin
- Civilian power (in person of President Ebert), already fearing democratic hours were numbered, struck **bargain** with **German High Command** (in person of **General Gröner**) to co-operate in:
  - Suppression of Bolshevism
  - Restore order
  - Maintain military discipline
- **Saved the Army**: Republican government (technically revolutionary regime) instructed Soldiers' Councils to support officers without reserve
- Within three months: **Weimar Assembly meeting under military protection**

### Army's Swift Return to Power

- For body of society who by strategic ambitions and failures brought Germany so low, speed with which Army **effectively achieved restitution of privileged position of power** nothing short of remarkable
- Although volunteer Free Corps used both to protect Weimar meeting and for suppression of Spartakist risings in March, **by May 1919 Army proper entirely reorganised**, with 400,000 men trained in arms

### Scapegoating and the Myth of Military Invincibility

- However, Germany's failure not been only in battle
- Nation which learnt before all others to **make virtue of war**, to **exalt warriors above all other professions**, was bound to seek scapegoats when end came
- **Myth that German Army undefeated in field**: believed not only because Germany wanted to believe it but because, other factors being equal, **military defeat not credible**
- If what Hindenburg coolly termed '**lamentable outcome of war**' not fault of Supreme Command, then had logically to be fault of someone or something else
- Yet when war over and recriminations began, **genuinely did not seem to occur** to Supreme Command (who kept civilian government largely in dark about true war prospects throughout summer 1918) that breakdown of military machine — that **complex synthesis of munitions, men and morale** — stemmed **as much from economic mismanagement as anything else**

<!-- pp. 21-40 -->

## Germany's War Financing: The Helfferich System

### The Origins of Inflation (1914-1918)

- Germany expected a short, victorious war in 1914, and planned finances accordingly
- **Karl Helfferich** (State Secretary for Finance, 1915-1917) presided over the first stage of inflation
- Before 1914, **Bank Law of 1875** required one-third of note issue backed by gold, remainder by discounted bills
- August 1914: gold redemption suspended, protecting reserves while enabling monetary expansion

### Loan Banks and the Printing Press

- War financed through **loan banks** (Darlehenskassen) whose funds came from printing money
- Loan banks issued credits to business, federal states, municipalities, and war corporations
- Advanced money for war bond subscriptions
- Loan bank notes (1-50 marks) declared legal tender, went into immediate circulation
- **Critical mistake**: Reichsbank permitted to include three-month Treasury bills in note-coverage, allowing unlimited amounts to be rediscounted against banknotes

### Borrowing Over Taxation

- Government financed war "wilfully and simply" by borrowing, not taxation
- Taxation played "not the smallest part" in meeting war costs before 1916
- Allied blockade threw Germany back on her own resources, making resource depletion inevitable

### The Scale of Wartime Inflation

- Total war expenditure: **164,000 million marks**
- Due to currency depreciation, equivalent to only ~110,000 million pre-war marks (£5,500 million)
- **"Mark gleich Mark"** already a fiction during the war
- War loans provided three-fifths of financing
- Credit banks willingly accepted Treasury bills (nearly 9,000 million marks' worth still outside Reichsbank at war's end)

### Minimal Tax Effort

- **Dr. Hjalmar Schacht** later criticized Helfferich's approach
- Helfferich announced in Reichstag (March 1915): war to be financed exclusively by borrowing
- Tax revenues raised: less than 8,000 million marks/year even in 1917
- This covered neither extra expenditure from inflation nor interest on war debt
- War expenditures exceeded revenues; money in circulation increased **5x by 1917** vs. 1913
- War profiteering began to flourish as supplies grew scarcer and money more plentiful
- War profits tax dismissed as "political sop" and "ineffectual" rather than serious fiscal policy

> "Germany tried to meet the colossal costs of the war by an appeal to the self-sacrificing spirit of the people. 'I gave gold for iron' was the slogan for the surrender of ornaments and jewellery. 'Invest in War Loan' ran the appeal to the patriotic sense of duty of all classes." — **Dr. Hjalmar Schacht**

### Germany vs. Britain: Contrasting Approaches

- **Britain** taxed industries and groups to whom war spelled prosperity
- **Germany** relied on War Loans, which lost value after the war
- Schacht: Britain's taxation policy "socially more equitable" than Germany's War Loans

### Financial Opacity During Wartime

- All German stock exchanges closed for duration of war
- Effect of Reichsbank policies on stocks/shares unknown
- Foreign exchange rates unpublished; only those in neutral markets (Amsterdam, Zurich) knew reality
- Impossible to distinguish domestic price rises from war shortages vs. inflation
- Black market rates much higher than official prices
- Only after war, with censorship lifted but Allied blockade continuing, did economic disaster become clear to all

## Social Consequences of Wartime Inflation

### Disruption of Pay Differentials

- *Vossische Zeitung* (August 1921): soldiers in trenches had double the deserters/embusqués at home
- Deserters motivated by economic reasons: price rises caused poverty for enlisted men
- Soldiers didn't share in wage increases, trading profits, or war industries

> "Our military defeat was due to the fact that for every 1,000 men we had in the trenches, double that number of deserters and embusqués remained at home... The first to suffer had to be those who did not share in the general increase in paper revenue, the soldiers who did not participate in the increase in wages, trading profits and war industries." — *Vossische Zeitung*

### Inflation Eroding Morale

- Soldier in *All Quiet on the Western Front*: "There must be some people to whom the war is useful"
- "The factory owners in Germany have grown wealthy: dysentry dissolves our bowels"

### The Currency Explanation

- *Vossische Zeitung* correctly identified cause of depreciation: not commercial balance or military situation abroad, but "exploitation of our currency for the purpose of obtaining money from the Treasury"
- In issuing levies, War Loans, Treasury bills without withdrawing corresponding amounts in taxes, government "created new paper income and wealth incessantly, while the real national wealth was steadily being diminished by the war"

## The Armistice and Its Economic Impact

### Immediate Collapse

- War damaged German economy; Armistice and peace terms "shook it to the foundations"
- **Compiègne Armistice** (November 11, 1918): surrender of fleet, withdrawal from Alsace-Lorraine, immediate evacuation of Belgium and France
- Continuation of Allied blockade specified in peace terms
- German standard of living estimated to have fallen to **half** pre-war levels
- First street demonstration in Munich (November 7): sparked by **6 pfennig increase in beer price** — "not only conscripted soldiers had lost patience"

### Political Chaos

- **Ludendorff's** October 1918 announcement: armistice needed on virtually any terms
- Military dictatorship subsided; coalition of **Majority Socialists (SPD), Progressives and Centre** found itself genuinely in charge
- New government under attack from all sides, responsible for "picking up the pieces"
- Not especially revolutionary itself, but "government of the revolution"
- Republic proclamation partly a holding operation against Bolshevik tide

### January 1919 Elections

- Over 30 million voters (80%+ of eligible) produced coalition to face peace terms presented by Allies in June
- New **Democratic Party** main author of **Weimar constitution** (completed August)
- **Sir John Wheeler-Bennett**: German people in 1919 "deprived of their physical and moral capacity for further resistance"

> "They lacked the power to translate their hatred into active opposition. Instead they cherished it within their bosoms, warming themselves with its rancorous fire."

## Treaty of Versailles: The Economic Straitjacket

### Germany's Illusions Shattered

- Germany hoped peace based on **Wilson's Fourteen Points** and national self-determination
- French determination, founded on fear and desire for vengeance, ensured prevention of German resurgence

### Territorial Losses

- Treaty separated Germany from one-seventh of pre-war territory and one-tenth of population
- Alsace-Lorraine returned to France
- France to occupy Rhineland and exploit Saar coal for 15 years
- Plebiscite to determine Upper Silesia's future

### The Labor and Reparations Problem

- Over a quarter million demobilized soldiers to be thrown on labor market
- Work had to be found "at any cost"
- Clauses making Germany responsible for war demanded "colossal reparations - in money and in kind"
- War guilt had not previously impinged upon German consciousness
- Ministry fell when peace terms published (May 1919); new one bowed to Allies' ultimatum
- First Weimar Parliament struggled on for another year, "as though a landslide had crashed across the road to economic revival"

### Currency Collapse Accelerates

- Before war: mark stood at 20 to pound sterling
- End of war (December 1918): stood at 43
- Before Treaty acceptance (June 1919): pound bought **60 marks**
- December 1919: pound bought **185 marks**
- Average annual wartime depreciation (~20%) came to resemble stability

## Chapter 2: Joyless Streets (Austria Post-War)

### Austria's Dismemberment

- Treaty of Versailles weakened Germany but "left her no less a whole nation"
- **Treaties of St Germain and Trianon** dismantled Hapsburg Empire entirely
- Austria and Hungary reduced to fractions of former size
- Lost enormous areas of territory and millions of nationals:
  - **German Austria** mainly to new Czechoslovakia
  - **Hungary** mainly to Rumania
- **Vienna**: once imperial capital, now "vast city without adequate hinterland" forbidden from *Anschluss* with Germany
- Revolution deposed **Emperor Karl**; Republican government came to power
- Budapest: **Bela Kun's** Bolshevik revolution succeeded by counter-revolution, then **regency of Horthy** (beginning 1920)

### Vienna's Plight

- Austrians, particularly Viennese, in pathetic condition after war
- Hungary's peasants willing to share produce, but not townspeople — Hungary could have been self-sufficient
- Remnant Austria: cold and hunger set in during first post-war winter
- Returning soldiers "defeated, angry and exhausted" — more susceptible to inflammatory talk than in Germany
- Vienna and neighborhood existed "upon what Germany had to spare, which was not much"
- Austrian krone depreciation advanced "far ahead of that of the mark, and with even less chance of recovery"

### Political Dysfunction

- **G.M. Young** (British Treasury, 18 months in Vienna 1920-21) reported to **Lord Curzon**:

> "Out of the capital and dynastic patrimony of a great empire, the Treaty of St Germain created a Republic. Nominally at least, it made this oddly mixed community of bankers and peasants responsible for the cost of a great war."

- Austrian constitution: "super-democracy, contrived to ensure that as little authority as possible is exercised by anyone"
- President: "purely ceremonial figure; he opens flower shows and legitimates bastards"
- Cannot appoint ministers, cannot dissolve the House
- Chamber supreme but actual business done "by standing committee, or preferably in the clubs and party meetings"
- Young: political parties "combining worst parts of an Approved Society with worst parts of the British Medical Association"
- Mental processes "recall to my mind those of a certified midwife"
- Austria "quite unripe for the advanced parliamentary system which the revolution gave her"

### Price Collapse and Black Markets

- Pre-war (1914): Austrian krone nearly at par with mark
- War's end: inflation pushed them apart
- Official prices seldom reflected true black market costs
- Vienna food shortage acute; black market "for many the only sufficient source"
- 1914 Vienna: kilogram best wheat flour cost **44 heller** (equivalent ~6d sterling)
- December 1918: wheat flour unobtainable; indefinable flour mixture from illicit dealer **22 kronen/kilo** — exactly **fifty times** as much
- By May 1922: pound sterling worth 1,200 marks, would have bought **35,000 kronen**

### Cultural Evidence: *The Joyless Street*

- Early **Greta Garbo** film (1925) made in Vienna by **Pabst**
- Symbol of purity in milieu of want, greed, and corruption
- Odious butcher insulting/taunting queues at his shop
- Refusing meat to women he found unattractive or unwilling
- Unlicensed, gluttonous revelry of nightlife speculators and profiteers
- Ultimate attack by starving, angry crowd on café full of merrymakers
- "Faithful reflection of the times"

### Anna Eisenmenger's Diary

- Detailed contemporary account of inflation's scourge in post-war Vienna
- Middle-class widow with war-blinded son, tubercular daughter, son-in-law with amputated legs, hungry grandson, Communist son
- Progressively turned to illegal practices to keep family going
- Resorted to **Schleichhändler** (smugglers) for basic foods state could no longer supply despite ration cards
- **"Hamstering"** (hoarding) became "no more than commonsense" though indictable offense
- Aware of family's lowering standard of living and social status
- Pre-war investments in "gilt-edged securities" still provided income: ~5,000 kronen/year = ~£200

> "I must make myself believe [she wrote] that I am really far better off than hundreds of thousands of other women. I am at least immune from material cares and can help my children since I have a small fortune, safely invested in gilt-edged securities. Thank God for that!"

### Currency Worthlessness Begins

- October 1918: resolved to cash 20,000 kronen for immediate use
- Bank manager advised converting to Swiss francs
- Private dealings in foreign currencies illegal; she decided breaking hoarding laws was enough
- Husband's cigars substantial quantity, could be traded for meat/food — important means of survival
- Country deprived of Czech coal and Hungarian food
- Within month of war's end, Austrian currency began losing exchange value "at far greater rate than before"
- December 1918: businesses forced to employ demobilized soldiers whether needed or not
- Bankruptcies common
- Son received 35,000 kronen in "caution money" which he decided to keep until krone increased again
- Converted it into War Loan instead
- December: as inflationary measure, all paper money had to be overprinted **'Deutschösterreich'**
- Frau Eisenmenger took remaining 20,000 kronen to bank to be stamped — recorded first evidence she heard that ruin lay ahead

### The Bank Official's Warning

- Banking hall full of animated discussions about stamping, new notes, purchasing foreign money
- Bank official she consulted:

> "Well, wasn't I right? If you had bought Swiss francs when I advised you, you would not now have lost three-fourths of your fortune."

> "Surely there can't be anything safer than government securities: Surely there can't be anything safer than that? 'My dear lady, where is the State which guaranteed these securities to you? It is dead.'"

### Food Crisis and Barter Economy

- Son's War Loan "already become unsaleable"
- Frau Eisenmenger induced to exchange government securities for industrial shares
- Grandson developed scurvy
- Two days after Christmas: first food train arrived from Switzerland
- New food prices (strictly rationed) **four times** previous official prices
- Other food hardly available for money; obtained principally by barter
- "Panic bids defiance to all legal decrees" (diary entry, January 1, 1919)

> "Even the most respectable of Austrian citizens now breaks the law, unless he is prepared to starve for the sake of obeying it... it is impossible to get domestic servants or indeed any sort of workers..."

### Class Warfare Emerging

- "Heightened class-consciousness is daily being instilled into the manual workers by the Socialist government"
- Leads to "enormously exaggerated estimate of the value of manual labour"
- Manual workers' wages now "far higher than the salaries of intellectual workers"
- "Even our otherwise honest old house-porter is demanding such extravagant sums for performing little jobs that I prefer to do the heavier and more unpleasant household work myself"

### Currency as Barter Chips

- Frau Eisenmenger's 1,000-kronen notes "lying by the side of the pack of unredeemed food cards in the writing table drawer"
- "Will they not perhaps share the fate of the food cards if the State fails to keep the promise made on the inscription on every note?"
- State still accepts its own money "for the scanty provisions it offers us"
- Private tradesman "already refuses to sell his precious wares for money and demands something of real value in exchange"
- Doctor's wife exchanged "beautiful piano for a sack of wheat flour"
- Frau Eisenmenger exchanged "husband's gold watch for four sacks of potatoes"
- Farmer hid potatoes under straw with apples on top; potatoes reached her safely
- Had to give porter half a sack as "hush-money"
- Farmer eyed grand piano where blinded son Erni was seated improvising: "My wife has been wanting one of those things for a long time. If you'll give it to me, you shall have all you want for three months."

### Pattern Repeated in Germany

- Austria's misery "more immediately and directly the result of war"
- Pattern "to be repeated almost exactly in Germany"
- Both countries: rapid inflation caused homegrown produce withheld from urban markets, "with hunger and anger the inevitable result"
- All Austrians, especially savers, "watched horrified as the value of their money fell"
- Frau Eisenmenger noted early 1919: "The State has been obliged to put 10,000 kronen notes into circulation - each equivalent to two years' income from my capital"
- Suit costs ~6x what it was in 1913
- Food a hundred or two hundred times as much
- "Paper clothes are being sold. Never had I dreamed it possible that one could purchase so little for 10,000 kronen"
- "Jealousy and envy flourish in this atmosphere"

### Spring 1919: No Relief

- Spring brought no alleviation for those without political leverage
- Austrian peasants and profiteers took advantage
- Furniture, fittings, pianos, carpets bought up wholesale by "gold-currency people" (occupying Italians, British, Americans)
- "Last valuables of countless houses flowed on to the market, no one warning their owners not to part with goods whose intrinsic value remained unimpaired"
- Viennese with bundle of kronen "thinks he has grown richer, without taking into account the enormous rise in prices resulting from the Zurich quotations"
- Germans looked to New York and London rates; "Vienna's eyes were on the Swiss franc"

### November 1919: Beyond Understanding

- Year after Armistice: Frau Eisenmenger's position "alarmingly worse"
- "Financial situation beyond her understanding"
- Krone at 25 Swiss centimes the previous Christmas, now quoted at **one-twelfth of a centime**
- Shares going up
- "Gambling on the stock exchange has become the fashion - the only way to avoid losing all one's money and perhaps to add to it"
- New bankers giving people advice; "flight from the krone governing all transactions"
- "Meanwhile," unemployment numbers "fermented by the Communists, are seething with discontent"
- Mob attempted to set Parliament building on fire
- Mounted policemen torn from horses, which were slaughtered in Ringstrasse
- Warm bleeding flesh dragged away by crowd
- Rioters clamoured for bread and work
- "Side by side with unprecedented want among the bulk of the population, there is a striking display of luxury among those who are benefitting from the inflation"
- "New nightclubs are being opened"
- "Greatly intensifying the class hatred of the proletariate against the bourgeoisie"

### December 1919: Industrial Shares Rising

- December 15, 1919: downward movement of krone in Zurich continued
- "Value of my industrial investments is rising to an extent which seems to be incomprehensible and almost makes me uneasy"
- Daughter could make **two dollars a day** at American Mission
- Could be exchanged for **400 krone**, only **100 krone less** than monthly pension of retired privy councillor
- "Former civil servants and officers are undoubtedly the poorest of the poor in Austria today"
- "Too proud to press their claims, can get no employment"
- "Elderly, retired officials of high rank collapse on the streets of Vienna from hunger"

### American Mission and Stock Speculation

- Frau Eisenmenger let room to gentleman from American Mission - just as Garbo's father in *The Joyless Street* could do
- Received **ten times** that in accordance with wartime rent restriction Act
- She herself paid for whole flat
- On now slender quantity of negotiable cigars, daughter's earnings, that rent, diminishing real income from shares, "tackled the first months of 1920"
- "Speculation on the stock exchange has spread to all ranks of the population and shares rise like air balloons to limitless heights"
- Banker congratulates her on every new rise
- "But he does not dispel the secret uneasiness which my growing wealth arouses in me ... it already amounts to millions"

### Foreshadowing Germany's Fate

- "What was happening to Austria then was simply a foretaste of what was to come to Germany"
- "Plight of Frau Eisenmenger and her family would be repeated a thousandfold in every town in both countries"
- "Torture of Germany's middle classes, however, was more lingering, and more intense"

<!-- pp. 41-60 -->

## Industrial Recovery and Living Standards (1920)

### Class Disparities in Post-War Germany
- German living standards fell steeply during war, while France/Britain's actually rose slightly
- Even small rises in German standards vs. large falls in British standards would create discontent in Britain while leaving Germans "feeling better off"
- **British consul in Leipzig** reported wages/cost of living reached equilibrium, purchasing power nearly equal to pre-war levels
- Middle class (fixed incomes, pensions, government officials) hardest hit - 10,000 marks/year now inadequate for bare necessities
- Saxon industry in "very satisfactory condition" despite eight-hour workday

### The Paradox of German Industry (1920)
- **Apparent industrial health confused the inflation issue**
- Currency depreciation made German industry highly competitive in foreign markets through subsidized vital ways
- Industrial lot materially improved over previous twelve months
- Industrialists publicly pessimistic to foreigners about reverting to ten-hour day
- Most workers had realized work (not political dogma) was the answer to difficulties
- **Von Thyssen** believed miners working well with British/French colleague support

## Political Polarization and Reparations (June 1920)

### June 1920 Elections
- **Two storm-cones for the future**:
  1. June elections returned central coalition under **Herr Fehrenbach** (Chancellor) and **Dr Wirth** (Finance Ministry)
  2. Political polarization demonstrated: DNVP (far Right) trebled its vote, Independent Socialists (far Left) doubled
- Moderate coalition (Democrats and Majority Socialists) lost much voter confidence

### Spa Conference (July 1920)
- First post-Versailles meeting on reparations and peace treaty matters
- Reparations questions postponed until Geneva meeting
- Geneva conference also failed, remitted to Brussels meeting (December)
- **Uncertainties caused wild mark fluctuations during 1920**

### Money Supply Explosion
- At war outbreak: 2,700 million marks in circulation (less than half the coinage value)
- November 1918: 27,000 million marks
- November 1920: 77,000 million marks
- **Pound sterling**: 240 marks (November 1920)
- **Dollar**: 60 marks
- During 1920 mark swung 230-152 to pound and back
- Low point reached when actual reparations amount appeared reasonably settled
- As mark improved, unemployment rapidly rose to 6% (summer 1920) - full employment became primary objective at mark's expense

## Lord D'Abernon's Observations (June 1920)

### Britain's Most Versed Money Observer
- **Lord D'Abernon** arrived June 1920 as British Ambassador to Berlin
- "More practically versed in money matters than most in any office in that city"
- Recorded mark's course "over the brink and far down into the depths" in diaries and dispatches
- Enjoyed full confidence of German ministers wrestling with inflation/reparations twin problems
- Unable to influence German monetary policy to any important effect
- Watched helplessly as "chickens of unlimited deficit financing swarmed in to roost"

### The Impossible Budget Math
- German budget barely balanced, leaving nothing for war indemnities
- Raising enough for June reparations would require **twice the revenue** from latest tax proposals
- "Altogether impossible to conceive that twice the new rate of taxation could be imposed without producing a revolution" - D'Abernon

### Germany's Debt Reality (October 1920)
- National debt: 287,800 million marks
- At old 1914 parities: £14,400 million
- At new 1920 exchange rate: only £1,200 million
- **Germany's national debt had been wiped out** a year before the great inflation began

## German Elite Pessimism

### Imperial Foreign Office Attitude
- D'Abernon found their attitude "one of unmitigated gloom"
- All banker friends sending money out of Germany - no restrictions could prevent
- Non-payment of taxes now "no longer a crime but a patriotic duty"
- **President Loebe** (Liberal-minded, Reichstag) especially pessimistic about nourishment conditions inviting Left action

### President Loebe's Testimony
> "I know from the case of my own children how badly people are fed. You cannot get milk, and an egg costs 2¾ marks. The financial condition of the middle classes, the small employers and so on is even worse than that of the working class, to which I belong. Only today we had a memo from the lower officials in South Germany saying that if their pay was not increased they would wreck the till. Working-class wages have roughly been increased eight to ten times compared with pre-war; smaller salaries have only been increased two to four times. This makes an impossible situation when the cost of living has gone up tenfold."

## Reparations Conference Cascade (1920-1921)

### Brussels Conference (End of 1920)
- Met to consider Germany's capacity for reparations payment
- Led only to **Paris conference** (January 1921)
- France (herself near insolvency) made demands D'Abernon described as "amazing"
- French figures nowhere near what they demanded
- Provoked shock in Germany
- Led to February London conference for Germany's counter-proposals
- Discussions lasted until mid-March

### Allied Occupation of Rhine Ports (March 1921)
- France lost patience with Germans during discussions
- **March 30**: Rhine ports of **Duisburg, Ruhrort, Düsseldorf** occupied by Allies under peace treaty sanctions
- Talks began in London again

### German Population's Ignorance
- British High Commissioner in Coblenz reported (days before occupation):

> "A large majority of the German people did not realise all that the Treaty of Versailles entailed. Probably by a large number of the lower classes it was not even read, and the result is that at the present time it has dawned on the population of Germany for the first time that the day of reckoning has arrived."

### Rise of Junkerism
- Military sanctions produced reaction at other end of social scale
- D'Abernon: "a decided reversion to Junkerism"
- Officers' clubs had quasi-penal lists of officers associating with ex-enemies
- Military sanctions "has not produced a normal or healthy reaction - it has turned the Germans sour"

## French Intransigence

### Lloyd George's Assessment
- **France's attitude** under **M. Briand** premiership "acidly but accurately summed up"
- D'Abernon found Lloyd George in Cabinet Room "just before the reparation conference one morning, as usual, a roaring fire behind his back and an open window in front of him"
- Prime Minister on France: "can never make up their mind whether they want payment or whether they want the enjoyment of trampling on Germany, occupying the Ruhr, or taking some other military action. It is quite clear they cannot have both."

## The London Ultimatum (April 27, 1921)

### Reparations Commission Fixed Total Liability
- **132,000 million gold marks** (£6,600 million) total liability
- Payment terms: 2,000 million gold marks (£100 million) annually **plus 26% of exports**
- Threat of further sanctions: occupation of Ruhr by French if compliance not within the week
- **"London Ultimatum"** drove mark to 268 to the pound
- Caused **Fehrenbach government to fall**

### Dr Wirth Accepts the Terms
- **Dr Wirth** became new Chancellor
- Accepted terms knowing heavy additional taxation required
- Mark advanced to 232 to pound as financial uncertainty briefly retreated
- Credit abroad improved
- Optimism from **Upper Silesia plebiscite** - majority favored adhering to Germany

### Relief from Communist Threat
- Communist-inspired armed rising by **Mansfeld miners** collapsed ignominiously
- Even caused Lenin in Moscow to despair of new German revolution
- General relief a Communist threat had passed

## Chapter 4: Delirium of Milliards

### Rathenau's Diagnosis
- **"Delirium of milliards"** - Rathenau's phrase
- "The majority of statesmen and financiers think in terms of paper"

> "They sit in their offices and look at papers which are lying in front of them, and on those papers are written figures which again represent papers … They write down noughts, and nine noughts mean a milliard. A milliard comes easily and trippingly to the tongue, but no one can imagine a milliard."

> "What is a milliard? Does a wood contain a milliard leaves? Are there a milliard blades of grass in a meadow? Who knows? If the Tiergarten were to be cleared and wheat sown upon its surface, how many stalks would grow? Two milliards!"

### The Affliction of Finance Controllers
- Rathenau diagnosed delirium not of people in general but of **those controlling the country's finances**
- Note circulation raised from 75 milliard to 80 milliard marks
- Mark slid from 261 to pound (June) to 310 (mid-August)
- Blame laid squarely by **Rathenau (as by Wirth)** on reparation payments
- 1,000 million gold marks due end of August
- Less than 60% raised on realistic terms in foreign credits
- "Next November, or next spring, whenever a large payment comes, exchange will fall again to a still lower level. This cannot go on." - Rathenau

## The Breaking Point (August 1921)

### Mannheimer's Signal
- Close confederate of **Herr Hugo Stinnes** (industrialist) said breaking point came when German government repaid loan arranged in England by **Herr Mannheimer** of Mendelssohn's Bank
- **Mannheimer**: "confidential man" of **Dr Rudolf Havenstein** (Reichsbank President since 1908)
- Instructed by chief, went to England (August 1921) and bought foreign currency at any price
- "For Germany had any amount of paper marks but no foreign currency"
- **First signal of absolute breakdown in mark's value**

### Four Reasons for Depreciation Policy
1. Enable heavy industry to compete with foreign countries
2. Satisfy workmen's demands by increasing wages with worthless paper marks
3. Avoid political troubles and disturbances
4. Prove to the world Germany could not fulfil Versailles Treaty

### Austria's Collapse as Warning
- Virtual collapse of Austria cast deep gloom over Paris conference
- **Krone**: 800 eighteen months before, fallen to 3,000 to pound, still falling steeply
- Apparently in advance of mark by factor of ten
- Confidence in headlong flight

### Bavaria's Foreboding (Munich, August 1921)
- Gloomiest forebodings about cost of living
- Farmers' scandalous profiteering in milk and grain
- Reich to increase taxes on sugar and beer
- Farmers' associations warned against overcharging/withholding produce
- Ill-feeling in towns against peasants thoroughly aroused
- Government identified with agrarian interests, blamed when hard-pressed
- **Munich municipality** voted against dearer bread (*tout court*) in vote-catching move
- Since dearer bread already fact of life, action encouraged advance demands for higher wages

## Frontkämpfertag - War Army Day (August 24, 1921)

### The March
- Nakedly political, anti-Republic display in Berlin
- March-past of 2,000 war veterans headed by **39-year-old Prince Eitel Friedrich** (Kaiser's second son)
- Marched under archway: *"In Kriege Unbesiegt"* (unbeaten in war)
- Past royal box in *Paradeschritt* (Prince Eitel Friedrich throwing heels as high as anyone)

### Army Chaplain's Sermon
- Before 20,000 spectators
- Suggested Germany's greatness could only be recovered by military power, through monarchy and Hohenzollerns
- Speeches by three generals: **Ludendorff, Graf Waldersee, von der Goltz**
- **Von der Goltz** (commanded Baltic Free Corps) attacked "Jew Government"
- Caused anti-Semitic incidents in crowd
- Stole limelight with telegrams from Admiral Scheer, Grossadmiral von Tirpitz, Hindenburg, ex-Kaiser
- Caused *"rauschender Jubel"* (roaring cheers) and long cheers for Hohenzollerns
- Arena lined by 2,000-3,000 youths/girls, two-deep, precision drill and military movements "most striking"

### Academic Honors for Ludendorff
- **University of Königsberg** conferred honorary doctorate of medicine same day
- Diploma tribute: "to the hero who with the sharp edge of his unbroken sword defended the German nation, hemmed in by a world of enemies all greedy for booty, till that nation, trustful of lying promises, abandoned its unconquered Army and its strong leader; to the German, whose picture, shining from the darkness of our present hour, gives us faith that the future will bring a Saviour and Avenger for our people …"

### Press and Government Reactions
- **Dr Gessler** (Defence Minister, civilian) publicly described display as "rattling of an empty scabbard" as ridiculous
- *Berlin Morgenpost* with restraint: effusion "ill befitted a body of professors in whose hands lay the education of German youth, and provided a commentary on the reactionary attitude of the *literati* of Germany in general and of East Prussia in particular"

### Academic Class Suffering
- Königsberg apostrophe read oddly to those remembering German High Command sword broken at Compiègne
- Ludendorff already in flight to Sweden, disguised in blue spectacles
- Nation had not abandoned its leader
- Academic class suffered heavily from mark's fall
- Unaccustomed to situation where "scholarly writer does not earn as much with a printed line as the street sweeper earns with two whisks of the broom"
- Liable to blame woes on new order, to advantage of military clique
- Convinced pacifist **Herr von Gerlach** (*Die Welt*) did not hesitate to put them straight:

> "Ludendorff, far from justifying the terms of the diploma, by his obstinacy and by his meddling in politics was responsible not only for the unnecessary prolongation of the war but also for the disastrous terms of the Treaty of Versailles."

### Ludendorff's Responsibility
- Gerlach reminded: Ludendorff telegraphed Berlin over and over (October 1918) saying peace offer had to be made at once as Army could not hold out another 48 hours
- Put **Erzberger** at head of Armistice Commission - "insane choice"
- First heard of Kaiser's abdication in Bois de Compiègne
- Got wire from Hindenburg: "if you can't force these points through, conclude an armistice anyhow"

### Erzberger's Murder (August 26, 1921)
- *Frontkämpfertag* expressed reaction spirit rife in Germany north to south
- Flesh added to skeletal myth of *Dolchstoss*
- Two days later: **Mathias Erzberger** murdered by Nationalist gunmen in Black Forest
- Likely inspired by speeches of DNVP leader **Karl Helfferich** (wartime Finance Minister under whose auspices inflation first got grip)
- Erzberger: civilian, Republican, **Jew**

### International Reaction
- Outside world watched with deep misgivings
- Belgian Socialist deputy in *Le Peuple*:

> "Assassination seems now to have become the rule in Germany, where militarist brutes, after having practised on thousands of Belgians whom they massacred, continue to adopt this means of suppressing those in their way … it is a very grave sign of collective criminal degeneration, which must strike all Germans who have retained feelings of respect for human life."

### Domestic Political Fallout
- Death of Erzberger (fearless Socialist taxation exponent) loosed torrent of abuse against Right
- Berlin: Majority Socialists and Independent Socialists joined forces in demonstration to protest "against enemies of the Republic"
- **Herr Harden** (acute, acid observer) explained to D'Abernon: Right perpetually hunting for old culprits responsible for downfall of empire/old system
- Instead of attacking generals (Ludendorff et al.) - who were really the cause - or old gang of princes/sycophants, they blamed Jews and assassinated Left leaders together with those who didn't take their perverted view
- **Over 300 assassinations among Left leaders** since Armistice, "and no one is punished"
- (Harden himself had fifty telephone calls warning he was next on black list, leaving for America)

### Wirth's Confidence vs. Economic Crisis
- **Chancellor Dr Wirth** expressed confidence public order could be maintained to D'Abernon
- Admitted several newspapers (notably Bavaria) would have to be suppressed
- Working classes "extraordinarily excited"
- Government's worries more for **economic crisis** than political one
- Revenue coming in quite well, better expected with new taxation programme
- Hoped to reconcile Left to indirect taxation by increasing taxation on capital
- Recent fall in exchange forced him to grant new salary/wage increases of about 10 milliards

### Bavaria's Economic-Political Crisis
- Economic crisis behind troubles in Bavaria
- Agitation continued against food price rises
- Development employed by Socialists as weapon against state government
- **British Consul-General in Munich, Mr William Seeds** (day of Erzberger's murder) reported Socialist trade unions holding mass meeting:

> "To protest against the increased cost of living and against the reactionary tyranny of Dr von Kahr's state government. The 'class-conscious workman' will be urged to carry out a gigantic demonstration through the streets undeterred by thoughts of the machine-guns and armoured cars of Herr Poehner, the Chief of Police. This official, with that curt firmness which makes him so obnoxious to the Socialists, has reinforced the government's warning with a terse little proclamation ending with these words: 'If you don't want to be hurt tonight, keep off the streets!'"

- Mass meeting of ~50,000 went off without serious disturbance
- **Poehner** (early convert to National Socialism) kept his men quiet
- Only one demonstrator killed, another wounded in scuffle with police
- Socialists passed resolution: wages fixed according to world rates, "never forgetting the fact that the welfare of the people depends solely on the overthrow of the present capitalistic system"

### German-American Peace Treaty (August 25, 1921)
- Separate peace treaty between Germany and America signed
- Neither mentioned League of Nations nor sought to blame anyone for war
- Did nothing to calm fears or tempers within/without Germany
- New run on mark set off not merely by irresponsible bank behavior, nor government's inevitable failure to raise cash for August reparations bill
- Owing to host of circumstances including Erzberger murder which undermined remaining confidence German economy might recover health

## International Financial Community's Verdict

### Berne Conference (September 1921)
- Bankers from Switzerland, Italy, Germany soberly concluded:
- **Impossible for Germany to continue payments to Entente**
- Sooner or later she would have to declare herself bankrupt
- Followed (they thought) by first France then Italy
- Mark at 310 to pound (mid-August) sped downwards to over 400 (mid-September), still going down

### Joseph Addison's Analysis (September 20, 1921)
- **Mr Joseph Addison** (Councillor, British Embassy Berlin) reported to Foreign Office:

> "The daily creation of fresh paper money which the government requires in order to meet its obligations both at home and abroad (services and goods which it is 'obliged both to render and deliver') inevitably decreases the purchasing value of the mark and leads to fresh demands, which in turn bring about a further decline, and so on *ad infinitum*."

- Even progressive taxation increases could not completely meet situation
- New impositions meant increased cost of living
- Automatically reduced purchasing value of mark, brought about more inflation and budget instability

### Speculation Against the Mark
- "There is enormous speculation"

> "Millions of persons in this country are, I think accurately, reported to be buying foreign currencies in anticipation of fresh tax burdens, and to be hoarding foreign bank notes … I hardly know a single German of either sex who is not speculating in foreign currencies, such as Austrian crowns, Polish marks and even Kerensky roubles. In as much also as a fall in the value of the mark is inevitably accompanied by a rise in the quotation of industrial shares, speculators are supposed to be operating systematically to depreciate the mark with a view to reaping the benefit of higher quotations in the share market."

### Tax Structure and Incentives
- Every incentive for ordinary citizen to take precautions against further tax liabilities
- Four principal taxes (assuming business escaped corporation tax *Korperschaftssteuer* up to 20%):
  1. Once-and-for-all increment tax (*Vermogenszewachsteuer*) on increase in property value 1913-1919
  2. Capital tax (*Notopfer*) on value of possessions after increment tax paid
  3. Unearned income tax (*Kapitalertragsteue*) 10% becoming less important as real value shrank daily
  4. Ordinary income tax (*Einkommensteuer*) affected wider public as money wages rose to keep up with prices

### Income Tax Progression (1921)
- Started at 10% on first 24,000 marks earned
- Rose to 20% on next 60,000 marks
- Steps upward until maximum 60% paid on all income over 395,000 marks/year
- 395,000 marks equivalent in September 1921 to about £1,000 or $4,200 - substantial 1920s salary
- Autumn 1921: minimum income for family of four (two adults, two children) just less than 24,000 marks (about £60/year)
- As mark fell and wages rose, taxation of real income became proportionately greater

### D'Abernon's September 30 Observation
- Compared with year before, feeding and clothing of people (especially children) had markedly improved
- Observed with misgivings: war privations must have given Germans distinct competitive advantage over populations whose nourishment and consumption of luxuries still near pre-war standard
- Fortuitous addition to other substantial German industry benefits

### German Industry's Advantages
- Government subventions cheapening production
- Coal available below cost price in Britain
- Bread sold considerably under open market price
- Railway transport offered at less than working costs
- German budget suffered from immense/continuous gain of German commerce and industry

### Businessmen's Protection Strategies
- Not all traders/industrialists had given up hope for mark
- Few not doing best to protect businesses in advance
- Protection could only be bought at State's expense, making fears self-fulfilling
- Where possible, created credit balances abroad via direct arrangement with customers/commercial friends
- Under-invoiced exported products (e.g., The Hague)
- Over-invoiced imports in return
- Such manoeuvres had extra advantage of avoiding taxation in Germany

### Capital Flight Consequences
- On large scale, this would tend toward mark's inflation
- If continued, eventual outcome: insolvency for Germany as country (though subjects might hold considerable assets outside)
- Process particularly reprehensible not simply because exporter's profit was country's loss
- But because part of loss was in substantial subsidies of workers' food and industry's rail costs
- Which ensured competitive prices of Germany's manufactured exports

### Limited Scope of Under/Over-Invoicing
- In practice probably not wide-spread
- All German exporter had to do (provided no need to bring profits home): pay foreign balances into foreign bank where tax authorities couldn't access
- So long as plenty of foreign currency received and enough returned, net effect on mark likely beneficial
- **Mr F. Thelwall** (British Commercial Secretary, Berlin) found more worrying symptoms mid-October
- As mark approached 500 to pound sterling: German workmen's wages too low, workers not being fairly treated

### Labor Unrest and Government Crisis
- Present labor unrest caused by mark's fall and impending new taxation
- Both sent cost of living up
- German manufacturer/trader making lots of money in Germany and abroad
- State getting ever nearer bankruptcy
- But not due to German exporter accumulating vast fortune in foreign countries
- Rather: wrong financial system of German government regarding own budget and fact government has obligations imposed too heavy to meet

### Tax System Flaws
1. On paper too heavy - places before citizen alternative of being ruined or not paying taxes
- No hesitation which course to choose
2. Involved such large reorganization of executive apparatus would probably be some years before becoming really effective

### Budget Reality (October 1921)
- State of budget somber
- In paper marks: government's ordinary expenditure (including recent 10 milliard wage increase) + estimated Allied payments in reparations/occupation costs = 113 milliard marks
- Revenue from previous budget + new July taxation proposals would amount to less than 90 milliards
- Calculations based on conversion ratio: one gold mark to 13 paper marks
- Already true rate was 22 to one

### The Arithmetic of Insolvency
- Reality: total due by Germany for Allied contributions alone already equalled total real receipts from ordinary and extraordinary budgets
- Would themselves be in balance only if Chancellor Wirth's 15 new tax schemes could be brought effectively into force
- Under prevailing political conditions and current fiscal system: most dubious proposition
- **Capital levy** (demanded by Socialists in July hoping to tap real property values) failed to produce substantial real revenue because of time lapse between assessment and payment
- Effectively: any reparations payments at all would unbalance budget again, with inevitable effect on mark

### British Ambassador's Assessment
- "The prospect is of a somewhat alarming character"
- No real determination to stop printing press
- Little efficiency in tax-collecting system
- Very great timidity in putting an end to doles and subventions
- "If a really able and powerful Finance Minister could be entrusted with the direction of Germany's finance I imagine he would soon put a different aspect on the position"
- Advanced two desiderata:
  1. Any increased direct taxation ought not to synchronise with higher prices
  2. Taxpayer ought not to realise too clearly destination of contributions, particularly when due to foreign creditors

## Wirth Government Crisis (October 1921)

### Upper Silesia Crisis
- Wirth's government undergoing severe fit of nerves, on point of resignation
- Straw that broke it: October 17 announcement of **League of Nations' decision** on Upper Silesia future
- Former imperial province to be partitioned between Germany and Poland
- Indignation universal and acute
- As much from national pride as because loss of another highly important slice of Germany's industrial areas would make economic recovery still less likely
- League's decision one of principal reasons making Germany's own membership impossible for years
- Chancellor obliged to resign
- **October 26**: back in power again
- Leading coalition of Majority Socialists and Democrats
- Accepted (though under protest) Allied Note delivering Geneva news
- Meanwhile mark hit new low of 600 to pound

### Dr Wirth's Advice
- Not short of advice how to carry on
- **October 25**: Bavarian state Finance Minister (professing himself not unopposed to reparation payments so far as possible) warned Berlin Government in speech:
- "There is a limit to taxation if the economic life of the nation is not to be paralysed"
- Drew attention to flood of new revenue legislation pouring in upon tax officials
- (He said) could have produced milliards more if revenue officers had had time to go after profiteers and tax evaders

### Public Anger and Speculation
- Public angry but not yet depressed/pessimistic as politicians
- Berlin shops selling huge quantities of goods to Germans and foreigners
- Share prices moved upwards as dollar improved against mark
- Banks so full of stock exchange orders some were days behind opening letters in stock departments

### D'Abernon's San Francisco Comparison
- "Of course the rise is unhealthy and feverish"

> "We cannot be very far from a panic. As soon as inflation ceases to increase and deflation sets in, there will be the devil to pay. Behrenstrasse here, which corresponds to Lombard Street, reminds me of San Francisco after the Earthquake. Almost every bank is being increased or rebuilt, and one can hardly get along the roadway. Something like the South Sea Bubble."

### The Ship of State's Course
- Very hard for ordinary man with little finance knowledge to determine whether outlook good or bad
- Truth: as Ship of State steamed headlong downstream towards cataract, it was good for some and bad for others
- At any rate, people knew whom to blame if (despite prosperity trappings) nation's survival in danger
- *Berliner Tageblatt* (November 9, 1921):

> "We still import more than we export. And yet we must surrender 26 per cent of the gross value of our exports [in reparation payments]. Foreign countries, frightened by our rivalry, are constructing barbed-wire fences. Obligations are forced on us for decades to come, and nothing is done to stabilise the mark by any international action. When the [London] Ultimatum was accepted the dollar was at 60 marks. Today it is 180 or more."

### Profiteering and Speculation
- Newspaper complained of "quite small capitalist upper class" making huge profits from exchange fluctuations
- While foreigners using discrepancy between home and foreign mark values "to purchase our goods *en masse*"
- Demanded profits on exchange and dollar speculations be taxed intensively:

> "The tax on corporations produces the minimum revenue because all kinds of expenditure are deducted … including the cost of the private motor cars of the owner or directors and so on … The assessment of all our taxes is so behindhand that hundreds of thousands of the wealthy classes have not yet paid their taxes for the year 1920. The whole tax edifice, a house of cards in Babel, is tottering. Social democracy demands an immediate visible sacrifice of the producing classes in the form of taxation of real values. Industry has sought to parry the thrust by its readiness to facilitate the payment of the next gold milliard by a credit action."

## Capital Flight

### Estimates of German Banknotes Abroad
- More and more astounding estimates circulating regarding:
  1. Amount of German banknotes held physically abroad (against what eventuality unclear)
  2. Amount of German capital deposited/invested/retained abroad to escape taxation
- **Arthur Eichhorn** newspaper article commented authoritatively on capital flight
- Observing amount of exported capital unknown even approximately, though certainly extensive since war's end:

> "Evasion of taxation, fear of socialisation, and inflation have combined to drive capital out of countries with a depreciated currency into countries where the currency is sound or at a premium … This has nothing to do with international trade or with normal credit operations, but merely increases the chaos of exchange rates."

### The Scramble for Hard Currency
- Dollars, Swiss francs, guilders: favourite conversion objects
- Others (including Czech crown) coming into favour
- Credits in Dutch names in Swiss banks out of all proportion to trade between Holland and Switzerland
- Assumption: these were "Swiss credits of German speculation camouflaged as Dutch"
- Curious side-effect: market rate for short-term money in Switzerland at less than 3% while long-term was over 10%

### The Inevitable Outcome (Mid-November 1921)
- With capital escaping, budget unbalanceable, no one wanting to hold marks: inevitable happened
- By mid-November 1921: dollar would buy 250 paper marks, pound sterling 1,040
- Mark sailed past another traumatic milepost in downward progress
- Germany needed to find 500 million gold marks before end of February to pay Allies
- Knew she faced sanctions by France if not paid

<!-- pp. 61-80 -->

## Financial Crisis and International Pressure (Late 1921)

### The London Ultimatum and Default Fears

- Germany faced threat of Ruhr occupation if default occurred on reparation payments
- London bankers refused credits unless Germany restored financial order and France became "more reasonable"
- German bankers feared the mark might fall to Austrian levels
- Three urgent measures needed but politically impossible due to industrial lobby power:
  - Balance budget to stop printing presses
  - End industrial subventions (food subsidies, inadequate rail freight rates, insufficient coal tax)
  - Revise customs duties with efficient tax collection

### Industrial Unrest and Price Inflation

- Rising cost of living caused industrial unrest in the Ruhr
- New wage tariffs failed to keep pace with inflation
- Factory owners blamed high prices on Entente financial blockade, particularly Upper Silesia partition
- **British Vice-Consul in Essen** reported inadequate punishment for profiteering despite weekly announcements
- Example: man arrested for selling illicitly obtained white flour was imprisoned but able to sell the flour again upon release
- Wholesale prices often 100% above retail prices
- Prices of existing stock increased within 24 hours

### Sir Basil Blackett's Assessment (November 22, 1921)

**Blackett**, Controller of Finance at British Treasury, presented sobering memorandum contrasting Britain (2 million unemployed) with Germany (virtually full employment)

> "In spite of his robust common sense, the man in the [German] street is beginning to believe what some interested industrialists are telling him, so that he seems almost readily to subscribe to the false doctrine that it is good for trade that a government, by inflationary finance, should habitually spend more than its income; and that it is necessarily bad for a country to receive a large income from abroad 'by way of an indemnity..."

- German industrialists knew their activity was "destroying the export trade of its neighbours" - a "sign of fever and not of prosperity"
- Each class wanted taxation to fall on other classes
- Big industrialists converting paper marks into foreign currencies or real assets (land, machinery) with independent value
- **Incentive to saving was gone** when saving became vital necessity for the State

### Impact on the Middle Classes

- Fall in mark "gradually-wiping out the middle classes"
- 1 million marks in German War Loan, worth £45,000 in British War Loan at purchase, now worth only £1,000 sterling
- Internal purchasing power: £3,000 and rapidly falling
- German pensioner with 10,000 marks pre-war income (comparable to £500 English pension) now had £10 sterling value and less than £30 purchasing power
- Insurance policies worth less than annual premiums paid from hard-earned savings
- Rent restriction Acts forced middle classes "to starvation in order to subsidise the German workman's wages and the employer's profits"
- Bread and rail subsidies enabled foreigners to buy German goods well below world prices and travel/eat/occupy houses at ridiculously cheap rates
- Foreigners buying up real property, factory interests, secondhand furniture, pianos - "A gradual process of buying up and carrying off Germany's movable capital"

### Blackett's Conclusion vs. French Government Belief

- Blackett: Germany's temporary employment advantage due to "misdirected consumption of holders of paper marks" wanting to dispose of them, creating misdirected production interfering with proper export flow and increasing luxury imports
- Government pursuing inflation policy was "sufficiently disproved" due to weakness and inexperience
- **D'Abernon** would have agreed with this assessment
- **French government** believed Germany was bluffing, manipulating exchanges to her advantage, and rapidly increasing prosperity

## Evidence from Occupied Zones

### British Consul-General in Cologne (November 23, 1921)

**Mr Paget Thurstan** observed shops daily thronged, many closing doors for much of the day in self-protection

> "It is no uncommon spectacle to see queues of intending purchasers lined outside the shops waiting for the doors to reopen... wholesale prices being now often considerably above retail prices, the difference in certain articles being nearly 100 per cent. Clearly, as long as such conditions prevail, there can be no limit to the rise in the cost of living as measured in marks, and settlements of wages' disputes are merely ephemeral."

### Addison's Berlin Report (Four Days Later)

- Shops declaring themselves sold out, closing 1-4 hours in afternoon
- Most refusing to sell more than one article per customer
- Prices raised to meet new exchange level
- Japanese eagerly purchasing in camera shops
- **Germans themselves** doing most retail buying, laying in stores fearing further price rises or total stock depletion

### Chancellor Wirth's Concerns

**Addison's interview with Chancellor**: fast-rising prices giving immediate concern for public order

> "The Chancellor is doing his best to keep things quiet, but the impossibility for the working classes to obtain even obvious necessities except at exorbitant prices, coupled with severe winter setting in, might lead to serious trouble."

- About to preside over Cabinet meeting on Berlin municipal employees' wage demands
- Sitting in semi-darkness from partial electrical workers' strike
- Strike settled next day with 400 million marks in extra expenditure

**Addison's assessment of Wirth**: "a man of quiet determination with a leaning towards optimism"

- Accepted middle classes in severe straits, working classes at bearable minimum
- Elements for disturbances and revolutions present in Germany by late November 1921
- Food riots taking place in Berlin
- Mark dropped to just over 1,300 to the pound

## The Vienna Riots (December 2, 1921)

### Parallel Crisis in Austria

- Austria experiencing similar inflation acceleration with even greater food shortages
- Intense resentment against profiteers - the *Schieber*, speculators, and Jews

### The December 2 Riot

- Triggered by severe fall in krone
- 30,000-person unarmed crowd (many hooligans) wrecked and looted food shops, restaurants, cafés
- Attacked hotels in inner quarter
- Only exception: **Bristol Hotel** where **Sir William Goode** (former Reparations Commission Austrian section president) was staying
- Crowd penetrated to second floor, invaded and ransacked his apartment
- Goode "kept the mob for an hour from entering a room where several English and American ladies had taken refuge" before being robbed of all effects

### Demonstrators' Demands

- Seizure of all foreign currency (medium shops insisted upon for purchases)
- State control of securities market
- All gold to State hands, including church and monastery holdings
- Progressive property tax, immediate child insurance system, systematic food subsidy reduction
- **Chancellor gave ground on all matters except food subsidies** - their abandonment would have raised apparent cost of living still more

### British Commercial Attaché Warning

> "I fear these disturbances presage collapse."

- Until stabilisation came, the one financial certainty
- Austrians' capacity for long-suffering proved remarkable
- Four-year concatenation of financial crises relatively tamely received
- Middle class hardest hit, had not taken effective public action
- December riots seemed to relieve most Viennese feelings temporarily
- With krone above 2,000 to pound, Austria settled back into usual lethargy
- Vienna University closed (cold), Stock Exchange on strike (tax), Railway fares raised 300%
- Rich nightlife grew more phrenetic while retired barristers and ex-generals found "stone-breaking beside the Danube"

## Chapter 5: The Slide to Hyperinflation

### Attempts to Address Profiteering

- Social unrest obvious symptom of inflation
- Politicians brought in measures hoping government might be seen dealing with profiteering
- **Bavaria's Prime Minister** submitted Bill to Reichsrat making gluttony a penal offence

### The Anti-Gluttony Bill

Definition of glutton: "one who habitually devotes himself to the pleasures of the table to such a degree that he might arouse discontent in view of the distressful condition of the population"

Penalties:
- First offence: arrest on suspicion, imprisonment and/or fine up to 100,000 marks (£75)
- Second offence: up to 5 years penal servitude, fines up to 200,000 marks, deprivation of civil rights
- Caterers who abetted/connived liable to extra punishment
- Foreigners on conviction liable to expulsion from Reich

- Bill never enacted but indicative of:
  - Great offence by German profiteers and foreigners exploiting exchange rates
  - Desperate lengths respectable politicians already being pushed

### The Mark's Relationship to Reparations

- Fall in mark universally presumed due to reparation obligations Germany couldn't meet
- Temporary alleviation of obligations would send mark briskly in opposite direction
- Third London conference convened December 18, 1921
- Announcement meant Allies appreciated January-February 1922 gold payments were virtually unmeetable
- Sent wave of confidence crashing back through exchanges
- December 1, 1921: mark soared upward, regaining quarter of November value
- Reached 751 to pound (from November average 1,041)
- Paper-mark prices of stocks/shares declined by half or more
- Reichsbank buying foreign currencies heavily

### Speculation and Panic Buying

**Mr Seeds reported from Munich**: smaller banks and financial concerns very hardly hit

> "But in this respect conditions are hopelessly unhealthy, and the public will continue to be swayed by rumours and to speculate either in goods or in stocks and shares."

- All classes speculating in shares "with fine disregard for common-sense"
- Shares bought in totally unknown concerns to exchange valueless paper money for "good security"
- Generally hoping to profit from stock rise
- Respectable shares paying 20% dividend pushed higher till final holders couldn't expect even 1% return
- "The improvement of the mark has brought not satisfaction but the very reverse"

### Purchasing Mania

- Previous mark fall drove population into shops in purchasing mania
- Foreigners abused for buying out Germany with profitable exchange rate
- Germans equally active emptying shops of stock
- Many thought money would soon have no value, must be exchanged for goods while possible
- Others realized purchasing mania would help falling exchange raise prices (speculative buying)
- Press noted disastrous trade slump inevitable when purchasing power exhausted, poorer classes suffering
- Panic-stricken people marking up shop articles to higher prices day by day

### Minister of Commerce on Capital Flight

From **Bavarian Minister of Commerce** discussion with Seeds:

- Money provided out of capital and savings for the buying craze
- **Most serious aspect**: people's confidence in and loyalty to the State gravely undermined
- Those who supported government during war by buying State bonds lost heavily from mark depreciation
- Whole population now evading taxation, devoting money to speculative purchases (carpets or "securities")

### Government Disillusionment

- Community of taxpayers making false returns wherever possible was "bad enough"
- Growing disillusionment with government itself made it worse
- **Berliner Tageblatt** (December 6): "The reins are trailing on the ground"

> "Nobody can say what will become of the whole batch of taxation proposals... [because] the Finance Ministry is 'run' by the Food Minister as a sideshow... More new banknotes were issued during the last week in November than ever before: 4.5 milliards of marks - practically double our entire note circulation before the war. If we do not make up our minds to put our finances in order we shall have compulsory administration forced on us by our creditors."

### Lord D'Abernon on Dr Wirth

**D'Abernon's diary** (November 24, 1921):

> "I am increasingly convinced that Wirth understands very little about figures and regards them mainly as pegs on which to hang rhetoric. Directly one discusses the details of the German budget with him, his attention flags and he seems quite unable to follow even my most lucid developments."

### Dr Wirth's Economic Philosophy

- Perhaps regarded budget balancing as "more academic than practical project" while France called upon Germany "to lay milliards of gold by the sack upon the table"
- **Berliner Tageblatt** (December 16): reported Wirth regarded economic system as "artificially swollen by the fall in the rate of exchange"
- Might lead to "very bitter disillusion in course of few months"
- "Fictitious prosperity" evident in other countries as unemployment (England and America)

> "Dr Wirth declared that it was impossible to restore the world, and especially the European, economic system when all Eastern Europe lay shattered, and when the incapacity of the peoples of Eastern Europe to purchase was spreading to Central European countries. The only cause for hope, he thought, was that the world, and 'English haute finance' in particular, was at last heeding Germany's explanations of why she could not pay what was asked, that the London Ultimatum had rendered Germany uncreditworthy, and that the problem was minutely related to the world economic system."

### The Challenge of Reform

- Press received speech coldly
- Law-respecting country already undergoing plundering by own population needed action rather than excuses
- To put reforms into effect depended on most reactionary official classes whose goodwill dwindled with savings and incomes
- Less and less was done, government losing support of workers who stopped voting
- Politics becoming irrelevant - rising cost of living and how to cope with it became sole concern at Christmas 1921

### Price Increases Since 1913

- Rye bread: up 13 times
- Beef: up 17 times
- Sugar, milk (4.40 marks/litre), pork, potatoes (1.50 marks/lb): up 23-28 times
- Butter: up 33 times
- Official prices often third higher in reality
- All prices roughly half as much again as October, only two months before

### Bankruptcies as Economic Indicator

- Pre-war: normally ~9,500 bankruptcies/year
- 1914: 7,739 (wartime inflation increase)
- 1918: 807
- 1921 (first seven months, fairly stable mark): 2,975 - more than double 1920, three times 1919
- 1921 most indicative: falling mark associated with decline in bankruptcies and vice-versa
- Largest number (845) in spring when mark stood highest
- After November low: only 150 bankruptcies
- **Frankfurter Zeitung**: "It gives some inkling of the awful *débâcle* which may be expected if a rapid and permanent improvement of the mark actually takes place"

## The Cannes Conference (January 1922)

### London Conference Results

- Lloyd George-Briand meeting solved nothing
- Reparations postponed until after New Year
- Further Cannes conference would grant Germany moratorium on January-February instalments
- Must pay 31 million gold marks every ten days thereafter pending readjustment
- Diplomatically dismal: German delegation headed by **Dr Rathenau** (Minister of Reconstruction) snubbed by French for four days
- **M. Briand** seen taking instruction from Lloyd George on golf links, accused of subservience to British policy
- Recalled to Paris by President Miller, replaced by **M. Poincaré** who attained office on simple programme: make Germany pay or "uphold firmly all France's rights under Treaty of Versailles"

### Lloyd George on the Victors' Costs

> "The fees in the Courts of War are all on the highest scale."

- Germany lost action, had to pay full costs
- With Poincaré: justice must be not only preventive but retributive

**Lloyd George on Poincaré** (writing 1932):

> "He had no use for the Cannes conference. He knew how to get money out of Germany - by the lash!... Briand was a Breton. M. Poincaré was a Lorrainer born in a province repeatedly overrun by Teutonic hosts... he himself twice witnessed the occupation of his own cherished home by German troops... He is cold, reserved, rigid, with a mind of unimaginative and ungovernable legalism. He has neither humour nor good humour... He was not concerned about a just, and least of all a magnanimous peace. He wanted to cripple Germany, and render her impotent for future aggression... The fall of M. Briand sent the world rolling towards the catastrophe which culminated in 1931."

- Rolled via mark collapse, Germany disillusion, progressive raising of world tariffs, cessation of trade, depression and slump, "and on to something much worse"
- Lloyd George writing 1932 when ultimate disaster seemed to have struck Europe, largely consequence of France's refusal to allow German recovery

### Germany's Taxation Efforts

- Germany's effort to meet reparations by implementing July 1921 taxation proposals showed no signs of desired effect
- **British Commercial Secretary in Berlin**: what was wanted not further imposts uncollected, confusing fiscal apparatus, but rather readjustment and ruthless application of existing taxes
- Strong pressure needed against wealthy - especially industrialists - to make them disclose foreign holdings

### Industrialists' Counter-Proposal

- When government proposed annexing portion of dividends, industrialists proposed instead:
- Place proportion of foreign holdings and foreign credit at State disposal for reparation instalments
- In return: proportion of future taxation remitted
- Manner of proposal (September 1921) "hardly that of subjects to their sovereign authority, nor of the taxed to the tax-gatherer"
- Industrialists made offer conditional upon State transfer of railways to themselves
- Government rightly refused such bargain

## The Mark's Renewed Decline (Early 1922)

### Post-Cannes Slide

- Mark drifted downward again with prospect of harder French line on reparations
- Reached 850 to pound in last week of January 1922
- One "influential" man compared country to automobile that couldn't stop in five yards
- Everyone recognized disagreeable deflation period coming: unemployment, factory closures
- "But, he added, 'Do not pull us up too short. Give the car time to stop without skidding.'"

### Life in Financial Pother

- Government and commercial world convinced unwise to precipitate action
- Life ground on in pother of financial worries for all classes
- Seeking commercial experience to represent Germany in Washington, **Dr Rathenau** heard complaints:
  - Very few businessmen had diplomatic experience
  - Those who did preferred restoring private fortunes to government service
  - Very few now had considerable private fortunes left
- **Herr Cuno** (to become Rightist government leader following year, might have served Washington) desired to make financial position secure first

### Bavaria's Tourist Season Worries

- Winter apprehensions: tourist season would see food supplies eaten by Germans and foreigners
- Specially drawn by **Oberammergau Passion play**
- Measures taken to assign expensive imported foodstuffs to tourists, leaving home produce for locals
- Berlin extensive strike early February of public employees halting railways, usual services
- Berliners growing accustomed to water consumption three times normal before city's water cut off
- Filled baths and receptacles to meet occasion
- **Moscow** generally blamed for backing workers' agitation with money
- Public opinion turned against Communists

### Scapegoating and Blame

- Natural for people in grip of raging inflation to seek someone to blame
- Picked upon: other classes, races, political parties, nations
- Blamed: tourists' greed, peasants, wage demands, industrialists/profiteers, Jews, speculators in money markets
- "In large measure still blaming not the disease but the symptoms"

### The Exchange Rate Debate

- Union demands still for higher wages to meet rising prices rather than stable prices and stable currency
- Few financially sophisticated blamed government and Finance Minister particularly
- Typical view: prices went up because foreign exchange went up, exchange went up because of Stock Exchange speculation (obviously Jews' fault)
- Dollar price matter of almost universal discussion, most Germans thought dollar going up, not mark falling
- Price of food and clothing forcibly increased daily, not value of money permanently sinking as paper marks diluted purchasing power

### The Reparations Commission's Misunderstanding

- Allied Reparations Commission vision similarly obfuscated
- February-March 1922: exchange fell from 45 to 70 paper marks to gold mark (or 900 to 1,400 to pound)
- Commission demanded Germany raise another 60 milliards in new taxes
- Didn't occur to demand restoration of exchange level
- Even less: saw little chance taxes increased to impossible level could make good such depreciation

### Dr Rathenau's Explanation

**Dr Rathenau** accounted for absence of unemployed by pointing out:
- Million men working to pay reparations
- Million producing goods to buy food abroad
- Another million making up loss of output since eight-hour day introduced

Best effort to explain to Reichstag what was happening to mark by alluding to "vicious circle":
- Adverse trade balance
- Consequent necessity to sell German currency abroad and its resulting depreciation
- Fall in exchange rate and inevitable rise of home prices
- Increased costs of materials and labour
- New rifts in budget

**Rathenau expressly and publicly denied printing press had any role** in permanently spiralling sequence, ascribing country's ills primarily to unfavourable trade balance caused by reparation payments

Totally failed to understand reality: country living far beyond its means, printing money to pay for excesses including:
- Over-employment
- Inordinate industry subsidy
- Import and manufacture of luxuries for domestic consumption
- Grossly inefficient tax-collection system

### The Industrialists' Heresy

- Most successful businessmen stuck to heresy: only by continually falling exchange rate could Germany compete in neutral markets
- "After them, the deluge"
- Neither they, politicians, nor bankers (with few exceptions) perceived direct connection between inflation and depreciation
- Printing presses churning out notes as exchanges continued rapidly to fall
- What impressed ordinary politician: danger of social unrest from currency scarcity
- Couldn't see or intentionally ignored obvious danger from continuous inflation
- Social unrest appeared just the same

## Early 1922: Accelerating Crisis

### First Quarter Deterioration

- First three months of 1922: economic situation notably worse
- Two-month moratorium did no more than postpone January mark fall
- End of February: first "ten-day payment" became due
- Throughout March fall continued
- Only April rally came when European financial community (amazingly unaffected by disappointment frequency) decided Genoa international conference (beginning that month) might bring salvation

### The Treaty of Rapallo

- Meeting brought extra-mural crisis: **Treaty of Rapallo** signed after secret negotiations between Germany and Russia
- Mutually feared being shut out of future European say
- Genoa conference over: prospect of thrice-monthly squeezing of Germany's real resources returned

### Living Standards Decline

- Second half 1921: 50% increase in official food prices
- Single workman's real wages kept pace
- Married workman worse off from greater demands for clothing and warmth (costs rising faster)
- In practice: prices depended on purchaser luck or skill

**Consul-General Seeds** (Munich) who kept careful family expenditure notes:
- Goods like butter only available considerably above nominal cost
- Munich milk: 4.50 marks/litre (December 1921) → 6 marks (March 1922) → 7 marks (April)
- Butter: 42 marks/lb December (9 above posted price) → 50 marks April only
- Eggs: 2.50 apiece → 3.60
- Beer: 3 marks/litre → 5.60
- Sugar, meat, potatoes prices all doubled

### Impact on Children and Families

- For those with incomes failing to keep abreast or close to such increases: "the tempest was blowing"
- Allied blockade still taking toll on young generation, effects amplified by inflation-bred poverty
- Study in Frankfurt-on-the-Main (February 1922): all children of every class two years physically and mentally backward for ages
- Difficult to recover lost years: milk obtainable only for sick during winter, bread price rising
- Anxious mothers searching dustbins of richer neighbourhoods hoping to retrieve food scraps from garbage

### Labour's Shelter and Employer Dilemmas

- Those lucky enough to have monopoly power of organised trade union still in shelter
- Faced employers (German manufacturers plus central/local governments) with theoretically crippling wage demands
- Employers' choice: grant demands or prepare for wholesale strikes and disorders (as recently in Britain)
- Nine weeks after Rapallo Treaty signed, although exchange rate comparatively static ~1,300 to pound, food cost soared upward
- 50% rise during second six months of previous year now became desirable objective
- Hamburg price rises for food alone: April 46%, May 51%, June 56%
- Brief time in May when meat price doubled in a month: cost of living rise so abrupt and startling unions unable to decide what demands to forward

### The Paradox of Industrial Expansion

- In view of rocketing labour costs, manufacturers' eagerness to extend works, renew plant, embark on large improvement schemes "at first sight somewhat extraordinary"
- From social viewpoint: so much commercial building unfortunate in country short over million houses
- Partly result of rent restriction Acts throttling private building sector
- German industrialists unable to build liquid reserves keeping value
- Cash they couldn't hold illegally abroad in foreign currency generally converted (as Blackett remarked) into real or fixed assets
- For reason of mark appreciation: even few weeks of post-Genoa "stability" invited business stagnation
- Industrial circles faced with danger: cash would become more valuable than goods, crash when everyone attempted converting assets back into money

### The Tax Payment Paradox

- Further reason for viewing appreciation with dismay noted by Rhineland High Commission member (end of May):
- Would render tax payment not academic hardship but real one
- Mark received as income in 1921 had actual average value of, say, a penny
- Year later when tax due: worth fifth or sixth of that figure
- Incomes increased meanwhile, if not same proportion, at least very substantially
- **Longer payment postponed, greater gain could be**

> "The big interests believe that as the mark is doomed as a currency beyond hope of recovery, all efforts to support it are costly, useless, and dangerous to their or, as they put it, the country's interests."

### Industrial Debt Advantage

- Better German industrial concerns had particular satisfaction reason
- Might look weak financially but many possessed enormous concealed reserves
- Debenture shares and prior-charge debts contracted on gold mark basis
- Gold-mark equivalents of goods and services had been received
- **Mighty Stinnes group** still working on gold capital
- Fall in paper mark value wrote off 98% of gold debt - companies' gain, shareholders' loss
- New Reichsbank borrowings (commercial enterprises could obtain credit at very low discount rates even at 1923 crisis height) automatically written off similarly
- Rapid depreciation caused real repayment value to be smaller than original loans by whatever factor time and rate of fall dictated

### Hugo Stinnes' Justification

**Hugo Stinnes** - richest, most powerful industrialist with empire of over one-sixth country's industry - largely built on inflationary economy foundation

- Paraded social conscience shamelessly
- Justified inflation as means of guaranteeing full employment, not as something desirable but "simply as the only course open to a benevolent government"
- Maintained: "the only way whereby the life of the people could be sustained"

### The Reichsbank President's Fallacies

**President of Reichsbank** (industrial interests negligible, not essentially denying argument) in speech on German currency May 1922 greatly vexed **Lord D'Abernon**

Had (in ambassador's words) "pressed into shortest space the maximum number of fallacies and errors"

- As though powers to wreck economy not great enough already
- At Reparations Commission behest, expecting money supply divorced from political expedience
- Reichsbank declared autonomous that month with **Dr Havenstein** as uncrowned king
- Quickly showed he too considered fall in exchange quite unconnected with gigantic note issue increases
- Went on "merrily turn[ing] the handle of the printing press completely unconscious of its disastrous effect"
- Evidence: 90 bankers in Germany out of every 100 expressed and perhaps held same views
- Financial press reported them without dissent

### Foreign Observers' Bewilderment

- Ever-climbing wages and high industrialist expenditure plans jaundiced many foreign eyes despite penury hitting so many
- **The Times** (April 18, 1922) printed bitter report from "a man of business" recently in country:

> "The greatest fraudulent conspiracy in the history of the world is now being enacted in Germany with the full concurrence and active support of its 60 or 70 millions of people. And this conspiracy is brazenly enacted under the very noses of the Allies. Germany is teeming with wealth. She is humming like a beehive. The comfort and prosperity of her people absolutely astound me. Poverty is practically non-existent. It is all the other way... And yet this is the country that is determined she will not pay her debts... They are a nation of actors... If it wasn't for the fact that the German is


<!-- pp. 81-100 -->

## Spring 1922: Germany's National Despair

### Social and Moral Deterioration

- Spring 1922 brought visible signs of **national despair** — the Imperial dispensation had at least provided confidence and prosperity
- **Upper and middle classes** realized the superficiality of Prussian culture
- Young people remembered these years "not as a nightmare but as an adventure" — mainly confused and disillusioned
- **Self-confidence of the country ebbed away** along with prosperity, and moral degeneration of nation and institutions set in
- Pessimism and restlessness grew as sense of security, community spirit, and patriotism dwindled
- Neither hatred of French militarism nor desire for revenge sufficient to unite the nation — "the very fabric of that nation was crumbling along with its ethical values"

### Longing for a Strong Leader

- Among some, **rebirth of the German soul** became an obsession — not just militarists of *Frontkämpfertag* and academics of Königsberg
- Many victims of inflation began to long for **a great leader** — not a ruler like the Kaiser or Tirpitz, but one possessed of "attributes and Spartan values of the legendary figures of early Teutonic history"
- **Hitler, with his attraction to Wagner**, fully understood this longing
- His **National Socialist Workers' Party (NSDAP)** already exploiting in Munich
- "When a nation is falling apart, its old values challenged by new conditions, there are always elements who will seize on any means of cohesion"

> 'Inflation finished the process of moral decay which the war had started.' — **Erna von Pustau** to Pearl Buck

### Personal Stories of Loss

- **Erna von Pustau** recalled selling tenanted houses — seemed like good business (twice the cash paid), but furniture prices had quintupled, "the worst was not over"
- Inflation "swallowed bit by bit the savings accounts of Mother and millions of others"
- One house sold because couple had both sons killed, no one to care for them, life savings devalued — "had gassed themselves"
- Inflation made society **cynical** — "the pie was growing smaller and more people wanted pieces," nothing left from "good Neighbour" atmosphere
- **Middle classes squeezed between** big business and organized workers — "are not organised against the wholesalers, while the workers are organised against us"

## 6: Summer of '22

### Rathenau's Assassination (June 28, 1922)

- **Walther Rathenau** murdered — apostle of 'fulfilment,' cosmopolitan statesman transcending nationalism
- Death celebrated by general strike in Berlin as warning to the Right
- **Mark collapsed** from 1,300 to 1,600 to the pound at once, within a week to 2,200, nearly 500 to the dollar
- Political enemies: **Herr Stinnes** (industrialist, "greatest obstacle to currency reform"), **Dr Rathenau** (reparation policy)
- June 28 early morning: Rathenau and Stinnes had come nearest to mutual comprehension at American Ambassador's house after coal deliveries debate
- Rathenau attacked in Reichstag by Rightist leader **Dr Helfferich** (like **Erzberger** before him)
- Hours later: Rathenau's car blocked, assassins riddled him with bullets at close range, bomb thrown in for good measure

### Bavaria's Financial Collapse

- State finances in hopeless condition — revenue officials couldn't handle tax arrears, estimated 1922 deficit had doubled
- June 1922: authorities hadn't yet dealt with **Federal taxes for 1920**
- Bavarian Landtag decision: **double the annual subsidy for encouraging gymnastics** (measure of their grasp on reality)

### External Pressures

- Negotiations through **Morgan Committee** in Paris for international loans failed
- Financial authorities had to ward off sudden movements in money markets
- *Frankfurter Zeitung* (July 7): fear of internal disturbance caused panic — larger industrial companies buying foreign bills heavily to safeguard raw material supplies
- First time since Armistice: **foreign countries refused Germany a loan** obtainable by selling paper marks abroad
- "The mark for the moment is unsaleable"

### Post-Rathenau Currency Collapse

- New development: **rapidity with which prices moved after exchange rate**
- Before post-Rathenau collapse: considerable interval between mark depreciation at home and abroad
- Many industries declaring costs reaching world market levels — couldn't compete abroad (puzzling since German labor remained cheaper)
- Actually a **labor famine** — many German laborers seeking higher wages in Belgium, Holland, even France border areas

### Reichsbank's Inflationary Role

- Spring 1922: growing divergence between **floating debt increase** and **volume of money in circulation**
- Private banks unable to advance loans needed for industry and commerce
- Reichsbank conceived duty to fill gap — from summer onwards, **commercial bills dealt with as generously as Treasury bills**
- Loans to business at far more indulgent rates than private banks could offer
- **Discount rate remained at 6% throughout August** while mark fell 250% against pound in same month
- Within six months: commercial bills approaching three-fifths of Bank's Treasury bill holdings
- Demand for extra credit stimulated by Reichsbank's behavior "scarcely less critical in promoting inflation than its profligate bounty towards the government itself"

### Financial World's Puzzlement

- Complete failure to consider **continuing flood of new banknotes** as reason for mark's behavior
- Latest fall "reckoned disastrous for finances both of Reich and regional governments"
- All efforts to restore federal budget order rendered void
- Further impoverishment of **classes on fixed incomes** (state officials included)
- Newspapers feared further recruits for "radical circles of the Right from these 'social *déclassés*'"

### Lord D'Abernon's Observations

> 'Grave feeling of disquiet here' — **Lord D'Abernon**, Berlin, July 10, 1922

- Mark at 2,430 — "about half the price of a month ago"
- Prices rising, will soon double June 1 level — "wages and salaries must be adjusted. Adjusted to what?"
- Financial position in Germany precisely that in Vienna a year ago (exchange 2,000-2,500)
- "Today exchange in Vienna is about 95,000. Will Berlin a year hence be at this level?"

### The Printers' Strike

- D'Abernon blamed German authorities' **recklessness with note issues** — "requires handcuffs to stay the hand which turns the crank of the printing press"
- **Reparations Commission's presence in Berlin produced panic** — "The moment they appear, the mark bolts"
- September 1921 visit: mark fallen 350 to 650; now plunged 1,800 to 2,400
- German government reminded them: six weeks expenses paid in 20-mark notes requiring seven office-boys with huge waste-paper baskets to carry to railway station
- Commission's insistence on making **Reichsbank independent** (May 1922) turned out "like giving maniacs the control of the asylum"
- "Last week, when by the blessing of Providence, the printers struck and printing of notes was perforce interrupted, Havenstein brought in strike-breakers to get the presses going again"

### The Note-Printing Crisis

- Extraordinary paper money needed in June — **Reichsbank issued 11,300 milliard marks in new notes**
- Strikes meant usual inflow back into bank didn't happen — **none in reserve**
- Six months before: contracts awarded for **special new paper** making quick printing possible with simple imprint that couldn't be imitated
- Paper arrived printing offices unexpectedly July 7
- Should have printed enough 500-mark notes by July 13 (Thursday) for delivery on pay day
- Despite trade unions' readiness, **printers themselves suddenly withdrew consent**
- "Plain that other forces were at work than a mere wage or sympathy strike. Seemed probable that hidden and illicit leaders were trying to seize the State by the throat"
- If no money forthcoming on pay day, government faced danger of popular disturbances
- Also faced danger of Berlin strikers destroying machinery if volunteers taken on

### Wage and Price Spiral (July 1922)

- **British Consul at Frankfurt-on-Main** (late July): instantaneous rise in price of necessities
- Workman's wage naturally raised in proportion
- Skilled workman demanding **100,000 marks a year** (£5,000 pre-war, barely £5 for subsistence by then)
- Manual worker's wage worked out same basis
- Professional man, doctor, teacher, bank clerk "far behind in their capacity as wage earners"
- Trained bank clerk: maximum yearly salary **12,000 marks** (about £5 if changed in London)

### The Cost of Living Crisis

- Four weeks of July: wholesale prices of 98 food varieties rose 9,000 to 14,000 (over 50% monthly rise)
- *Frankfurter Zeitung*: wholesale price of 'goods' up **139 times since before war**; leather and textiles by **219 times**
- American index (world prices): fall in cereal prices, increase in metal — remained steady
- Communist *Rote Fahne*: minimum existence for four-person family increased since 1914 by **86 times** while average wage increased only **34 times**
- Egg that cost 4 pfennigs now cost 7.20 marks (**180-fold increase**)
- First week July alone: four-person-family weekly minimum rose from 2,300 to 2,800 marks
- **Bank clerk's annual salary would keep his family alive for about a month**

### Anti-Semitism Rises

- Austrian situation relentlessly reproduced in Germany
- More educated classes, deprived of right to live decently and raise families, becoming hostile to Republic and receptive to forces of reaction
- **Consul in Frankfurt** reported virulent growth of **anti-Semitism**

> It is no exaggeration to say that cultured German men and women of high social standing openly advocate the political murder of Jews as a legitimate weapon of defence.

- Even in Frankfurt with preponderating Jewish population, movement so strong that "Jews of social standing are being asked to resign their appointments on the boards of companies"

### Erna von Pustau on Hamburg

- Same trend in Hamburg — **'stock exchange' and 'Jews'** very much connected in people's minds
- Her father began to speak against Jews more and more
- Asserting now: "creative capital is the capital we Germans have: parasitical capital is the capital of the Jews"
- 'You should have known my father as he used to be' — he had provided political education, explained things against Kaiser and Parliament
- "But now he has stopped thinking and reasoning, and this will do more damage to us than it will ever damage the Jews"

### Reparations Commission Crisis

- End July 1922: **Reparations Commission took summer holidays**
- Effectively postponed any settlement of exchange turmoil until mid-August
- **M. Poincaré** sent Note accusing Germany of wilful default on debts, threatening 'retortion'
- Effect on financial situation calamitous — rise in prices intensified demand for currency
- **Private banks couldn't meet demand**, had to ration cashing of cheques
- Uncashed cheques remained frozen while purchasing power drained away
- Impossible to persuade anyone to accept description of cheque
- Panic spread to working classes when they realized **wages simply not available**

### Emergency Money (*Notgeld*)

- Reichsbank's printing presses and note-distribution insufficient
- Law passed permitting issue of **emergency money tokens (*Notgeld*)** by state/local authorities and industrial concerns
- Under licence, against deposit of appropriate assets, when Reichsbank couldn't satisfy wage-payment needs
- Purpose: regularise and regulate practice that had gone on for years
- Authorized *Notgeld* now had **Reichsbank's guarantee** behind it
- As guarantee became less esteemed, tide of emergency money entered local circulation
- With or without Bank's approval, **enormously raised level of paper sea engulfing the country**
- Ability to print money privately during accelerating inflation made possible private profits "only limited by people's willingness to accept it"
- "Process merely banked up the inflationary fire to ensure a still bigger blaze later on"

### August Strikes and Wage Demands

- Excessive rise in cost of living brought pressing demands for higher wages from all classes
- **Strikes accompanied those demands**
- **Shop employees in Frankfurt** strike (August 8): wage increase 7,200 to 9,600 marks/month backdated to beginning July
- Followed by **compositors' strike** — closed newspapers two weeks, settlement promised weekly wage increase of 500 marks effective until September 1, then 800 marks until September 16
- **Government officials** awarded 38% increase from August 1
- **Government workers** additional 12 marks/hour — further burden of 125 milliard paper marks
- No plans to meet burden beyond 50% increase in rail freight charges (September 1) and postal rate increase
- Face values of new postage stamps in late 1922: started at **50-mark blue**, went up to **100,000-mark red** (1916 range: 2-pfennig grey to 4-mark red and black)

### Mr Seeds on Munich Living Costs

- **Mr Seeds** (Munich): chauffeur's weekly food expenditure now 5½ times as great as year ago (August 1921)
- Wages nearly six times higher
- Fixed according to average rate paid to his class of worker
- Wage rises (monthly occurrence) **always lagged behind price rises** (weekly, if not daily)
- Case for vast mass of artisans and workmen
- **Middle class, officials, journalists** "far from being in the same satisfactory position"
- Foreign information mostly derived from this latter group — "why accounts of incidence of inflation published abroad were almost unrelievedly gloomy"

### Ernest Hemingway's Kehl Report

- Young **Ernest Hemingway** (working for *Toronto Daily Star*) crossed frontier from France, managed to be equally gloomy from other side:

> There were no marks to be had in Strasbourg, the mounting exchange had cleaned the bankers out days ago, so we changed some French money in the railway station at Kehl. For 10 francs I received 670 marks. Ten francs amounted to about 90 cents in Canadian money. That 90 cents lasted Mrs Hemingway and me for a day of heavy spending and at the end of the day we had 120 marks left!

- First purchase: fruit stand — picked five very good apples, gave old woman 50-mark note, received 38 marks change
- White bearded old gentleman saw purchase, raised hat, asked timidly "how much were the apples?"
- Told him 12 marks. "He smiled and shook his head. 'I can't pay it. It is too much.'"
- Old gentleman walked away very longingly looking at apples
- "Twelve marks, on that day, amounted to a little under 2 cents"
- **Old man's life savings** probably invested in German pre-war and war bonds — couldn't afford 12 mark expenditure
- "He is the type of the people whose incomes do not increase with the falling purchasing value of the mark and the krone"

### Exchange Rate Anecdotes

- Mark at 800 to dollar, or 8 to cent
- Pound of coffee: 34 marks
- Beer: 10 marks a stein (one cent and a quarter)
- Kehl's best hotel: five-course meal for 150 marks (15 cents)

> The French cannot come over to buy up all the cheap goods they would like to. But they can come over and eat … This miracle of exchange makes a swinish spectacle where the youth of the town of Strasbourg crowd into the German pastry shop to eat themselves sick, and gorge on fluffy, cream-filled slices of German cake at 5 marks the slice.

- Pastry shop contents swept clear in half hour
- Proprietor and helper "surly and didn't seem particularly happy when all the cakes were sold. The mark was falling faster than they could bake"
- Profiteers' motorcars raising dust cloud, French hoodlums eating cakes, French mothers wiping sticky mouths — "It gave you a new aspect on exchange"
- As afternoon tea-ers went Strasbourg-wards, "first of the exchange pirates coming over to raid Kehl for cheap dinners began to arrive"

### Dr Wirth's Despair (August 16)

- Mark plummeted downwards
- **Dr Wirth** dining with Lord D'Abernon (August 16): mark fallen below 1,000 to dollar (price about 5) — "one of the worst in the history of Germany and also one of the worst in his experience"
- Inundated with visitors in semi-panic about financial crisis, all kinds of unworkable or impracticable solutions

### The Denial of Money Printing

- **Chancellor would accept no connection between printing money and its depreciation**
- Remained largely unrecognised in Cabinet, bank, parliament, press
- *Vossische Zeitung* (August 16):

> the opinion that the flood of paper is the real origin of the depreciation is not only wrong but dangerously wrong … Both private and public statistics have long shown that for the last two years the interior depreciation of the mark is due to the depreciation of the rate of exchange … our paper circulation, although it shows on paper a terrifying array of milliards, is really not excessively high … We have no 'dangerous flood of paper' but, on the contrary, our total circulation is at least three or four times as small as in peace time.

- Lord D'Abernon described these views as "far from exceptionally retrograde" — typical of enlightened Berlin opinion
- *Berliner Börsen Courier* (couple days later): greater concern for social consequences but no more awareness about reasons
- Regretted German mark at **one-three-hundredth of par value**, now same class as Hungarian korona
- Proletariate becoming restless, State whose taxation estimates based on average exchange rate of 500 to dollar was helpless

### The "Moral Effect" of Depreciation

- Real tragedy: **"the moral effect"**
- Apparently endless fall in mark value "predicted abroad will cause at home an unbearable increase of uncertainty"
- No economic discussions will pacify masses or hide price of bread
- Long realised: **printing of notes is result, not cause of depreciation**
- Amount of currency increasing in bulk, actually decreasing in value
- Point reached where **lack of money has worse effect than depreciation itself**
- "Even should quantity of paper money be three times its present size, it would constitute no real obstacle to stabilisation"
- "Until such a time, therefore, let us print notes!"

### The True Picture

- Clear to leading financial daily: as total paper marks rose from 35 milliards (December 1919) to 200 milliards (July 1922), **equivalent sterling value fell from £193 million to £83 million**
- Before war: currency circulation of 6 milliard marks worth about £300 million
- Cause still matter for firmly asserted conjecture

### Dr Hummel's Views

- **Dr Hummel** (young, influential State President of Baden): wouldn't take responsibility for halting presses
- Attributed fall in mark variously to **moral and psychological causes, Poincaré's posturing, burden of reparations**, and note-printing
- "Doubtless they were all contributory factors"
- **D'Abernon** likened Poincaré's attitude to teacher constantly rapping pupil on knuckles without realising he was moribund
- "Yet the catastrophe of Austria was an object lesson for all to see"
- "A continued panic in the mark is probable unless the immediate cause of its fall - i.e. the continuous outpouring of notes from the printing press - is stopped"
- "It will require a surgical operation to get this into the heads of authorities here: nothing short of trepanning will do it"

### Wirth's Food Crisis Warning

- August 24: **Dr Wirth** telling ambassador about fears Germany unable to find enough food during coming winter during reparation payments
- As they talked: "a card was brought in giving the dollar exchange at 1,837 - an enormous fall since yesterday"

### Diplomatic Confusion (August 26)

- Confusion of people and government echoed at diplomatic levels
- **D'Abernon's diary** (August 26):

> Met the American Ambassador this afternoon, who said, 'I know a great many things; how much do you know?' But I could not get out of him what the deuce it was. He said, 'We are almost at war'; but whether he meant America and England, or France and Germany, or some other complication, I have no idea.

## 7: The Hapsburg Inheritance

### Austria's Wealth Redistribution

- Post-war years brought remarkable **redistribution of wealth and income** in Austria
- Main problem: excessive proportion received by working classes now escaped taxation
- Beyond government's wit to tax wages workers couldn't immediately pass on to employers (who wouldn't pass to consumer)
- Wouldn't then be passed round again to printing press via wage and price increases
- **Alarming picture of national selfishness** bred by inflation and **political ineptitude** bred by economic uncertainty
- **Mr O.S. Phillpotts** (Commercial Secretary, British Legation, Vienna):

> The Austrians are like men on a ship who cannot manage it, and are continually signalling for help. While waiting, however, most of them begin to cut rafts, each for himself, out of the sides and decks. The ship has not yet sunk despite the leaks so caused, and those who have acquired stores of wood in this way may use them to cook their food, while the more seamanlike look on cold and hungry. The population lack courage and energy as well as patriotism.

### The Krone's Collapse

- May 1921: krone reached 2,000 to pound
- May 1922: **35,000 to pound**
- Root causes much the same, supported by international doubts
- Public domestic pessimism drove Austrians to **purchase all they could with all cash they had**
- Determination to **hoard all food obtainable** despite harsher penalties recently imposed
- Shopkeepers recently obliged to accept State's banknotes
- Since it also permitted continued use of foreign currency, tradesmen found excuses for accepting little else
- Move led to considerable aggravation — every shop in Vienna crowded, peasants trooping in thousands to old imperial capital to rid themselves of money

### V.W. Germains on Vienna Shopping

> 'Women bought in stocks of sugar, coffee, and other goods against a rise in prices, or spent their money on clothes and furniture'

- Others squandered money recklessly — wine dearer tomorrow
- Days when wine would rise: run on shops, prices rise hour to hour, public seized with **mania for buying**
- Stories of old bachelor who bought swaddling clothes because local shop had nothing else to sell
- Shopkeepers countered by closing shops on pretexts (illness, family affairs, stocktaking)

### Dr Schober's Fall (May 1922)

- Mid-May 1922: **Dr Schober's** gallant, almost single-handed efforts as Chancellor to bring order to Austria's economy came to end
- Administration defeated in parliament bare four weeks after persuading Allies at Genoa to relinquish prior mortgage rights on Austrian State property
- Agreement cleared way for **raising an Austrian loan**
- Politicians felt Schober served his turn
- Dismissal of country's strongest statesman immediately sprinkled question-marks over creditworthiness
- With news of ex-police chief's resignation: British credit promised by Lloyd George ran out, that from France and Italy never materialised
- **Krone began to slip away again**
- Austria's condition stayed particularly critical vs Hungary or Germany due to heavy dependence on foreign imports

### June Krone Crash

- After June 1: krone's fall became vertiginous
- June 5: **52,000 to pound** (well over 10,000 to dollar) — produced panic contributing to further 40% fall in next two days
- June 9: pound at **70,000 kronen**, dollar at more than 15,000
- Within a month of **Rathenau's assassination** in Germany (end June): krone dived in sympathy with mark from 100,000 to 125,000
- In parallel: huge price increases (index base 100 in July 1921 reaching 2,645)

### Political Incompetence and Anschluss Talk

- Viennese politicians' competence became "merely a bad joke in the capital"
- Outside: contempt for and dislike of central government increased
- Styria and Tyrol: union with Italy widely canvassed as better alternative
- Vienna talk of ***Anschluss*** with Germany continued, encouraged by Pan-Germans
- Forbidden by peace treaties, disparaged by Berlin
- "Who would want to join us, with the mark in the condition it is?" — **Dr Wirth**
- League of Nations Council refused necessary permission
- **Communist subversion** of country increased, with more finance from Moscow

### Austrian Communist Party

- Austrian Communist Party itself as completely and hopelessly bankrupt as the country
- Moscow thought it worthwhile supporting because of relations with Germany's more significant movement
- Well organised and, apart from protests against rising prices and routine appeals to confiscate wealth of rich, interested itself successfully in provoking or extending strikes
- Notable development: far from being covert organisation, **individual Communists began to show their allegiance and hands quite openly**

### Dr Seipel's Desperate Plea (August 1922)

- August 1922: new, despairing plea sent by **Dr Ignaz Seipel** (Schober's successor as Chancellor)
- Requesting from Entente loan of **£15 million**
- In name of Supreme Council: **Lloyd George refused it**
- Regretting Austria since war had 'already received so much from them with such disappointing results'
- Austria cuttingly referred to League of Nations
- By end of month: krone fallen to **350,000 to pound** (exactly one-tenth its May value)
- **Despair was complete**
- Austrians waited for sky to fall as though it hadn't already done so a dozen times
- Chief of police publicly announced **20,000 men he could count upon to disarm the dangerously Left-wing Austrian army**
- **American minister in Vienna** warned visitors not on business to stay away
- Frequent strikes and demonstrations, greater disorders prophesied
- 'Timid Jewish businessmen' reported hastening to get passports in order
- Risk of plundering by hungry, workless mobs daily grew
- Since July: **cost of living index increased 124%**
- July alone: State could only meet liabilities to employees of 150 milliard kronen by paying instalments
- August increase raised obligation to 344 milliards
- **National wage figure for month about 700 milliards** — in any case, far more than existing circulation
- **Collapse of all governmental authority was imminent**

### Austria's Basic Financial Problem

- Situation reflected Austria's basic problem: **excessive expenditure on superfluous official salaries and wages**
- Number of recipients greatly inflated during war years
- As they rose automatically on index, could only be met by printing more money
- Trade unions by end July protesting: index adjusted monthly on basis of previous month's cost of living rise **no longer sufficed to keep pace with prices**
- Pressures to print more constantly growing
- August alone: extra issue of uncovered banknotes **560 milliards** — helped make nonsense of Act passed in July to set up new bank of issue
- Capital of 800 milliards supplied half by forced loan, half by new taxation
- Though encouraged by Reparations Commission, scheme stillborn because **scale of depreciation made it out of date**

### *Devisenzentrale* Failure

- With July's krone crash: substitute Bourse (**_Devisenzentrale_**) set in motion in Vienna
- Means of regulating transactions and movements in foreign currency
- Germany and Hungary both emulated within couple months
- Not only failed to stay the rout: couldn't bring back critical **£18 million worth of Austrian gold** reckoned lodged in Switzerland
- Didn't alleviate harassing conditions of Austrian middle classes or terrible life of lower
- No noticeable effect on operations of speculators, deprivations of profiteers, or process of currency devaluation
- As krone became unacceptable and unaccepted, those with foreign banknotes (main medium of exchange) began to **refuse to part with them at all**
- Austrians back where war had left them: few million bankrupt, hungry people floundering about on map they didn't recognise

### Seipel's Tour of Europe

- Austria "barely afloat as a nation on the tumultuous European seas of 1922," suddenly to find ground beneath feet
- Refusing to await supinely approach of ruin, **Dr Seipel** resolved to trade part of country's independence in return for survival at all
- "Now was seen the hitherto unparalleled spectacle of an Austrian Chancellor touring Europe offering his country to the highest bidder"

### Seipel's Appeal to League of Nations

- Seipel's tour embraced each of Austria's neighbours in turn
- Subtle diplomatic prelude to moving appeal to **League of Nations in Geneva** (early September)
- Demonstrated conclusively: without financial help, Austria established by Treaty of St Germain would fall to bits
- Announced Vienna prepared to accept whatever degree of discipline League might require
- Pistol at League's head less the horror of Austrian disintegration than **threat of Austrian customs union** with Germany, Bavaria, Italy, or Danube States
- Speedily becoming only other viable solution
- Austria becoming Italian protectorate, part of Greater Italy, gave France particular cause to think twice

### The Recovery Begins

- Entire position changed miraculously as negotiations with League began
- Krone which reached nadir August 25 rose little: 350,000 to 335,000 to pound in first week September
- Helped by confidence talks engendered, government

<!-- pp. 101-120 -->

## Austria's Stabilization (Late 1922)

### The Geneva Protocols

- Three protocols prepared within a month to rescue Austria
- First: guaranteed Austria's political and territorial integrity
- Second: Britain, France, Italy, and Czechoslovakia underwrote 650 million gold kronen Austrian loan
- Third: Austria pledged to balance budget, cease discounting Treasury bills, establish new bank of issue
- Absolute financial power vested in **Commissioner-General** appointed by League of Nations

### The Paradoxical Stabilization

- After price index peaked September 15, 1922, prices fell 20% by year-end
- **Krone stabilized against dollar from September 2 onward** — despite money supply inflation continuing for 2.5 more months
- Note circulation more than trebled while krone held steady
- Government "walking the thinnest of tightropes" — living on printing press credit while waiting for Geneva rescue

### Post-Stabilization Crisis

- Oxymoronic inflation after stabilization — need to replace foreign banknotes in circulation
- Physical shortage of cash: August 1922 only 80 million gold crowns circulating vs. 500 million pre-war
- Prices fell because no longer exorbitant to ensure profitability; market saturated, demand collapsed
- **Austria so geared to continuous depreciation that stabilization alone created acute economic crisis**
- Government needed kronen; foreign currency (domestic or foreign sources) swelled bank reserves
- Bank forced to buy more foreign notes than needed

### Psychological and Administrative Roots

- Speed of confidence restoration showed Austria's problem was "mainly psychological and administrative"
- **Profound distrust in themselves and government, childlike reliance on foreign help and control**
- Revolution swept away traditional authority; void remained unfilled among impoverished officials and ruling classes

### Political Aftermath

- **Dr. Seipel** attacked by Socialists for "bartering sovereignty for gold"
- Mussolini's coup in Italy (mid-October) raised fascist specter — **fascismo** popular among many Austrians
- League understood no Austrian government strong enough to implement necessary economies or extricate country from anarchy/famine threats
- **Dr. Zimmermann**, League's Commissioner-General, arrived Vienna mid-December 1922

## Hungary's Parallel Crisis (1921-1922)

### Economic Devastation Statistics

- Currency in circulation increased 64x between 1913 and end of 1921
- Average domestic articles: 100 korona (1914) now cost 8,260
- State revenue had been 1/10th greater than expenditure pre-war
- By 1921, expenditure 1/3 higher than revenue
- War, revolution, counter-revolution, Red Terror, White Terror, Admiral Horthy's regency destroyed normal monetary standards

### Flight from Currency

- Great despondency: anyone with money converted to foreign currency, industrial stock, antiques, jewellery
- Stock Exchange speculation rife across all classes
- Currency rates watched daily

### Dr. Hegedüs's Draconian Reforms (1921)

- **Finance Minister Dr. Hegedüs** aimed to stabilize krone at 400 to pound (from 2,100 in January)
- April 1921: Emperor Karl's restoration attempt brought rate to 800 briefly
- **Hegedüs reforms spread over nine months proved too draconian** — led to resignation September 1921
- Bills passed: 20% levy on capital, fiscal attacks on war fortunes, shares, luxuries, property
- **Grave psychological mistake: 20% levy on bank deposits** — peasants hoarded cash at home afterward, "dearth of currency"

> "Dr. Hegedüs ascribed his failure to the fall of the German mark, to the poor harvest, and to the uncertainty about reparations."

- Final act: 960 million krone (£600,000) salary increase for civil servants — triggered new inflation/depreciation

### Trade Effects of Currency Swings

- Korona appreciation (spring 1921) → unemployment grew (goods purchased at 2,000:£1 couldn't be sold at 800:£1)
- Merchants and manufacturers suffered when korona improved
- Industrial workless welcomed relief when korona fell
- **Official classes on fixed incomes welcomed temporary rise**
- **Peasantry (two-thirds population) indifferent** — sold produce near world market price, possibly better off than similar Europeans

### The Official Class Tragedy

- High official (under-secretary): pre-war salary 2,000 korona/month sufficient for moderate luxury and education
- Now aided with 3,000 korona/month subsidy, needed minimum 20,000
- 20,000 korona = £120/year (September 1921), worth £70/year by Christmas
- Clerical work remunerated at fraction of pre-war rates — "correspondingly miserable"

**Mr. Hohler** (British High Commissioner Budapest) reported:

> "Under such circumstances one could scarcely be surprised were bribery rampant: and it says much for the Hungarian civil servants that cases of officials being corrupted are comparatively speaking rare. The official and cultured classes are by far the worst off. Reticence prevents ascertaining what proportion is actually in need. The sale rooms, however, indicate the straits to which so many are reduced."

- Younger members of official class joined **violent anti-Semitic secret societies**
- Attracted support from younger Army officers seeking cause to blame for poverty

### Accelerating Crisis (Mid-1922)

- June 1922: note issue +28%, price index +36%, korona depreciation -75% (spread representing single week's disparity)
- Mid-June: pound bought 4,500 korona — reflection of Germany/Austria's financial state
- **New Finance Minister Dr. Kallay**: orthodox circles blamed "lack of confidence in Zurich," not printing press
- Depreciation abroad often preceded fresh currency issues — textbook effect on budgetary deficit knowledge
- Government supposed stabilization impossible while reparations debt unknown
- Circulation doubled since Treaty of Trianon ratification

### Social Unrest (Late June 1922)

- Cost-of-living protests growing
- Strikes by Budapest municipal scavengers and sewage-pumpers bought off with 12-75% wage increases
- **Dr. Kallay "irresistibly driven towards increasing issues of paper money"**
- Korona: 6,000:£1 (July 17) → 7,000:£1 week later
- Prices moved up in step; new wage demands arrived

### Farmer Withholding and Self-Created Doom

- Nation's wealth produced by farming community paying same money taxes as pre-war (less than 1/200th real terms)
- Fiscal inequity intensified urban/industrial vs. farmer enmity
- **Financial opportunities encouraged farmers to withhold crops** — create artificial demand, increase average price
- "Hungary's doom was largely self-created"

### Devaluation Acceleration (September 1922)

- September: note circulation +25% over August, korona dropped to 11,000:£1
- Finance Ministry claimed increases "merely reflected increase in country's assets with harvest gathering"
- Currency would be gathered in as crop distributed
- Hope vain — couldn't move harvest at the price

### The *Devisenzentrale* Disaster

- Government set up **foreign exchange control office** (*Devisenzentrale*) on Austrian model to ward off disaster
- **"*Kinderkrankheiten*" (teething troubles) made situation greatly worse**
- Fixed exchange rate for korona below market value
- Unable to induce foreign currency holders to part with it
- Office couldn't help merchants pay foreign creditors
- Previously: traders sold overseas at day's exchange rate, covered creditors' currency immediately
- New regulations: each application came before badly organized office, delayed up to two weeks
- Only proportion of applications granted due to shortage
- **Foreign trade quickly slowed, led to more unemployment**

### Currency Stabilization and Stock Bubble (November 1922)

- November: korona held artificially steady at 12,000:£1
- *Devisenzentrale* working smoothly; speculators disgusted (opportunity for korona price speculation abroad gone)
- **Exchange speculation → Stock Exchange speculation → wild industrial share buying stampede**
- Shares quoted 8,000 korona (spring) soared to 100,000+
- Companies increased capital, watered stock
- Public spending continued; conservative investors sold new holdings for profit at compatriots' expense
- Two months steady currency + preventive laws against exchange speculation → forced speculators to realize share holdings
- Quotations fell; many badly bitten

### Inflation's Relentless March

- Watching public too poor to gamble couldn't rejoice
- Korona firm, but prices +60% in two months before November 1
- November 13: government raised rail fares and freight charges substantially — direct fierce consequences for general prices

**Hohler** wrote:

> "All classes have completely lost any sense of proportion so far as costs are concerned. A Hungarian who merely shrugs his shoulders and murmurs something about the Treaty of Trianon when charged 5,000 kronen for a bottle of *vin mousseux* is exasperated by a rise of 5 kronen in the price of tram tickets."

### Class-by-Class Impact Assessment

**State officials:**
- Extremely hard hit, unable to strike
- Kept alive only by meagre salaries supplemented by privileges (nominal rail fares, right to buy needs cheaply)
- Difficult to understand how those unable to *profiter de l'occasion* managed to exist

**Army officers:**
- Major: 575 korona/week pre-war → 17,000/week (£1 10s) → needed 184,000 to regain spending power
- Real terms: lieutenant made do with £1/week, corps commander £2 5s
- Married officers: wife and child allowance 3,500 korona/month (6s) per head

**Rentier classes:**
- "Most distressing picture" except lucky few with capital in neutral countries
- Younger/active found work; older destitute
- Professional classes (doctors, lawyers) in Germany/Austria: shortage of patients/clients, but could adjust charges
- Medical profession hindered by hospitals denuded of elementary appointments
- Professional men on fixed salaries: "reduced to absolute penury"
- **Clerks (highly important class in capital):** 12,000-20,000/month (£12-£19/year), shrinking continually
- Most got nominal luncheons from offices — "body and soul just kept together"
- "60% rise in prices for this class does not bear dwelling upon"

**Workers with trade unions:**
- Not badly off, pay revised time to time
- Not exactly fortunate
- 1914: 80 hours work to buy suit of clothes
- 1919: 141 hours
- July 1922: 381 hours
- Dozen eggs: 1 hour → 3 hours
- Kilo bread: 0.5 hours → 2 hours

**Countryside landowners and farmers:**
- Least affected
- Produced own essentials, raised commodity prices regularly
- Landless peasants not doing well
- Casual labourers (wanderings limited by new Hungarian confines) particularly destitute

**Thrivers in crisis:**
- Many thriving, responsible for superficial prosperity atmosphere Budapest presented
- **Notably Jews, who made up much of capital's population** (Hohler's assessment)

### Crisis Atmosphere (Christmas 1922)

- Clear crisis couldn't be long delayed
- Korona support unsustainable
- Secret organizations growing, extreme nationalism burgeoning, anti-Semitism evident even in official circles
- **Hungary near the brink**

## Chapter 8: Autumn Paper-chase (Germany, Fall 1922)

### Rural Germany's Advantage

- Only country people surviving in comfort — readiest access to real values
- Accused of extortion when delaying sales (knowing prices would rise)

**Erna von Pustau** (country visit):
- Asked hosts what they were doing with money from squeezing townspeople
- Reply: paying off mortgages
- **"*Mark gleich Mark*" principle helped agriculture enormously**
- August 1922: mark 2,000:$1 (9,000:£1) — seven/eight-year mortgage 399/400ths paid off
- Upon return home, family talk: "prices going up, credits reduced, middle-class party, big business and workers who always asked for more"

> "The contrast between country and city was so enormous that it cannot be understood by people who have not lived through it."

### Windfall Profits and Speculation

**Herr Hans-Georg von der Osten** (former Flying Circus pilot, later Goering's ADC):
- Shot Reichsmarschall's favourite stag, recalled February 1922 loan from friendly banker
- Bought estate neighbouring own property (Pomerania) for 4 million marks (£4,500)
- Paid debt in autumn with sale of less than half crop from one potato field
- June same year: bought 100 tons maize from dealer for 8 million marks (£5,000)
- Week later, before delivery, sold whole load back for double — made 8 million marks without lifting finger
- Used sum to furnish mansion house, buy three guns, six suits, three expensive shoe pairs — then eight days in Berlin

> "This was simple commerce: the only thing to do with cash by that time was to turn it into something else as quickly as possible. To save was folly."

- Many farmers behaved outrageously, buying useless machinery, furniture, pianos for unmusical households
- **Dr. Schacht's** account: farmers safeguarded against paper currency losses by buying assets maintaining value

> "Wholesale recourse to real values enabled not only the well-to-do but also, and especially, the unscrupulous to preserve and even possibly to increase their assets... As a result of this struggle for self-enrichment and financial self-preservation, based on exploitation of the ignorance of the masses, every aspect of business life was vitiated."

- Condemning individual struggle as selfish/unnatural/wrong was unjust
- When people don't understand what's happening, why it's happening, what to do, panic follows
- Country people behaving naturally brought no comfort to townspeople with no goods to barter, static incomes

### Academic and Intellectual Class Devastation

**Hesse professor** (September lament):
- Professors, teachers, men of science "no longer given the right to live"
- Many would die coming winter from lack of food and warmth
- Feared sons would turn to manual labour instead of following fathers' careers

> "Labour, wholly or partially educated labour, has already begun to rule in Germany, and there is no demand for brains: that is to say, brains have no longer a marketable value. The result can only be a catastrophe for Germany and the downfall of civilisation in central Europe if not, indeed, the whole world."

### Wages Falling Behind Prices (First Time)

- New crisis element: wages lagging behind price rises — noticeably, seriously
- Despite union monopoly, couldn't act
- **President Ebert** (pleading with Curzon for reparations moratorium): working population conditions "completely impossible," Germany's economic downfall imminent

**Price increases (April-September 1922):**
- Milk: 7 marks → 16 marks (mid-September 26 marks)
- Beer: 5.60 marks/litre → 18 → 30
- Single egg: 3.60 → 9 marks
- **Mr. Seeds's chauffeur:** weekly food basket bill 370 marks → 2,615 (nine months)

**Consul's report:**

> "The rise of nearly 100 per cent within the last four weeks has proceeded by such sudden leaps and bounds that no scheme for a simultaneous increase in wages can well be devised to cope with it: an increase of wages granted at the end of one week would not meet the rise in prices by the following Tuesday, for instance, and the working and salaried classes have suffered severely despite their continually increasing remuneration... The wage situation is hopelessly dislocated at present."

### Printing Press Acceleration

- September 9: 23 milliard marks printed and distributed in previous ten days (10% of total circulation)

> "The daily production of the Federal printing press has now risen to 2.6 milliards of paper marks. In the course of this month it will be increased to almost 4 milliards of paper marks, at which figure it is hoped the shortage of money will be definitely overcome."

### Emergency Money and Municipal Currencies

- **Shortage of liquid cash acute** — July emergency money law effect
- Large industrial concerns paid workers partly in notes, partly in coupons (accepted by local tradesmen, redeemed very short time)
- **Municipalities issued own currencies** — aware delay in pay packets would aggravate workers (main concern: spend before depreciation)
- Cities/towns developed parallel fear of unemployment → outbreaks of Communist disorder
- Began artificially creating employment for staff
- Frankfort citizens alarmed: serviceable roads being repaired outside town, overhead telephone wires converting to underground

### Free Fall Resumes (October 1922)

- Reichsbank's September plans fulfilled
- Second week October: mark entering free fall — 9,000 → 13,000:£1 (six weeks)
- Hopes demand for ready money would be met speedily dashed
- **Professor Keynes** (15 months earlier): predicted mark would fall point/day until reaching 1,000:£1
- Out by factor of 13 in less than 2/3 time
- Wrote *Manchester Guardian* (September 29): 2 milliard gold marks/year (£100 million) maximum Germany could pay reparations
- Beyond that sum "in realm of phantasy," no certainty even that amount could be paid
- France's demand >3 milliards/year based on "fallacy that extremity of France's need enlarges Germany's capacity"
- Keynes promptly invited with other independent experts to Germany to advise on arresting mark's fall

### Expert Proposals Ignored

- Keynes considered "breathing space" essential before resuming even modest payments

**Albert Einstein** forwarded to Lord Haldane article from *Berliner Tageblatt*:
- Suggested Britain and France participate in German industry to extent of 30% share capital
- Einstein desired Haldane arrange "so my name shall not be given publicity in connection with this matter" — considered it happy solution

- Einstein's recommendation bore no fruit
- November experts' report published: sensible programme (monetary stabilisation ~14,000:£1, budgetary equilibrium, foreign loans, temporary reparation relief)
- Totally ignored by debtor and creditor alike
- Much else to preoccupy them:
  - Britain: Lloyd George's coalition displaced by Conservative administration under Bonar Law (October)
  - Italy: Mussolini staged *coup*

### Capital Controls and Currency Regulations

- Germany: people resorting to barter, turning to foreign currencies as only reliable exchange medium
- **New Orders re: foreign bills purchase and foreign exchange use for inland payments**
- Imprisonment + fines up to 10x illegal deal amount
- **To prevent capital flight:** transfer from country had to be authorized, not justified
- Importers' transactions closely regulated
- Moves (unfortunately) made legitimate trade more difficult, took no account of foreign stock exchange speculation possibility
- Unlikely to prevent mark's downward course

### Rye Bills Experiment

**Oldenburg** attempt to offer safe public investment alternative to foreign currency:
- **"Rye bills" (*Roggenmarks*)** issued by state bank, due for repayment 1927
- Issue price: current value of 125 kilograms rye
- Repayment: average price of 150 kilograms rye (first quarter later year)
- Extra 25 kilograms = four years' interest
- Bearer bonds with stock exchange quotations, secured by bank's total funds

### October Price Explosions

- September's 26-mark milk litre → October's 50-mark litre
- Butter: 50 marks/pound (April) → 480
- Two months: egg price doubled to 14 marks
- Pocket comb: 2,000 marks
- Pot of honey: 8,000
- Pair child's trousers: 5,000
- Dozen kitchen plates: 7,500
- Pair silk stockings: 16,500
- Roll lavatory paper: 2,000
- Pair children's shoes: 2,800
- **Three masses for relation still available at old price of 150**

### Oktoberfest and Starvation Threats

- Bavarian Landtag deputies vied urging central government send state poor relief
- Hundreds of thousands threatened with starvation
- Plight made poignant by **Oktoberfest** arrival (Munich's three-week annual fair)
- Mark dropped 9,000 → 12,000 → 18,000:£1
- Beer: 30 marks/litre → 78
- Merrymakers from countryside celebrating harvest became political denunciation objects (replaced tourists mostly gone home)

**Mr. Seeds** (Munich consulate):

> "The deputies are thoroughly justified in speaking of the excesses of the fair with bitter condemnation, but a foreign observer who noticed that the thousands and thousands of revellers were composed solely of the working and lower middle classes, would be justified in doubting the existence of the much advertised starving population. Except where certain sections of the middle classes are concerned, it is difficult to resist the feeling that the food subsidies are merely a means of passing on to the taxpayer a portion of the wages which should be paid by the industrialists."

### Stinnes and Industrial Strategy

**Stinnes** (eponym of capitalist ruthlessness, meeting with British businessmen Cologne, November 1922):
- Asked how long Germany's industrialists prepared to see state of affairs continue
- Replied: would try to carry on as long as they could
- "If necessary until day after French government makes up its mind to pursue policy of understanding"
- Apt to seize any opportunity driving wedge between France and Britain
- Probably genuinely regarded as secondary importance to unemployment risk the actual point to which mark might sink

> "With a central government without power or authority, with acute economic distress, and with revengeful neighbours ready to fish in troubled waters, we will do everything in our power to keep our workmen employed."

### Employment at Any Cost

**Ruhr** factories using various devices to avoid putting men on streets:
- **Bochumer Verein** (Essen): engaged 1,500 men making railway stock articles with no immediate requirement
- Such measures only possible for firms with big financial reserves
- Small firms already dismissing workers in small numbers
- November price increases (butter 800 marks/lb., eggs 22 marks each) → shops cutting assistants (sales dropping)

### Wage-Price Spiral Catastrophe

- Disparity between cost of living rise and wage rise now very marked
- Since war: former up ~1,500 times
- **November 1922 best-paid worker (miner):** gone up barely 200 times
- Mark (mid-November): 27,000:£1, 6,400:$1
- Prices following both with unfailing regularity
- Wages generally failing to keep pace; workers not even paid their due
- **Shortage of paper money all kinds (federal currency or *Notgeld*):** by time balance paid, lost 50% value
- Best-paid workers unable to purchase barest necessities
- Others and those on fixed incomes/dependent on savings suffered accordingly

### Physical and Social Breakdown

- Suffering acute, only culmination of many months increasing misery
- Worse to come
- Conditions Berlin may not have been typical of every urban community, but indicative of general distress
- **Chief burgomaster of Pankow (1922):** nearly 25% children leaving school below normal weight/height spread, 30% unfit to work for health reasons
- Schöneberg: 1913 8% school leavers tubercular → 15%

**Burgomaster's report:**

> "Want is gradually strangling every feeling for cleanliness, and decency, leaving room only for thoughts of the fight with hunger and cold."

### Trade Union Collapse

- Wages failing to keep pace with prices → impoverishment of even fortunate workers → direct effect on trade unions
- Tumbling union fund values + impossibility of raising subscription in hard times → ordinary strikes less and less practicable
- Union leaders less able to extract/deliver higher wages workers/situation demanded
- Lost first influence, then control (though wouldn't admit it)
- Increasingly nervous state, necessary to make repeated appeals to members to maintain discipline and abide by union decisions

### Worker Radicalization and Riots

- Workers easily roused by extremist factions, liable to get out of hand and start rioting
- Especially when believed eight-hour day (greatest Revolution achievement) under attack from big industrials
- Many local authorities hesitated to fire on rioting mob; mixture unusually volatile
- **Third week November:** serious police-crowd collisions after Mannesmann works employees demanded 100% wage increase, tried unsuccessfully (with Communist encouragement) to declare general city strike
- Similar manifestation in Cologne
- **Dresden:** fierce outbreak against cost of living — provision shops looted, damage estimated 100 million marks
- Noisy xenophobia display before principal hotels housing foreigners (whose presence in country popularly supposed cause of price rise)
- Braunschweig: food riots, shop-plundering
- More food riots Berlin
- All controllable, but symptomatic of general distress and unrest

### Currency Collapse Reality

- Gold value money in circulation: nearly £300 million pre-war, £83 million July 1922 → £20 million by November
- More notes printed, lower value fell
- Illustrated **Copernican thesis** endorsed by King Sigismund of Poland (1526): "money loses its value when it has become too much multiplied"
- How country business could be carried on with so small real currency amount mystified many observers
- Accounted for ever-mounting pressures on bank to continue printing
- Trade continued notwithstanding — usually explained by reference to accelerating velocity with which money circulated
- Notes held for as short time as possible
- Private-account cheques hardly accepted
- Anyone receiving money for goods quickly converted back into other goods
- Money never stopped moving, doing work of 10x amount moving 1/10th as fast

### Government Breakdown (Mid-November 1922)

**Chancellor Wirth's government** broke down under strain mid-November:
- As month passed, mark fell to 30,000, 32,000, 34,000:£1 (8,000:$1)
- Reichsbank proclaimed, carrying out unlimited printing notes programme
- More and more printing presses employed
- December: amount issued limited only by press capacity and printers' physical fatigue

**Lord D'Abernon** (reported to London):

> "The exchange market and the Reichsbank are like a runaway horse with an incompetent rider - each aggravates the folly of the other."

Alternative metaphor:

> "In the whole course of history, no dog has ever run after its own tail with the speed of the Reichsbank. The discredit the Germans throw on their own notes increases even faster than the volume of notes in circulation. The effect is greater than the cause. The tail goes faster than the dog."

### Stock Market Collapse

- **Scarcity of money:** one reason for precipitous real terms drop in industrial shares
- Towards end of summer (gold terms): fallen to about 1/10th pre-war value
- Substantial loss for consistent holders, nothing like suffered by War Loan/fixed interest stock holders (values wiped out)
- **August *Berliner Tageblatt*:** assessed total value all German companies at not more than 4 milliard gold marks (~£200 million)
- Pointed to danger shares might systematically be bought up by foreigners
- "Picture of German industrial prosperity widely different from that current in certain organs of the London and Paris press"

### Nominal Share Price Inflation

**Basket of shares (companies not inflating or altering peace-time capital), July 1914-July 1922:**
- Daimler motor company mining shares (Gelsenkirchen): 181 → 1,374
- Muhlheimer: 155 → 1,990
- Schwelmer Eisenwerk: 135 → 2,800
- Deutsche Waffenund Munitions-fabriken: 331 → 1,605
- Kammgarnspinnerei Düsseldorf: 131 → 2,550
- Hotelbetriebs Berlin: 136 → 2,100
- Anglo-Continentale Guanowerke: 119 → 1,776
- Rise compared with 143-fold rise in gold mark value against paper mark

**Real terms valuation:**
- End of war: share price index fallen to about 1/3 of 1913 level
- Year 1921: at 1/5th
- October 1922: dropped to 3/100ths
- Popular felicity: Daimler Motor Company (at which point) with factories, lands, reserves, capital, organisation could have been swapped for price of 327 of its cars
- Demand for shares small: average dividend yield on equities only 0.25% (biggest shareholders preferred it so)
- Many less unsatisfactory ways of getting return on capital when wanted

### Bank Performance Statistics

**Deutsche Bank Report 1921:**
- Showed how greatly inflation reduced gold value of dividends (contrast to illusion of prosperity from high paper dividends)
- Bank's paper turnover: 2,125 milliards (1921) had real value of 85 milliard gold marks
- 1913 (less extensive ramifications): turnover 129 milliards
- 1922 dividend on capital of 400 million: equivalent to 1.5 million gold marks
- Against 25 million dividend distributed 1913 at 12½% on capital of 200 million

### Foreign Buying Begins (Post-October 1922)

- October 1922: nadir for shareholders
- From then on: money found way back into shares
- People who could obtain cheap credit or unable to send money abroad began realising advantages of buying up own country's industrial and other assets
<!-- pp. 121-140 -->

## End of 1922: Hyperinflation Accelerates

### Daily Price Explosions

- Stock market rising in real terms, but mark's purchasing power collapsing
- **Erna von Pustau**: "By end of year, my allowance worth less than one cup of coffee. Baker sold rolls for 20 marks in morning, 25 marks in afternoon. No one knew why — somehow the dollar, the stock exchange, the Jews."
- **Mr. Seeds's chauffeur** still instinctively trusted the mark like gold, failing to see how sick it had become
- Milk: 78 marks (first week Nov) → 202 marks (month later)
- Butter: 800 → 2,000 marks/lb
- Sugar: 90 → 220 marks/lb
- Eggs: 22 → 30 marks each
- Potatoes: still 8 marks/lb (only 1 mark increase)
- Eatable sausages: 1,400 marks for 1 lb

### Emergency Currency Proliferation

- **Notgeld** (emergency notes) now common as Reichsbank paper across most of country
- Could be printed in denominations up to 500-1,000 marks, limits regularly raised
- Redeemable in Reichsbank notes after 2-3 months
- Mid-November: 40 issuing bodies in occupied territories alone
- Diverse issuers: Anilin, Sodafabrik, Düsseldorf Landesbank, Stahlwerk Becker-Willich, chemical/banking/steel/flooring companies
- Towns paying employees with own currency: Krefeld, Coblenz, Düsseldorf, Duisburg, Worms, Treves, Mayence, Bonn, Cologne (bills signed by **Konrad Adenauer**)

## Fourth London Conference (December 1922)

### Poincaré's Hardline Position

- Conference was preliminary to Paris meeting, considering moratorium on reparations
- Remarkable for presence of **Mussolini** representing Italy, and **M. Poincaré's** firm announcement to **Bonar Law**: "Whatever happens, I shall advance into the Ruhr on January 15."
- **France**, not Britain, intent on "getting everything out of Germany that you can get out of a lemon and a bit more" — determined to "squeeze her until you can hear the pips squeak"

### Lloyd George vs. Poincaré

- **Lloyd George** believed Poincaré's proposals showed "either total inability to grasp even the alphabet of economic conditions governing payments from one country to another, or sinister resolve to engineer a German default under the treaty which would justify invasion of Westphalian minefields with ulterior possibilities of detaching them from the German fatherland"

### Bonar Law's Dilemma

- **Bonar Law** fully appreciated that mark stabilisation meant unemployment, industrial crisis, enormous financial strain for Germany
- Failure to stabilise = catastrophe
- Unable to convince French PM of futility of amassing vast quantities of paper marks by retortionary/extortionary measures
- Already 1,500 milliards collected by German customs on Allied reparations account — Reparations Commission dared not cash them (would get nothing)
- **Poincaré** obstinately sure German forests could be exploited under Allied military supervision, Reichsbank could be controlled to force up mark value
- Ruhr invasion proved him tragically wrong — whether intended to wreck Germany forever or not, it reduced French franc to one-fifth pre-war value

### Germany's Proposals Rejected

- December 10: London conference received Note from **Dr. Wilhelm Cuno** (Germany's new Chancellor) suggesting mark stabilisation measures including two-year moratorium on reparation payments
- Note rejected
- **Poincaré** insisted on 'productive pledges' from Berlin
- Further angered by Germany's proposing 30-year peace pact (regarded as manoeuvre)

### Events Move Toward Ruhr Invasion

- France and Britain parted brass rags January 4
- French, Belgian, Italian members of Reparation Commission (with Britain dissenting) decided January 9, 1923: Germany had been in voluntary default on coal/timber deliveries under peace treaty
- No legal way to prevent **Poincaré** from carrying out threats
- America's interceding was vain — US occupying forces withdrawn January 10
- January 11: **Poincaré** despatched control commission of engineers to Ruhr "for securing deliveries," accompanied by troops "for protection and ensuring execution of mission"
- French PM warned sanctions and coercive measures would be used if necessary

## The Ruhr Invasion (January 1923)

### Ostensible Purpose vs. True Motive

- Ostensible purpose: 'bring Germany to her senses' and compel her to pay up
- How severance of principal industrial region would make it easier to pay remained unexplained
- **Lloyd George's** opinion (strongly supported by summer events): true motive was setting up Rhineland confederation friendly to France
- Called it "act of military aggression against unarmed nation that was as unjustified as it was to prove unprofitable"
- One result: persuading many Germans that rearmament should be pursued at earliest opportunity
- Immediate effects simultaneously dynamic and catastrophic — country scandalised
- Lacking army big enough for counter-measures, Germany riposted only way that came to mind: **policy of passive resistance** in newly occupied areas

### The Ruhrkampf Economic Picture

- Industrial heart of Germany practically stopped beating
- Hardly anyone worked, hardly anything ran
- Coal mining never entirely stopped — some mine-owners pleaded reserves (always seized by French) should be maintained
- Population of Ruhr area: 2 million workers, 6 million souls — had to be supported by rest of country
- German economy denied most important domestic products and raw materials: coal, coke, iron, steel
- Robbed of former enormous foreign earnings from Rhine-Ruhr exports
- Exchequer deprived of all normal tax revenue from huge proportion of nation's industry, plus coal tax and income from Ruhr railways
- World price of coal and steel (which Germany now had to import) proceeded to rise, increasing difficulties still more

### Passive Resistance Forces France's Hand

- Policy forced invaders to act on wider scale than contemplated
- French franc moved sharply downwards from then on, France's war indemnities drifted further off than ever
- Yet France couldn't allow herself to lose the battle — more than German government could have capitulated before **force majeure**
- German nation wouldn't have stood for it, least of all in first months when unity of purpose of all classes in Ruhr astonished everybody
- Both sides totally committed in holy war
- German government knew only one weapon: **Ruhr struggle was between French pressure/subversion vs. German printing press**
- So long as paper banknotes exchangeable for food, fight would continue
- When they were not, it did not

## Pre-Ruhr Inflation Causes

### Why Germany Inflated Before the Ruhr

- Until Ruhr invasion, reasons for German inflation:
  1. Uncertainty of war aftermath
  2. Inexperience and weak acquiescence of new men in power
- **Industry** wanted neither heavy taxation nor to be hampered in expansion at home/abroad — government gave way and replaced missing revenue by printing
- Neither industrialists nor general public prepared to pay true costs of railways, post office, bread
- Government understood and printed money to pay for them
- Did Germany's nationals have claims from war or peace treaty? Did federal states or districts need to meet financial requirements? Government printed notes to satisfy everyone
- Told itself that granting credit through cheques had greatly decreased actual currency in circulation — had to be much greater
- **The rich and the strong came off best**

### Paradoxical Results by End of 1922

- **Destruction of State credit abroad** — one result of unlimited inflation
- **Other results beginning to show:**
  - Germany's strong competitive position meant German goods again available worldwide, though still only third of pre-war quantities
  - Everyone spending income as quickly as possible
  - Germany's home market absorbed incredible amounts of national product (greater short-term benefit to industry)

### Export/Import Distortions

- Since mid-1922, private payments and private credit (in/outside country) became much more difficult
- **Exporter generally well-placed** for restocking with raw materials — could use proceeds of foreign sales
- Comparison of German exports (chemicals, earthenware, metalware) with other countries showed **German export prices often ridiculously low**
- Part of reason: exporters careful profits not made at time of leaving Germany but on subsequent resale — evading regulation requiring foreign earnings to be repatriated
- Many export profits immune from everything from capital levy to financial crash
- **Those importing raw materials for selling on home market were in bad way:**
  - Exorbitant interest rates (25% per month)
  - Universal shortage of money
  - Normal commercial life seriously hampered
- Employers and employees already in continual session fixing wage tariffs (usually out of date as soon as they came into force)
- All internal values so distorted that confusion was complete at all levels of commerce

### Motor Trade Example

- Number of cars in country (1922): 1 car per 360 people
- Not great compared to France (1 per 176), Britain (1 per 91), US (1 per 10)
- Scope for sales correspondingly greater, demand very high
- Foreigners, **nouveau riche** businessmen, and landed proprietors usually the buyers (found cars cheaper to maintain than horses)
- Since war, gentleman owner who kept car for fun had practically disappeared
- Petrol cost: 17 marks/litre (½d) January 1922 → 686 at end of year

### Automobile Price Inflation

- **Ten-horse-power car** (with lighting and starting sets, no tyres):
  - January 1922: 220,000 marks (≈£270)
  - August: 1.25 million
  - January 1923: 11.4 million marks
  - Price varied by half or twice depending on which end of frenzied month one bought
- **Four-ton motor lorry** (without tyres, but with body and acetylene lighting):
  - January 1922: 265,000 marks (£320)
  - January 1923: 12.9 million
- **Pneumatic tyres** (one non-skid cover, one inner tube): 4,920 (£6) → 161,000 marks
- **Solid tyres**: 3,691 (£4 10s) → 202,095 marks apiece

### Business Impossibilities

- Impossible to quote prices in advance
- Customers wouldn't risk committing to 'gliding clause' in contract — after non-returnable deposit, final bill could be almost limitless depending on delivery date
- Dealers (financial resources already under enormous strain) constantly engaged in unpleasant correspondence with clients and suppliers
- Long time to iron out quarrel between dealer and manufacturer over deposit paid when ordering
- Normally one-third of current price as deposit, but by delivery time (very slow), deposit had become minute proportion of final price
- Manufacturers unfairly insisted full nominal balance should be met
- Throughout trade, sums realised from sales would not replace stocks

### Government Budget Disaster (Last 9 Months of 1922)

- Unsatisfactory conditions of internal commerce persuaded Exchequer that unbalanced budget had to be accepted
- **Revenue** (taxation, export duties, customs dues): 324 milliard marks (≈£10 million at current exchange)
- **Government expenditure** same period: 1,173 milliard marks (≈£40 million)
- Deficit made up by increasing floating debt with note issues amounting to nearly 850 milliards
- Very low levels in real terms showed how much finances of highly-industrialised nation of 60+ million had gone to pieces
- Inside country at Christmas: mark worth 1/1,723 of pre-war value
- Outside country: worth only 1/1,923

### Two Bright Patches

- Country's **internal debt**, to distress of stockholders, had dwindled to nothing
- Almost **total absence of unemployment** — but worklessness had been Socialist government's greatest fear ever since Army started to disband
- That fear had been in large measure behind the inflationary policy

### Bavaria's Conditions (End of 1922)

- Close of 1922: return to wartime conditions for most people in Bavaria
- People once more issued with bread and sugar cards, supplies doubly affected by extreme shortage of fuel
- Coal shortage attributed squarely to Allies' demands in kind made under peace treaty
- For these privations, fall of mark was official excuse — seldom believed, as prices seen to rise equally steeply during periods of temporary currency stability

### Bavaria Not Starving, But...

- **Mr. Seeds** observed: population not on verge of starvation
- Poorer quarters of English towns could have shown as many glaring cases of poverty
- Thought middle classes still hard up rather than poverty-stricken
- Out of population of 7 million, mere 16,000 were out of work
- **Bavaria became more than ever forcing house for reactionary movements**
- Progress of National Socialist Party during previous twelve months one of year's most remarkable features
- **Hitler's Storm Troops (SA)**, founded November 1921, numbered 6,000 within a year
- Permitted to train and manoeuvre alongside Reichswehr

### Rise of Hitler in Bavaria

- **Mr. Seeds** reported to Berlin Embassy: formerly, **NSDAP** existence only known through enormous red placards advertising public speeches by **Herr Hitler**, always closing with notice "No admission to Jews!"
- Anti-Semitism seemed chief plank in platform, but in general he was **anti-everything**: the Entente, the Reich government, the capitalists, the Bavarian government at times, the Socialists and the Communists — all depicted in eloquent language as betrayers of the people
- Public attitude at first: amusement
- As time went on and political and economic conditions grew from bad to worse, tendency arose to consider **Hitler as the man who was always in the right**

### The Middle Class Going Nazi

- Bit by bit, **Hitler's** star began to outshine **Ludendorff's** medals
- Economic salvation had become for most people the more pressing need
- They were being turned from politics by cost of living, poor wages, low salaries
- **Hitler alone was capable of trimming his ship to every wind**
- In a word, **the middle class was going Nazi**

### Germany's War Losses

- Result of war: Germany lost 9/10 of merchant fleet and all colonies
- Lost coal and zinc of Upper Silesia, potash of Alsace, iron ore of Lorraine
- Lost to France control of Saar mines
- Lost more than 14% of cultivated land — 15% of former wheat crops and 18% of potatoes
- All German capital held abroad confiscated

### Dr. Stresemann's Portrait of Germany

- Looking at it in worst light (as **Dr. Stresemann** happy to do as Chancellor later that year when appealing for overseas aid):
- Germany already **"an amputated corpse racked with bitterness, working only an eight-hour day"** when French and Belgian armies under **General Degoutte** moved in to claim missing telegraph poles on January 11

### The Ruhr's Strategic Importance

- Ruhr basin in 1923 provided nearly 85% of Germany's remaining coal resources
- Accounted for 80% of steel and pig-iron production
- Accounted for 70% of traffic in goods and minerals
- Contained 10% of population
- **Loss of Ruhr's production was therefore bale of last straws**
- At 35,000 to pound (Christmas 1922), mark fell to 48,000 day after invasion
- End of January 1923: touched 227,500 (well over 50,000 to dollar)

### First 100,000-Mark Note

- Reichsbank circulated its first 100,000-mark note at that moment
- Purchasing power equalled little more than two dollars or ten shillings sterling — perhaps 1/10 or 1/15 of what its face-value must have been when on drawing-board
- Didn't matter: **million-mark note was on the stocks and would be issued within another three weeks**

## 9: Ruhrkampf

### National Unity Against External Threat

- External threat will unite a disintegrating nation
- Entry of French and Belgian armies into Ruhr had galvanising effect on Germany
- **Tirpitz**: fate seemed to have assigned to France 'historic role of welding divergent forces of our people into unity again and again'
- Not only did all Germany rally at once to notion of supporting brothers on Rhine — socio-political fever in industrial areas itself subsided in torrent of national passion against common enemies

### Suspension of Class Hatred

- Sudden absence of class hatred was remarkable feature
- Helped by willingness of some industrialists (notably mine-owners and directors) to be arrested and imprisoned for non-cooperation along with their employees
- They became national heroes
- In Berlin, even Left-wing Independent Socialist Party happy to give temporary support to government of **Cuno**
- Indeed, 'revival of the national spirit' was matter for universal comment
- Only **Ludendorff** failed to cash in on new awakening
- Taking appeal for unity to Vienna where (though still in desperate poverty despite health of krone) people remembered which side their bread was buttered — greeted with shouts of 'To the gallows!' and 'Down with the murderer of millions!' — had to be smuggled back to own country

### Patriotic Response

> "All the old patriotic songs were sung. Even Father gave money to help the Ruhr. Clothes were collected. The coal shortage began. We had cold houses again, but we were willing to suffer cold for our fatherland." — **Erna von Pustau**

### French Military Occupation

- With absence (in prison or unoccupied part of country) of managerial staff of mines and forests, what had begun ostensibly as administrative operation quickly escalated into stark and often brutal military occupation
- Ruhr basin's Coal Syndicate replaced with Franco-Belgian officials
- Administration of forests, customs, export licences throughout newly occupied area taken over
- Customs cordon set up between Rhine-Ruhr and unoccupied Germany — all coal exports were prohibited
- Rail link between unoccupied Germany and Switzerland was cut
- French and Belgian personnel introduced to Ruhr state railways
- With these alien operatives, German workers would have little to do — former management and officials suffered accordingly

### Mass Expulsions and Casualties

- Within fortnight of January 11: mayors, lord mayors, customs officers at all levels, police directors and commissioners, local councillors, revenue officers being hounded out of jobs and homes
- Chief Commissioner of Forests dismissed, along with assistant commissioners at Cleve, Speyer, Mainz, Treves
- Director of Wiesbaden chief customs house replaced
- In protest at arrest of Mayor of Essen, all shops and restaurants in town closed in middle of day — until French forces started reprisals
- **During occupation:** 147,000 Germans actually expelled from Ruhr by **General Degoutte**
- Included 5,764 railway workers and 17,237 of their dependants
- More than 2,000 people wounded and 376 killed
- Every town in Germany as far east as Breslau was burdened with Ruhr refugees
- Apart from economic damage, Ruhr struggle added incalculably to already horrific sum of human misery

### Sabotage and Resistance

- Passive resistance not so passive as government genuinely intended
- **Sabotage of railways became popular pastime:**
  - Bridges, points, junctions dynamited at regular intervals
  - Signals jammed
  - Railway officials made point of losing or destroying freight waybills, particularly any relating to perishable goods which were subsequently pillaged
  - French military trains derailed and ships sunk in canals
  - No coal flowed westwards except at sporadic intervals

### Reactionary Movements Emerge

- With wave of nationalism that swept through Germany after French invasion, reactionary movements hurried out into open with tacit support of German Army and financial encouragement from industrialists
- **National Socialists**, **Deutsche National Volkische Partei**, and **Fascisti organisations** made huge capital out of patriotism
- **Hitler** appeared personally in Ruhr on recruiting drive — played as large part as any in arranging disruption of area
- Most movements, notably **'Orgesch'** (known to be supported by **Stinnes**), had strong military and student backing, based in Bavaria
- However, disaffected and out-of-work in Ruhr did their share of discouraging forces of occupation
- Even instances of well-paid workers from rest of country (such was chauvinistic fervour which **Ruhrkampf** excited) who would spend annual holidays on jaunts to Ruhr with object of shooting French officer or blowing up supply train

### French and Belgian Retaliation

- French and Belgians arrested, gaoled and executed
- Diplomatically both they and German government worked themselves into impasse from which extrication without loss of face became impossible
- Russian agents (as might have been expected) began to pour into Ruhr
- In general found flood of paper money which accompanied them more than match for weasel words of Bolshevism (at least in beginning)
- By March, Russian propaganda in Ruhr ceased because Soviets didn't want to appear unsympathetic to popular distress
- In contrast, French then started to act in collusion with local Communists to undermine German authorities
- This stimulation by France of **Rote Hundertschaften** ('Red Centuries') operating in Rhine-Ruhr echoed policy German High Command had adopted six years before in shipping Lenin off in sealed train to Petrograd during war to hasten disintegration of Czarist Russia

### Munich's Patriotic Demonstrations

- Munich distinguished itself from rest of Germany by rigid adherence for several months to manifestations of mourning and indignation inaugurated with first day of occupation
- No dancing in public or private permitted, despite losses suffered by those classes whose livelihoods depended on such things
- No Frenchman could show himself with impunity in restaurant, shop or other public place (practice in respect of which Berlin was far more lenient)
- Moreover (**Mr. Seeds** reported), perpetual singing of **'Deutschland über Alles'** often entailed savage assaults on any foreigners who (by inadvertence or boredom) failed to rise to their feet

### Government's Monetary Programme

- Committed to monetary programme of unlimited printing, government and Reichsbank fully recognised that if mark's value continued to sink forever, days in which Ruhr population could be sustained in idleness must be very short
- For that reason, by middle of February large amounts of foreign bills being thrown onto market at home and abroad by Reichsbank to support rate of exchange
- Policy immediately made possible by government's having suspended reparation payments for duration of hostilities
- As excess paper mopped up, price of mark rose sharply
- By February 20: recovered by more than half, moving from 50,000 to dollar to 20,000
- One encouraging consequence: favourable reaction in wholesale prices
- One distressing consequence: correspondingly severe fall on Bourse (as every speculative calculation went wildly wrong)

### Reichsbank Printing Accelerates

- Main reminder that sanity had not even thought of returning: appearance of more and more paper from Reichsbank presses
- During February, note circulation being increased by matter of 450 milliards every week
- On single day in early March, by way of Treasury bills discounted at Reichsbank, floating debt increased by 800 milliards

### Criticism of Reichsbank Credit Policy

- Anomaly of currency temporarily stable on world market and roaring inflation at home (accompanied by usual price increases) did not go unremarked
- **Berliner Tageblatt** roundly condemned Reichsbank credit policy for 'giving advantage to individuals at expense of community by clinging to fiction of paper mark which has long ceased to be reservoir or even measure of value'
- Main reference: continuing tendency of industrial and other concerns (partly to avoid taxation but more so as not to hold marks) to put every spare mark into extensions, renewals or improvements
- Practice which for many months French had been watching with mounting disapproval, unable to reconcile it with Germany's protestations of national poverty

### Mark Holds Position (March-April 1923)

- Nevertheless, mark maintained position at just under 100,000 to pound throughout March and first two weeks of April
- Survived further incursion of French Army on March 13 across Rhine to occupy parts of Mannheim, Karlsruhe and Darmstadt
- News that Japanese placing new shipbuilding contracts in Britain rather than Hamburg
- Survived collapse of franc which (at between 20-25 to pound before war) now sank from 66 to 77, relieving French rentiers of another sixth of their purchasing power
- Survived troubles accompanying suppression of Bavarian separatist plot in Munich
- Worries repeatedly expressed in Reichstag about manoeuverings of 8,000 troops under direction of **Herr Hitler** in same town
- Even survived announcement of budget deficit of 7,000 milliard marks (≈£70 million, about four times January level) which (as everybody knew) only printing would make good

### Leipzig Spring Fair Disappointment

- Leipzig Spring Fair (held early April despite country's troubles) was disappointment to exporters
- Very reason that export prices now too high to get orders
- Because of mark's stability on foreign exchanges, inland prices often higher than export prices when expressed in foreign currencies
- Wild fluctuations in mark's value over previous months when goods actually being manufactured meant extraordinary price differences throughout fair — amounting to as much as 60% for same type of wares
- Only products in which traders could hope to prosper: those like toys and fine mechanical instruments where Germany still enjoyed something of monopoly
- German leather goods, glass and crystal now being severely undercut by United Kingdom

### German Production Shifts to Low-Class Goods

- Visitors to fair found German firms seemed to be concentrating upon large quantities of low-class goods
- Inference: production ensured maximum employment, would meet greatly reduced inland purchasing power, and in addition gratify Germans' need and urge to get rid of all their paper money
- Average citizen these days preferred buying three pairs of indifferent leather boots to buying one good pair
- At fair he was being offered mouth organs at equivalent of 17s a dozen, or concertinas at half a guinea each
- His was becoming in many respects **a cheapjack country**

### Government Loan Attempt Fails

- Could only be matter of time before Bank's capacity to support currency ran out
- Government attempted to raise gold loan with issue of dollar Treasury bonds (repayable at 120% three years later)
- Found that after all people preferred to hold on to any foreign currency they had
- When first official results of loan announced in last days of March: turned out to be still under-subscribed by 75%
- Lack of confidence this news engendered led to demand for foreign currencies greater than ever before
- Not until April 18 when **Hugo Stinnes** presented Reichsbank with demand for £93,000 in foreign bills that intervention policy came to grief
- Support withdrawn
- Mark broke
- Decided to let exchange find more realistic level
- Within twenty-four hours mark was at 140,000 to pound, and still sliding

### Lord D'Abernon on Inflation

> "Inflation is like a drug in more ways than one. It is fatal in the end, but it gets its votaries over many difficult moments." — **Lord D'Abernon**

- Hopelessly addicted, Reichsbank ploughed on
- Foreign currency holdings failed to keep mark steady while more and more paper notes gushed forth day upon day
- Gold reserves thrown into breach as well
- March: stood at 1,004 million gold marks (equivalent to just over £50 million)
- By middle of May: one-fifth of them had gone (good money after bad) — at time, moreover, when those reserves would almost certainly still have been sufficient basis for issue of stable currency

### Gold Reserves Dwindle

- From spring onwards, gold reserves dwindled away
- Not exclusively in support of mark (much spent on essential imports of food and British coal)
- More and more desperate attempts made to control market in foreign exchange
- Such intervention as sporadically took place thereafter to stem fall of currency contrived at best to brake its descent for few days at time
- Almost invariably these attempts made it easier for speculators to pick up foreign currencies at artificially low prices
- Regulation in May requiring banks to report in detail any purchases of foreign currency made on behalf of clients was simply tinkering with one of inflation's natural side-effects
- Three dozen or so separate ordinances to follow (governing buying, selling, even casual holding of foreign money) did little more than hamper normal workings of commerce

### Separatist Movement Threat

- Prices went up
- Although no weakening of resolve in country at large or in Ruhr in particular to continue enfeebling struggle with France, morale began to sink (especially in Rhineland)
- If small Francophile party there had then decided under French backing to proclaim Rhenish Republic, most of population would probably have closed eyes and accepted situation
- Separatist movement gave Communists opportunity to stir up trouble all way from Essen to Frankfort
- Flood of refugees into unoccupied Germany increased in size — caused there as many economic and social problems as they thought they had left behind

### Labour Unrest and May Day Incidents

- Labour leaders who stayed at home now beginning to demand work in lieu of increasingly inadequate dole
- With May Day, when **Hitler's** attempt to use stormtroopers to break up traditional trade union demonstration in Munich (if possible force Reich into civil war) was thwarted by local Reichswehr commandant **von Lossow**, mark dropped past 200,000 to pound
- **Curzon's endeavour** to break Ruhr deadlock by appealing to Germany to make new offer in respect of reparation payments came to nothing

### Ernest Hemingway's Return to Kehl

- **Ernest Hemingway** returned to Kehl in late April, fortified by visa obtained from German consular attaché in Paris with aid of bribe
- Since year before, little Rhineland town had been transformed

> "The waiter sat down at the table. 'No, there is no one here now. All the people you saw here in July cannot come now. The French will not give them passports to come to Germany … The merchants and restaurant keepers in Strasbourg got angry and went to the police because everybody was coming over here to eat so much cheaper and now nobody in Strasbourg can get a passport to come here … Now no Germans can get passports to go across the river to Strasbourg where many worked. They could work cheaper than the French, so that is what happened to them. All our factories here are shutdown. No coal, no trains. This was one of the biggest and busiest stations in Germany. Now nix. No trains, except the military trains, and they run when they please … We haven't had any fun since 1914. If you made any money it gets no good, and there is only to spend, it. That is what we do. Last year I had enough money saved up to buy a *Gasthaus* at Hernberg: now that money wouldn't buy four bottles of Champagne.'"

- **Hemingway** recorded for **Toronto Daily Star** that Champagne then cost 38,000 marks a bottle, luncheon 3,500 marks, sandwich 900 marks, beer 350 marks a stein

> "I remembered that last July I stayed at a de luxe hotel with Mrs Hemingway for 600 marks a day. 'Sure,' the waiter went on, 'I read the French papers. Germany debases her money to cheat the Allies. But what do I get out of it?'"

### Who Benefits from Inflation?

- Answer: waiter got nothing out of inflation
- Apart from relieving itself of further minute proportion of remaining minute fraction of national debt — nor now did Exchequer
- There were those, however, who were doing better than ever
- **Currency speculator** who borrowed from Reichsbank on January 1, 1923, enough paper marks (about 1,980 million) to buy 100,000 dollars, and on April 1 sold enough dollars (about 80,000) to repay bank, and who again borrowed equivalent of 100,000 dollars and continued thus until end of May, could have made equivalent of quarter of million dollars at expense of acceptors of pure marks
- His problem: in what form to keep his profits — if in marks, they would evaporate before his eyes

### Government Revenue Crisis

- That evaporation was inevitable
- March, April and May: government's income was mere 30% of its expenditure
- During May: working classes actually paid more to Reich in tax than assessed tax payers of higher social classes
- Reason: former could be tapped at source, others had to fill in returns which were long out of date by time administrative machine could deal with them
- Between May Day and May 31: mark fell from 220,000 to 320,000 to pound
- First of June celebrated with issue of **first five-million-mark note**

### Currency Speculation Becomes Mass Phenomenon

- Speculation in currency was in no way exclusive domain of financially informed
- Anyone (banker, politician, businessman or workman) who observed there were easier ways of keeping one's head above water than now very problematic one of working for it was ready to indulge as opportunity offered
- Computed that well over million Germans in early 1923 engaged in exchange speculation
- Dealings took place mainly through so-called **Winkelbankiers** (back-street operators)
- Had sprung up with inflation and (battening on unhealthy economy) made living entirely through taking advantage of difference in buying and selling prices of foreign currencies
- Although not even members of Bourse, they played significant part in determining daily rate of exchange
- Indeed, to arbitrage machinations of **Winkelbankiers** was attributed fact that Berlin invariably closed at lower rate than New York

### Small Reforms, Massive Unemployment Arrives

- By end of May 1923: no single reform, possibly no half dozen measures, would have been enough to avert ultimate disaster
- Small reforms made:
  - Law passed on May 19 to liquidate holdings of Government stock of less than 5,000 marks (cost too much to administer)
  - 920,000 holders of War Loan alone who had paid up to £250 to help war effort were compelled to accept nominal value (at most, 6d) for their stock
  - Minister of Interior permitted substitution of paste-board coffins for wooden ones (especially for rising number of pauper funerals)
- Otherwise, Government contented itself with steps to postpone inevitable

### Inflationist Policy After Ruhr Invasion

- Until Ruhr invasion, inflationist policy mainly governed by fear of unemployment
- Now massive unemployment had come — although revival of national spirit had greatly mitigated its worst disruptive side-effects
- Inflation pursued more vigorously than ever
- As Ruhr unemployment was fully subsidised, it had no corresponding countervailing influence on huge additional wage claims there or anywhere else
- Conjointly minds of Berlin turned more earnestly towards reforming tax system
- To great degree meant persuading **Stinnes** and friends to make real fiscal contributions to Exchequer
- June: of 511 milliard marks received in income tax, only 90 milliards came from assessed tax payers — wage-earners' prepayments accounted for rest
- **Stinnes** increasingly seen to be maleficent influence on Germany's finances
- Exchequer's only joy that month: increased yield from Bourse turnover tax (which doubled because of new rush of orders to buy German securities)

### Petty Crime and Barter Economy

- **Petty crime** (crime of desperation) was flourishing
- Pilfering had been rife since war, but now began to occur on larger, commercial scale
- Metal plaques on national monuments had to be removed for safe-keeping
- Brass bell plates stolen from front doors of British Embassy in Berlin (part of systematic campaign unpreventable by police even in Wilhelmstrasse and Unter den Linden)
- That members and families of British Army of Rhine suffered severely from burglaries probably reflected fact that thieves had particular animus against forces of occupation, but that these days foreigners were so much more robbable than anyone else
- Over most of Germany, lead beginning to disappear overnight from roofs
- Petrol syphoned from tanks of motor cars
- **Barter already usual form of exchange**
- Now commodities such as bread and fuel were becoming currency of ordinary purchase and payment
- Cinema seat cost lump of coal
- With bottle of paraffin one might buy shirt — with that shirt, potatoes needed by one's family
- **Herr von der Osten** kept girlfriend in provincial capital — for whose room in 1922 he had paid half pound of butter a month — by summer of 1923 it was costing him whole pound
- **'The Middle Ages came back,' said Erna von Pustau**

> "Communities printed their own money, based on goods, on a certain amount of potatoes, or rye, for instance. Shoe factories paid their workers in bonds for shoes which they could exchange at the bakery for bread or the meat market for meat."

- Those with foreign currency (becoming easily most acceptable paper medium) had greatest scope for finding bargains
- Power of dollar in particular far exceeded its nominal rate of exchange
- Finding himself with single dollar bill early in 1923, **von der Osten** got hold of six friends and went to Berlin one evening determined to blow the lot
- Early next morning (long after dinner and many nightclubs later) they still had change in their pockets
- Stories of Americans in greatest difficulties in Berlin because no-one had enough marks to change five-dollar bill
- Stories of others who ran up accounts (to be paid off later in depreciated currency) on strength of even bigger foreign notes which (after meals or services had been obtained) could not be changed
- Stories of foreign students who bought up whole rows of houses out of their allowances

### Inflation Anecdotes and Reality

- Stories of shoppers who found thieves had stolen baskets and suitcases in which they carried their money, leaving money itself behind on ground
- Stories of life supported by selling every day or so single tiny link from long gold crucifix chain
- Stories (many of them, as summer wore on and as exchange rates altered several times a day) of restaurant meals which cost more when bills came than when they were ordered
- **5,000-mark cup of coffee would cost 8,000 marks by time it was drunk**

### The Grim Reality

- Reality behind such inflationary anecdotes (amusing in retrospect) was exceedingly grim
- Agony displayed as much by shrunken-necked gentlemen to be seen in streets with their mended white collars and shiny suits saved from war as by exhausted workmen queueing impatiently outside pay windows with big shopping bags in which to rush their wages away to shops
- Badly off as wage-earners were, their standards were still at level distantly comparable with past
- Throughout Germany, Austria and Hungary, old standards of salary earners, pensioners and people living on savings had often dropped almost out of sight

### Lady Listowel's Budapest Testimony

- **Lady Listowel** (whose father held senior post in Hungarian diplomatic service) recalls distress among circle of family's friends in Budapest:

> "One used to see the appearance of their flats gradually changing. One remembered where there used to be a picture, or a carpet, or a secretaire. Eventually their rooms would be almost empty - and on paper some people were reduced to nothing. In practice, people didn't just die. They were terribly hungry, and relations and friends would help with a little food from time to time. We sent them parcels, or took them ourselves because we had no cash to pay for postage. And some of them begged - not in the streets - but by
<!-- pp. 141-160 -->

## June 1923: The Mark Collapses

### Daily Life Under Hyperinflation

- Families struggled with appearance maintenance — early on, people economized on luxuries and club memberships; later it became about necessities
- Medical care became unaffordable without money — dentists, hospitals inaccessible
- Only one family member could afford Budapest trips at a time
- Rural living provided some food security, but monetary poverty created other crises

### Price Explosions After May 20

- **Egg**: 800 → 2,400 marks
- **Liter of milk**: 1,800 → 3,800 marks
- **Kilo of flour**: 2,400 → 6,600 marks
- **Pork**: 10,400 → 32,000 marks
- In the Ruhr, salaries doubled (3,300 → 6,800/hour) while commodity costs trebled
- Tradesmen couldn't establish prices, many simply shut their shops

### The Reichsbank's Failed Interventions

- June support for the mark resumed "to allay popular discontent which was assuming alarming proportions"
- Single day in June: **6 million gold marks lost** from reserves in futile currency market intervention
- **Joseph Addison** described it as attempting "to bolster the mark by throwing foreign currency on the market — in this case with the object of bringing the dollar below 100,000"
- Mid-June: note circulation at **8,564 milliard marks**
- June 21: daily circulation increase of **157 milliards**
- June 28: mark at **170,000 to the dollar**, total circulation **11,000 milliards**, minimum denomination **100,000 marks**

### The Absurdity of Paper Money Growth

- June 26-27: circulation increased by **1,523,534,460,000 marks in one day**
- **Addison** quoted Mephistopheles from *Faust*: "The little God of the World remains always of the same stamp, And is as wunderlich as on the first day"
- One day's increase in floating debt (1,500 milliards) exceeded total May revenue (1,400 milliards)

### The Taxation System Collapses

- Government expenditure in two months: equivalent of **£15.5 million** against revenue of **£5 million** (sterling terms)
- Real burden: nation of 60 million couldn't raise £30 million/year to meet £80 million expenditure
- **The multiplier** — Minister of Finance's tool to adjust taxation with depreciation
- Income tax multiplied 25 times in May; announcement that August multiplier would be 40
- But tax returns could never keep pace with depreciation speed
- Consumption duties (tobacco, beer, wine, sugar, salt, playing cards) no longer covered their own administration costs
- **Dr. Hermes** (Finance Minister) argued correctly that raising duties to "normal world levels" offered "no financial guarantee for the future" — despair was his keynote

### Government Policy Shifts

- Second half of June: doubled government salaries, increased grants to war-wounded, widows, pensioners, unemployed
- **Umlage** policy ended — forced delivery of first 2 million tons wheat annually at cheap prices
- From August: farmers paid world prices because they still paid world prices for fertilizers when forced to sell cheaply
- Policy shift: from subsidizing food to subsidizing the needy (but extra subsidies soon became worthless again)

### Crackdown on Currency Speculation

- Third week June: ordinance to control foreign currency speculation — fixed legal exchange rates
- Penalties: unlimited fines, up to three years' gaol
- Aimed at **Winkelbankiers** who could no longer profit before official quotation
- Required to ensure German industry had enough foreign currency for the month
- **Rhineland High Commission refused to adopt ordinance** — huge transactions continued in Cologne, depressing the mark further
- **General Degoutte** declared it inapplicable in Ruhr, accused Germans of "wilfully debasing the mark" by forbidding a strengthening move
- July 2: dollar opened in New York at **174,000 paper marks**, closed in Berlin at **160,000** under Reichsbank influence — Bank selling dollars at 160,000 knowing dollar was worth 14,000 more points abroad

### The Futures Ban and Dollar Arbitrage

- July 3: new ordinance forbidding buying of futures (restricting imports — stocks were very high)
- Bourse overloaded with demands for "sight" bills rather than three-month bills — only 1/10 could be satisfied
- Importers began applying for 10x the dollars required, hoping to get full quota
- Arbitrage opportunity: buy dollars at 160,000 marks, use them to buy dollar Treasury bills quoted much higher — obvious great gains
- Over-ordering exposed smaller banks condoning exchange speculation when Reichsbank called their bluff by requiring cheques for total application

### Havenstein's Defiance and Gold Reserve Depletion

- **Dr. Havenstein** (Reichsbank president) believed Berlin must keep mark exchange low "whatever it might do elsewhere"
- Autonomy Act of May 1922 convinced him he was master in his own house — no intention of resigning despite mounting pressures
- Last days June/first days July: mark sank 600,000 → 800,000 to pound
- Nearly **80 million gold marks (£2 million)** thrown away to satisfy German speculators' greed
- Only **1 million gold marks** used for the "laudable purpose" of supporting mark in New York
- By July 10: Germany's free gold reserve fallen to equivalent of **£35 million pounds**
- Week ending July 14: another **50 million gold marks lost** — direct result of supporting paper mark by rationing foreign currencies and covering imports from gold reserve

### Bankruptcy Arithmetic

- If intervention continued at 10 million gold marks daily: **bankruptcy within 60 days**
- If intervention ceased: expectations were dollar → 1 million marks, pound → over 4 million, end of July fulfillment
- Merchants borrowing paper marks at **80% of stock value**, exchanging at Bank for dollar Treasury bills ostensibly for imports — bills sent abroad to buying agencies, in most cases stayed there with no countervalue returning to Germany

### Complacency and Delusion

- **Herr Schroeder** (Finance Under-Secretary): 8,000 milliard marks discounted in June = only £10 million sterling, "hardly excessive seeing that the country was in a state of war"
- July 19: Reichsbank suddenly suspended discounting trade paper, refused to sacrifice more gold reserve
- Ordinary import trade came to standstill — very hard to finance coal and food imports (coal desperately needed for railways)

### The Banking Crisis

- July 19: demands on Reichsbank from other banks equalled **entire paper circulation in country**
- Exchange Department manager produced only **1/4 of 1%** of total demand — banks rejected as inadequate
- Two days later: Reichsbank relented, issued **5% of demand** — resumed discounting interior trade bills
- End of July: Reichsbank had only **£25 million in gold left**
- Government attempts to raise loan abroad (London) met with: nothing available until Germany's finances in order

## July 1923: Political and Social Disintegration

### Nationalist Spirit vs. National Collapse

- Diverging tendencies throughout Germany — bewilderment and depression afflicted all levels
- Among lower German officials (loyal to government because fortunes linked): **extremely nationalist spirit developed**
- Politically impossible for any government to consider giving up passive resistance in Ruhr
- Coalition losing support rapidly everywhere else
- **Germania newspaper** (leading Centre): July 27 announced confidence in administration "now completely shattered" — anger "universal," general feeling "that of the Ninth of November" (1918 Republic proclamation day)

> "The Wirth government was accused of wobbling [*Germania* said] but the Cuno government makes no movement at all. They stand still. Beyond a few ordinances, such as controlling the consumption of meat in restaurants, and occasional speeches, they remain passive."

- Huge sums for passive resistance provided by printing press
- Credits issued to industrial circles — extent used for hoarding foreign bills unknown
- **Policy of fulfilment only partly responsible** — first symptom was **Rathenau murder**

> "The real collapse of our currency began when it became evident that certain industrial circles were more powerful than the government."

### Working Population Loses Patience

- Withdrawal of 1,000 mark note (July) — worth barely 1/3 penny — an "unhappy loss"
- Highest denomination since 1876, repudiated because rumours of revalorisation at old gold rate
- Also disappeared because producing low-currency notes required more working time (paper-makers, engineers, printers, lithographers, colour experts, packers) than value of finished article
- Fourth week July: new denominations introduced — **10, 20, and 50 million marks**

### Strikes, Riots, and Civil Unrest

- Workers demanded higher wages and **daily payment** so income wouldn't lose spending power
- Repeated strikes, disorders, demonstrations across Germany
- Possibility of civil war openly discussed, "frenziedly denied by the government"
- July 20-21 **Breslau**: thousand arrests after riots and plundering, organized Communist bands prowling streets
- July 24 **Frankfort**: demonstrations against profiteering, capitalism, Fascism — inoffensive citizens molested, windows broken, one man kicked to death
- Berlin: open air meetings forbidden, but **10,000 demonstrated** in Leipzig, **5,000 in Dresden**
- Last week of July: demonstrators killed in Bavarian town of **Rosenheim** and in **Potsdam**
- Ship-building strikes in Hamburg, pilots' strike in Kiel canal

### Communist Influence and the Red Centuries

- Pattern continued through August — armed strikers killing police at Wilhelmsburg, throwing them into water at Hamburg
- Basic wage dispute inevitably out of date by time negotiated and paid
- Some troubles Communist-inspired, others not particularly so
- **1922 Third International** policy in Germany: restricted to gaining influence with workers by exploiting serious economic situation
- May 1923: rising in Ruhr considered again, but "generally now it was felt that the time was not yet"
- **Rote Hundertschaften** (Red Centuries) — organised bodies of Socialist workmen, Soviet agents among them, whose purpose was to supplement the police
- Probably **30,000 strong in Saxony** vs. **11,500 in police force**
- Dangerous from national viewpoint, but some saw them as neutralising reactionary societies
- Combustible material — Saxon factories pricing themselves out of business, foreign orders reduced, short-time working and unemployment spreading

### Wage Indexation Agreement

- Beginning of July: agreement between Minister of Finance and trade union committee to relate wages by indexation to cost of living
- Weekly wage adjustment (as well as daily payments) to maintain value
- Adjustment applied equally to **Leistungslohn** (efficiency wage) and **Soziallohn** (social wage covering extra-family allowances)
- Negotiation of **Reallohn** (real wages = increased payments based on gold mark) to be regarded as separate
- In practice: wage rises always **15 days in arrears** of cost of living rises
- New adaptations received at end of each 15-day wage period, basic wage received at start
- Great saving to Exchequer as mark's rate mounted: 800,000 (July 7) → 900,000 (July 14) → 1,600,000 (July 23) → 5,000,000 or 21 million to dollar on last day of month

### Lord Curzon's Pressure and German Ambassador's Plea

- **Lord Curzon** described "this extraordinary and almost incredible fall in the value of the mark" bringing acute food crisis
- German Ambassador in London pressed to use influence to secure long-requested loan for Germany's essential fuel and food imports
- France still titularly Britain's ally — Curzon unable to accede
- Confined refusal to asking whether intention was that Reichsbank's printing presses would cease work
- Ambassador had no answer to why latest tax measures hadn't been tried before
- Ambassador's memorandum to Curzon (couched in terms *Germania* might approve):

> "It is an ominous sign that the mark following its latest tremendous collapse [*nach ihrem letzen ungeheuren Sturz*] is now beginning to lose its purchasing power in internal trade also. At the same time the Reichsbank no longer has sufficient foreign currency to make it possible for industry and for the State to procure abroad the necessities of life, especially coal and food. The dreary foreign outlook together with the destruction of the currency and the resulting chaos in the whole economic structure have produced the result that the population are beginning to lose confidence in the State and in themselves. Distrust of the depreciating currency is driving goods from the market, while the late harvest has produced an exceptionally alarming scarcity of foodstuffs in the towns, especially Berlin. The desperation of the masses is being exploited by radical agitators from both Left and Right."

### The Wheat Crisis and Failed British Loan

- Wheat crop had been rather good, especially in Saxony
- Scarcity caused by **farmers' refusal to accept paper** for produce
- Government's only policy: borrow at maximum rate to pay wages in Ruhr
- Independent Reichsbank fueling folly (Havenstein and directorate more wrong-headed than government)
- No loan possible — Britain already stung by agreeing to part with **£12 million to aid Austria** earlier that year
- Phenomenal mark fall in last days of July caused grave embarrassment to government

### The Reality of Currency Collapse

- German Ambassador's complaint that mark losing internal purchasing power "becoming ever more real"
- For present, traders' disinclination to accept Reichsbanknotes could theoretically be countered by multiplying quantity and denominations
- Practice: harder than ever to supply banks with enough money for business on traditional lines
- From Dresden to Coblenz (end of July): new high denomination notes awaited anxiously

### Fiscal Breakdown

- July 11-20: floating debt increased **28,000 → 40,000 milliard marks** — daily issue (excluding Sundays) of **2,000 milliards**
- Taxation system entirely broken down
- Living day to day, government didn't seem to care
- Of 12,000 milliard marks expenditure in those few days: only **4%** from taxation — just over 500 milliards, not even enough to cover interest (570 milliards) on debt for same period

### Railway Finances and Austria Comparison

- Appalling figures foretaste of following weeks' chaos
- Ruhr railways (once providing 1/3 of Germany's revenue from Ruhr): now accounted for **1/5 of her outgoings** in wages and doles
- **"Wir schiessen," a high official told British Ambassador, "dieselben Böcke wie die Österreicher"** — "We shoot the same goats as the Austrians"
- August 1-10: floating debt almost doubled
- During those 10 days: government's general administrative expenditure rose to **40,000 milliards** — somewhat greater than total nominal expenditure during first four months of year

## Austria's Contrasting Recovery

### The Geneva Protocols Success

- Austria's situation very different since autumn when **Dr. Zimmermann** took financial control and **Geneva Protocols** approved by National Assembly
- Germany might look at neighbour with awe — Austria undergoing "full throes of the exorcism of the devil of inflation, and it was plainly the most unpleasant process"

### Austrian Unemployment and Social Crisis

- Christmas warning: necessary reforms couldn't be achieved without hardship and sacrifice
- Victims of recovery would be "hardly less severely selected than those of the inflation"
- August 1922 official dole figure: **21,000** (substantially underestimated real unemployment, ignored short-time working)
- October 1922 - February 1922 progression: **38,000 → 58,000 → 83,000 → 117,000 → 161,000**
- Over half the workless in **Vienna itself** — February meant **more than 100,000 idle men** receiving maximum dole of **87,360 paper kronen** (about 5s./week)
- Dangerous concentration embracing both working and official classes in politically divided city where class war still popular topic

### Government Sector Dependence

- About **1/5 of population** dependent on government money for salaries or pensions
- Railways had **two ex-employees pensioners for every three workers** still on staff
- Although deadwood not properly cut away until towards end 1923 under external guidance, railway finances were crux of budgetary deficit
- Essential economies started at once in public and private sectors — redundancies and dismissals in both
- Stabilisation brought Austrian manufacturer face to face with reality — serious industrial depression setting in
- Stagnation affecting iron, wood, paper, leather industries and manufacture of metal, machinery, shoes, furniture
- First bankruptcies spawned by inflation beginning

### Banking Sector Crisis

- Concealed overstaffing coming to light
- January 1923: leading Vienna banks had **one official for every £2,000 of total reserves and deposits** vs. **one for every £18,000 in London**
- Partly due to compulsory extra work for foreign exchange office and tax authorities
- Also banks finding it impossible to administer except at prohibitive cost great number of smaller, older accounts reduced to value of few pre-war pfennigs — some cases less than value of paper they were written on
- Savings banks catering for small saver and hoping to restore confidence particularly badly affected

### Civil Service Reductions

- Public sector dismissals governed by public expenditure cuts called for by **Dr. Zimmermann's office**
- Generally came after sackings in private industry — government slow to implement directives
- Those last axed were first, almost those with no political connections
- Unfortunate consequence: by end 1923, **administrative efficiency had seriously declined**
- Civil service hardly less overmanned than railways
- Senior, more experienced civil servants were those who had traditionally kept politics at arm's length

### Economic Recovery Signs (March 1923 onwards)

- Unemployment (reached nearly 170,000 in March) began to fall substantially and regularly
- Dropping in August to as low as **84,000 (53,000 in Vienna)**
- **Krone remained rock-steady**
- For best part of year, already more stable against dollar than any other currency in Europe — solid foundation for confidence
- Deposits accumulating in savings banks
- When long-term international loan floated June 1, 1923: **huge and immediate success**
- Austria's budget to be balanced ahead of Zimmermann schedule, whole loan never called up
- Striking increase in demand for Austrian stocks and shares — index doubled December 1922 - May 1923, increased **400% during the year**
- Development reflected general confidence more than tangible economic benefit — speculation in undervalued shares absorbed domestic capital that might have gone to productive purposes

### Unemployment Trough and Ruhrkampf Benefit

- Lowest point of Austria's official unemployment: **79,000 in November 1923** (still nearly 4x pre-stabilisation number)
- After November: planned redundancies in civil service (*Volkswehr*, postal services, railways) began to have real impact on labour position
- Comparatively promising situation mid-1923 largely due to increase in Austrian trade from **Ruhrkampf**
- Foreign orders for certain goods switched from Germany to Austria — even a little of Germany's business would go a long way

### Civil Service Purge Reality

- Dismissal of **23,000+ officials** from State service October-December 1923: much truer gauge of belt-tightening
- Strikes were few because strike policy (with or without union support) obviously suicidal when everyone losing jobs and employees easily/cheaply replaced
- Official target: cut of **100,000 State jobs** by end 1924
- Unions well aware autumn 1923 that programme of government officials reduction was falling badly behind

### Foreign Confidence Returns, But Austrian Misery Continues

- Satisfactory that foreign confidence returned in full measure to this European financial oasis maintained and guaranteed by the Allies
- Austria's economy (public and private) obviously reorganising along correct lines
- Yet hardly considerations allowing Austrian people much scope for rejoicing — greatly as general atmosphere of uncertainty and gloom of 1922 had improved
- From January 1923 onwards, despite *Ruhrkampf* effect on European economy, **cost of living began to creep upwards** — continued throughout year, adding **3% in August alone**
- By December 1923: only attained once more previous highest level of September 1922 (after which came 20% drop)
- Rise took place in face of higher taxes which more people than ever had to pay

### Price Increases Despite Reforms

- Government found it particularly unfortunate that prices (in line with world prices) went on rising while necessary reforms and reductions were taking place
- As early as May: questioned whether possible at all to maintain law and order at same time as budgetary equilibrium

### Workers Oppose Index System Abolition

- Not surprising workers persisted in opposing abolition of index system under which wages couldn't be reduced until index had fallen in two consecutive months
- Factory worker now relatively better off than most, in some cases better off than before war
- Wages lower than anywhere else in Europe except Germany
- In country with great excess of educated men, difference in average rewards between manual and intellectual workers had become very small
- Wages of skilled mechanic often exceeded those of factory manager (who himself received many times those of government official)

### Social Misery Despite Financial Soundness

- Financial picture sound, economy improving, but **social picture far from happy**
- Classes who had already endured much well understood far harder time might be on the way
- Those whom index had somewhat protected began to experience chiller winds — partly because until stabilisation hardly knew how poor they'd become
- Days of subsidies and doles over
- People with no work more penurious than ever — spending time searching notice-boards and newspapers for non-existent jobs
- State officials remaining on national pay-roll: on average in 1923 received **1/4 of their 1914 spending power**
- State pensioners received **1/3 in real terms** of what had been little enough before war

### Housing Crisis in Vienna

- Most people lived in flats — only very rich had houses they could afford to keep in repair
- Because rents kept so low (**rent restriction habitually one of first and cheapest government devices to restrain cost of living under inflation**), flats themselves in short supply
- Even had Viennese municipality been well-disposed toward landlord: couldn't be ignored most middle class would have been entirely unable to afford economic rents of up to **20,000 times pre-war figure**
- Though unable to raise rents, many landlords at least had consolation their mortgage payments no more than nominal burden — consideration long since dismayed depositors and mortgageholders of mortgage banks
- Under such circumstances: no new buildings at all put up by private developers, most virtually expropriated
- **More than 42,000 families** waiting for **6,000 or so dwellings** local authorities built in Vienna each year
- Shortage and regulation whereby local authorities (not landlords) decided who would go into any empty flat led to great deal of jobbing and corruption

### Political Division and Class Struggle

- Period of Austrian rehabilitation: great popular suffering, continuing class and group hatred, political struggle
- State and municipal government of Vienna appeared to compete to tax Austrian industry — so much of which centred in capital — to utmost
- State (in order to repay interest on foreign loans), latter (whose activities free from League control) in order to pursue interests of political supporters in working classes
- Whether or not charge just that Socialists controlling Vienna did little more than hang doctrinaire reforms around Republic's neck — "actively concerned in the pleasing process" (*Germains* wrote) "of converting middle-class incomes into doles for workers" — no doubt party politics continued to rend country in two when unity was crying need

### The Failed Experiment Metaphor

> Austria's reconstruction was compared to the experiment made by the gipsy to teach his horse to do without food. When he got it down to a straw a day, the horse died.

<!-- pp. 161-180 -->

## Chapter 11: Havenstein

### The Collapse of Passive Resistance

- **Cuno Cabinet falls**: In an avalanche of paper marks and crashing exchange rates,
  the Cuno Cabinet fell under pressure from **Curzon's Note** stating France had no
  right to be in the Ruhr. Replaced by **Dr. Gustav Stresemann**, leader of the
  constitutional, anti-socialist businessmen's **Volkspartei** (business party).

- **Political atmosphere**: Stresemann inherits a nation unable to forget financial
  anarchy. The **Right** suspects him of following a Socialist line; **Communists and
  patriotic organisations** become less ruly than ever. Fear that Stresemann's
  appointment signals end to passive resistance and capitulation to France, bringing
  **Hitler** within an ace of welding reactionary forces into unity.

- **Military coup whispers**: Anti-Hitler Communist disturbances in Stettin, Lübeck,
  and other towns; labour riots across Germany. From Stettin, warning of a planned
  dictatorship in Pomerania, East Prussia, and Bavaria with **Ludendorff** as leader
  and **Hitler** as Bavarian deputy — monarchist in flavor, Socialist in outlook.

### Hyperinflation Accelerates: Havenstein's Catastrophic Policy

- **Havenstein takes charge**: "No situation was so bad that summer that Dr Havenstein
  could not make it worse." He held firmly that **money supply was unconnected with
  either price levels or exchange rates**; saw his duty as supplying to the limit of
  his ability — the mark's ever-tumbling purchasing power spurred him to **renewed
  activity by the latest enormous price rises**.

- **August 17 speech to Council of State**: Havenstein announces with pride that the
  Reichsbank will increase daily issues from 20,000 milliard to 46,000 milliard marks
  daily (with 18,000 in large denominations). Total circulation would reach 63,000
  milliards: "In a few days we shall therefore be able to issue in one day two-thirds
  of the total circulation."

- **Immediate catastrophe**: Before the speech, mark at 3 million to dollar and 12.5
  million to pound (recent small improvement). Within 48 hours: fell to 5.2 million
  to dollar, 22 million to pound. Circulation in August 1923 had exchange value of
  £9 million — less than one-thirtieth what it had been ten years earlier. **No amount
  of printing contributed to increase its value by a penny.**

- **Lord D'Abernon's judgment**: "No one could anticipate such an ingenuous revelation
  of extreme folly to which ignorance and false theory could lead. The Reichsbank's own
  demented inspirations give stabilisation no chance."

### Government Paralysis: Taxation and Public Services Collapse

- **Tax system breakdown**: Statute books mountain-high; tax receipts for August,
  though nominally 98 times greater than April, were in real terms worth half as much
  — mark fell 200 times in same period. Between August 20-30, receipts represented
  0.7 per cent of expenditure. **Impossible debts** destroyed tax morals at every level.

- **Postal and railway crisis**: Post office tariffs raised from derisory to inadequate
  (letters 400 marks inland, 1,000 marks foreign). Expected postal deficit ~6,000
  milliards. Railways: first and second class fares rose 300 per cent on August 1;
  third and fourth by 250 per cent; freight by 150 per cent. Public outcry more
  remarkable than returns. **No government department could balance a budget while
  banknote-printing continued**.

- **Wage chaos**: On August 13, firms gave wage rises of 5-15 million marks per week;
  bulk paid by cheque. Average cash available: only 5 million (6 shillings). On August
  14, Wupperman employees' directors' houses surrounded demanding 50 million marks
  (£3) per head; 10,000 making same demands on Bayer. Within week: police assaulted
  with iron bars and stones, mobs patrolling streets in Wesdorf, Ohligs, Hilden,
  **tremendous unemployment setting in**.

- **Berlin paralysis**: Printers' strike broke out; large crowds furnished with baskets
  and wheelbarrows surrounding Reichsbank demanding banknotes. Currency "still current,
  nothing having replaced it; but it was no serious measure of value, and hardly a
  medium of exchange." For a fortnight, Berlin like a besieged city — country districts
  had practically stopped all supplies of meat, eggs, vegetables to the capital.

### The Arithmetic of Chaos: Daily Price Lists

- **Mathematical impossibility of commerce**: The complications of daily life required
  extended mathematical knowledge merely to keep body and soul together. Each morning,
  press published daily prices with **different index or multiplier for every trade and
  class of goods**. Most ordinary purchase demanded three or four minutes of calculation;
  several more minutes usually needed to count out the notes in payment. Queues grew
  longer and longer.

- **Example pricing multipliers** (ordinary fare as base):
  - Tramway fare: ×50,000
  - Taxi-autos: ×600,000
  - Horse cabs: ×400,000
  - Bookshops: ×300,000
  - Public baths: ×115,000
  - Medical attendance: ×80,000

- **Lord D'Abernon on discontent**: "It is hardly to be wondered that great discontent
  prevails. A foreigner charged one million marks green fee at golf course — about a
  shilling in his case. The housewife charged similar rates can make no such reflection.
  To boot, she has to stand in queue for several hours to get butter."

### The Interest Rate Farce: Disconnect from Reality

- **August 3, 1923 rate hike fails**: Observing market rate on loan money at 1 per cent
  per day, Reichsbank president raised Bank's discount rate from 18 to 30 per cent per
  annum and loans from 19 to 31 per cent. **Against advice of central committee**, the
  president considered it truckling to market conditions; Havenstein and his directors
  insisted it was the Bank's duty to follow rates, not make them.

- **Vast inadequacy**: Current accounts showing 3-4 per cent per week = 200 per cent per
  year. New rate had **no impact whatsoever**. Had Havenstein understood, should have
  set Bank rate at 360 per cent to even begin addressing the reality of depreciation.

### Havenstein Responds: Printing Accelerates Further

- **Fitzgerald principle**: "Leistungsfähigkeit" (efficiency) of printing system became
  Havenstein's greatest worry. Day and night: 30 paper mills, 150 printing firms, 2,000
  printing presses toiled away adding perpetually to the blizzard of banknotes. **Private
  state banks permitted to issue up to 15,000 milliard marks not daily (as Reichsbank
  did), but as once-and-for-all legal limit** — now demanding right to print more.

- **Havenstein's mission statement**: Proclamation to relieve Germany of dearth of
  currency would "render nugatory the whole credit policy of the Reich and of the
  Reichsbank."

- **September 1 note introduced**: 500 million mark note issued; new word **"billiard"**
  coined (joining three more noughts to old milliard). **50 million marks now needed to
  buy one pound sterling**.

### The Rue Emerges; Government Strains

- **The coalition fractures**: Strain of Havenstein and the **Ruhrkampf** together more
  than government could take. Without supplementary estimate before Cabinet for 6,000
  milliard marks (about £400,000) because of Ruhr subvention, and knowing that ending
  passive resistance would mean not only political death but probably physical death,
  coalition began to founder.

- **Foreign Minister Rosenberg's ultimatum**: "It is not a choice between capitulation
  and chaos. Capitulation would mean chaos. If things go on much longer without relief,
  we shall have chaos without capitulation. It comes to this: the alternative is chaos
  with honour or chaos with dishonour."

- **Desperation consumes Germany**: Believed disturbances in Ruhr and Rhineland might
  lead to French march on Berlin; French did not discourage such talk. Violent
  Communist outbreaks in Saxony and Thuringia; **reactionary movement under Hitler in
  Bavaria was probably growing in strength and size**.

- **August 8 Reichstag speech by Cuno**: Warned that imports would have to be curtailed
  more than ever, taxation would be "unrelenting," national unity needed as never before.
  Although feature was hostility between Communists and Majority Socialists, together
  with increased insolence of former towards everyone, Chancellor heard in silence as he
  claimed that seven months of passive resistance in Ruhr had shown world Germany was
  worthy of respect. **House listened with approval to his call to continue the fight,
  but it was Cuno's last effort** — scapegoat for failing policy, he would be replaced.

### Plunder and Social Breakdown in Austria

- **Anna Eisenmenger's diary from Linz**: Vivid account of complete breakdown. Peasants
  refusing to accept paper for produce; bands of hundreds riding out on bicycles to
  confiscate food. At a farm near Linz: **80-100 men and women plundering**, cart of
  three slaughtered pigs, dead hens, cows slaughtered in place. Cow-shed drenched in
  blood; monsters slit udders of finest milch cow so she had to be put out of misery
  immediately.

- **Property destruction**: In granary — grain and fodder in wild confusion; rag soaked
  in petrol still smouldering showing intent to burn. In kitchen-living room (of which
  aunt was very proud) — nothing left whole. **Uncle estimates damage at 100,000 peace
  kronen; no insurance company will pay compensation**.

- **The desperate hunger**: Peaceful Linz "looked as if visited by earthquake." Furniture
  smashed beyond recognition littered pavements. Not only provision shops, inns, cafés,
  drapers' shops looted — jewellers and watchmakers unable to defend wares. Inn where
  uncle and aunt usually stopped after Mass was completely devastated.

### The Rye Loan and New Currency Scheme

- **September 18 announcement**: Plans for new **Boden Credit Bank** (later Rentenbank)
  — bank of issue backed not by gold (too late for that) but by **mortgages on both
  agricultural land and industry**. Fundamentally an expedient to induce farmers to
  co-operate in feeding nation. **Bodenmark** by way of solid form of **Kontomark** —
  units of account worth ten cents each which Reichsbank was now using to express the
  real values of current accounts. At last the old fiction of **"Mark gleich Mark"** had
  been formally abandoned.

- **Comment on the new scheme**: Most unusual comment was that, having found printing
  press almost played out as instrument of inflation, the Reichsbank was looking round
  for a new one. Bodenmark was in no way intended as means towards stabilisation. Like
  gold loan before it, and rye loan to be issued and repaid according to going price of
  rye, which was proposed simultaneously, it was merely a **stop-gap**.

- **The illusion of improvement**: Ten and twenty-milliard mark notes just coming into
  circulation; larger falling from theoretical exchange value of perhaps £50 on day of
  issue (September 15) to £30 within seven days. By this time an **acute divergency of
  up to 40 per cent** between official exchange rate and free market rate. Paper mark
  finding fewer and fewer takers; every industry fixing its prices according to
  different indices.

### Final Dissolution: Stresemann Takes Decisive Action

- **September 26**: Stresemann suspended seven articles of Weimar constitution, declared
  State of Emergency, gave executive powers to **Herr Gessler** (Defence Minister,
  succeeding Noske after the **Kapp Putsch**). General **von Seeckt**, Commander-in-Chief
  of Reichswehr, became supreme executive and administrative power in the land.

- **Germany becomes military dictatorship**: Country divided into seven military districts
  with local military dictator over each. Simultaneously **President Ebert announced end
  of passive resistance in the Ruhr**.

<!-- pp. 181-200 -->

## Chapter 12: The Bottom of the Abyss

### The Price of Dictatorship

- Germany's emergency powers brought restrictions on personal liberty, freedom of expression, press, and association
- Army and police could interfere with postal, telegraph, phone services and conduct house searches
- Incitement to disobedience: punishable by imprisonment or fines up to 15,000 gold marks
- Death penalty for treason, arson, railway sabotage, or leading armed mobs
- Bavaria already negotiating with **Beneš** about Czechoslovakia's position—would remain neutral if no union with Austria and if Hitler/Rupprecht/Ludendorff stayed out
- Bavaria appointed **Gustav von Kahr** as State Commissioner-General with dictatorial powers, violating Treaty of Versailles
- **Von Seeckt** suppressed Right-wing putsch in Küstrin and the "Black Reichswehr" remnants in Free Corps
- Germany effectively had **two dictators**: von Seeckt in Berlin, von Kahr in Bavaria

### Motor Industry Exhibition—A Façade of Normality

- October motor car exhibition in Berlin attempted to show German competitiveness
- Reality: proliferation of small, ugly, poorly made cycle-cars

> "Euler still shows his fantastic car shaped like a drop of water [the *Tropfenauto*], blunt end at the front... Maybach again his gearless chassis, Benz and Mercedes their usual types, and the only other make worth mentioning is the Audi... All the bodywork is inferior, the colour schemes are painful, and the shapes are monstrous where not stereotyped. The fittings are shoddy and in bad taste. There is no intelligible basis for prices." — British Commercial Attaché

### Hyperinflation Accelerates

- Last week of September: Reichsbank issued 3,267 million million marks (£5.2 million exchange value per day)
- Mark's collapse: 315 million to pound (Sept 11) → 1,500 million (Oct 2) → 5,700 million (Oct 9)
- Pre-war wage: ~36 gold marks (£1 16s) per week
- October 1923: purchasing power of average wage fell to **less than 20% of normal**
- Sums under one million marks no longer accepted

> "A beggar would hardly accept any smaller note." — Lord D'Abernon to Curzon

### Psychological Collapse After Passive Resistance

- Eight months of propaganda for passive resistance suddenly abandoned
- Government admitted making fools of themselves, must surrender unconditionally
- Contempt for Republic and its servants became nearly universal

> "The population is ripe to accept any system of firmness or for any man who appears to know what he wants and issues commands in a loud, bold voice." — Joseph Addison to Alexander Cadogan

- Economic distress made people amenable to authority as "only hope of salvation"
- Unemployment removed "gilt off the gingerbread of democracy"
- Workers realized striking was useless—nothing more unwelcome to employers

### Stresemann's New Government Moves Right

- Stresemann attempted Enabling Act for extra-constitutional powers (early October)
- **Hilferding** finally resigned as Finance Minister—government fell
- New Ministry (Oct 6) moved further Right, seeking to make people work harder
- Workers disposed to agree—little enthusiasm for democracy, moving toward authoritarianism through "weariness of spirit"
- Enabling Act passed Oct 13

> "The helm of the Ship of State must be put over to the Right... Marxism has ruined Germany... An end must be made to this policy of compromise. Away with the Socialists out of the government!" — Volkspartei manifesto, Oct 4

### Return to Work in Occupied Zone

- Workers accepted Ruhr struggle was over (Sept 30)
- *Kölnischer Zeitung* published oath of service to Belgians/French
- Oct 6: German government abandoned *Rhein-Ruhr-Hilfe* (aid to occupied area)
- Until Nov 1: dole twice the normal amount; after Nov 1: same as elsewhere (equal to half estimated basic requirement)
- Oct 7: industrialists (Stinnes, Prussian State Mines director—but not **Krupp von Bohlen** in jail) approached French Commander-in-Chief about resuming work
- Week later: German government instructed railway personnel to return

### Currency Reform Schemes—The Rentenmark

- No settlement possible until German finance restored
- Coal deliveries to France could only be paid by government increasing banknote issue
- Oct 10: pound at 7 milliard marks officially, 18 milliard on free market
- Oct 15: official 18.5 milliard, free market into 40 milliards
- Multiple reform plans discussed: gold, rye, foreign exchange, "material values"
- Question: would foreign control of Germany's finances be acceptable?
- **Rentenmark Ordinance** published Oct 15—hailed as radically unsound
- **Rentenmark**: *Bodenmark* (land mark) rechristened, essentially a modified *Roggenmark* (rye-mark) proposed by **Karl Helfferich**
- Designed to win support from Helfferich's Nationalists and the Left who distrusted *Roggenmark*
- Released Reichsbank from obligation to finance government
- Aimed to restore 1913 currency framework—every banknote meant what it said
- Contrivance of Hilferding's successor **Dr Luther** and **Dr Schacht** (Darmstadt & National Bank managing director, soon Currency Commissioner)
- Mid-October: just one more scheme to "smudge one's brain with ink"—no new bank, no new banknotes yet

### Bavaria's Explosive Situation

- Munich and Bavaria suffering same economic distress but "most explosive mixture in Germany"
- **Robert Clive** (British Consul-General at Munich): correspondents gathered at Bavarian capital thinking "nothing for the present is likely to happen"
- Daily decrees prohibiting public meetings and strikes
- **Von Kahr** and **General von Lossow** in full control, calculatingly ignoring Berlin's instructions
- Refused Berlin's order to ban Hitler's newspaper *Völkischer Beobachter* (Oct 2), but suspended it Oct 5-15 for treasonable article

> "Bavaria prefers Kahr. The eclipse of Hitler is almost complete." — Robert Clive

- Von Kahr tearing leaves from Hitler's book: fostering *Kriegschuldlüge* (war responsibility lie), expelling Jewish families from state
- When *Münchner Post* suggested von Kahr took this action to please Hitler, it too was suppressed
- Von Lossow equally undisciplined—ignored instructions as *Reichsdiktator*

> "Lossow is always protesting that he is doing his best to carry out instructions as *Reichsdiktator*, but somehow something invariably happens to nullify those excellent intentions: his instructions arrive too late, or he is out at lunch, or he is burying his aunt... For practical purposes Bavaria is no longer part of the Reich." — Addison to Stresemann

- Oct 20: Kahr overruled Berlin's dismissal of Lossow

### Economic Desperation Reaches Critical Mass

> "The distress is very great." — Clive's report, Oct 18

- Few families afford meat more than once weekly
- Eggs unprocurable, milk terribly scarce, bread 16x the price of days earlier
- Expensive restaurants full of well-dressed people—either German-Americans or Ruhr industrialists
- No one expects Rentenmark will help

> "The desperate economic conditions are mainly responsible for these recurring troubles. Things could not be worse. Demoralisation and irresponsibility are rampant, and will continue until some light appears on the horizon and the feeling again begins to grow that there is something to live for, beyond the value of the dollar and the necessity to get rid of paper marks before they are worthless." — Herr von Haniel, Berlin's representative *Reichsminister* in Munich

- Bremen: machine-gun patrols, cost-of-living strikes by cotton-spinners and shipyard workers
- Hanover province: unemployment increasing ~10% per week
- **Mr Elphick** (Consul at Bremen): prices in Germany reached world level, already outstripping it—cheaper to buy in England

> "The reason is that even in Germany it is now fully realised that the mark is absolutely valueless and all prices have been placed on a gold basis."

- "Ground price" fixed on gold marks at double pre-war, multiplied by retailer's multiplicator
- Multiplicator increased day by day, frequently hour by hour, to keep pace with mark depreciation—providing against rapid depreciation, enormous profit margin included

### Bremen's Gold Note Experiment

- Oct 24: Bremen Senate issued gold notes totaling 1 million dollars (not marks) in denominations of quarter, half, one dollar
- Smaller values (5, 10 cents) for daily purchases without exchanging for paper marks
- Gold certificates already issued as wage packets—repayable in 5 months in Bremen State 5% dollar bonds or Reichsbank currency at middle official NY rate
- One-dollar note redeemable anytime in paper marks at full official rate without foreign exchange tax
- Backed by all receipts and resources of Bremen
- Seemed as stable as possible in any part of Germany

### Gresham's Law Reversed

- Bremen risked bad money drives out good (Gresham's Law)—new gold notes might be hoarded
- Autumn 1923: new factor—**absence of ability to hoard**
- Workers and *petits bourgeois* reduced to penury, resources gone
- Retail goods stocks badly needed replenishing, but pockets empty
- Contrary to theory: better medium actually drove inferior out of circulation
- Result: fall in prices as retailers no longer had to allow for depreciation

### Separatist Threats Multiply

- Financial separatism least of government's worries
- Territorial separation threatened in Prussia, Saxony, Bavaria, Rhineland
- Guelph secessionist plot in Hanover with figurehead Duke of Cumberland (deposed Elector of Hanover)
- Most menacing after Bavaria: **Rhineland separatist movement**
- Düsseldorf, Sept 30: 20,000 separatists gathered, marched, killed 11 policemen—crowds imported by train with French permission while locals locked doors
- Following three weeks: further outbreaks with/without French support
- Oct 21: **Rhenish Republic** proclaimed in Belgian zone at Aachen—immediately quashed by Curzon's sharp note to Belgium
- Supported by French troops, separatist administrations declared at Bonn, Trier, Wiesbaden, Mainz
- Leaders quarrelled, German civil service refused cooperation, regime and services collapsed
- French turned attention to **Palatinate** (integral part of Bavaria), intimating it had become autonomous State

### Hamburg Communist Uprising

- Simultaneously: serious Communist-encouraged trouble in Hamburg
- Fundamental cause: wages received in tail of currency collapse entirely inadequate
- Oct 15: authorities withdrew bread cards (enabled buying bread at less than half market price)
- Week later: dockers and shipbuilders struck again
- Police stations rushed, trees felled, trenches dug, open food shops plundered
- One *coup* already suppressed in Küstrin
- German cruiser *Hamburg* arrived with torpedo boats, put ashore marines to stamp out rebellion, arrest 800 Left-wing activists

### Currency Collapse Metrics—October

- Oct 15: mark passed 18 milliards to pound
- Oct 21: 24 milliards → 80 milliards in three days
- At 60 milliards: approximately **one mark for every second elapsed since birth of Christ**
- End of month: banknote circulation = 2,496,822,909,038,000,000 marks
- Oct 26: Reichsbank in Berlin (no bread for days—bakers short of flour) surrounded by crowd demanding milliard-mark notes carried off in baskets and carts
- First billiard, 5-billiard, 10-billiard notes ready Nov 1

### Hamburg Strike—Wage Depreciation Outpaces Adjustment

- Hamburg disturbances (end of October): product of genuine frustration and despair
- Depreciation so rapid wages could no longer be adjusted via index numbers and multiplicators
- Workmen receiving 405 million marks/day Oct 1 (about 6s 8d at exchange rate)
- Oct 20: 6,500 million on Oct 20
- New packet (with exchange at 80 milliards) = only 7½d
- Prices kept pace with exchange rates—speed of retail price movement was protective measure
- Business virtually impossible
- Oct 22 ordinance: compelling shopkeepers to keep shops open and offer goods for paper marks

### Demand for Wages of Fixed Value

- Hamburg: cry for wages of fixed value
- Oct 26: workers clamouring for fixed wages turned down offer of wage in new Hamburg gold mark notes
- Dual grounds: employers couldn't pay it, and workers needed paper marks for living expenses
- People hardly knew what they wanted
- Nov 1: Hamburg assembly voted 500,000 milliard marks (nearly £2,000) relief
- Hamburg returned to work with payment in port made in municipal gold currency

### Relief Mixed with Continued Crisis

- Arrangement imperfect: notes had to be converted to paper marks before spending
- Outrageous advantage frequently taken by moneychangers
- Relief that Communist uprising suppressed was so great that industrial situation's seriousness widely unappreciated
- Hamburg's 100,000 unemployed: 30,000 shipbuilders, 6,000 longshoremen, 60,000 others

### National Unemployment Crisis

- Same story all over Germany—better some places, worse others, worst in Ruhr
- Dismissals continued everywhere
- Marines from *Hamburg* despatched to Ruhr due to trouble feared from Thyssen, Stinnes closing many factories
- Their discussions with French amicable, mutually advantageous, but conflicted with Berlin's requirements
- Chancellor visited Ruhr, returned appalled (Oct 27)
- Run-down of official dole in occupied areas nearly complete
- Even at risible national level, government could no longer afford any subvention
- Trade unions reporting overall German unemployment: 18.7% of members
- Another 40% of work force on short time: 4-40 hours/week
- Apart from 2 million workers in occupied territories: government paying unemployment relief to 877,262 in unoccupied Germany (union unemployment at 10%) and short-time relief to nearly 1,700,000
- Many more whom no relief reached
- Practically all stagnation in unoccupied Germany due to shutting down of rest

### Stresemann's November Prognosis

- For November: prospect of 5 million workers without work, without government support, largely without food
- More riots inevitable
- Stinnes and colleague Vogler continuing negotiations with French
- Nationalists with Stinnes behind them determined as first priority to destroy present government
- Coal tax demanded by French as part of return-to-normality price simply could not be paid
- Rhineland became domain of lawlessness, anarchy, unrestrained terrorism of armed separatist bands
- Occupying town halls with French support, defying police
- Country in general: population would no longer accept currency losing half its value every successive day

### Saxony's Red Dictatorship

- **Dr Zeigner's** Communist ministers in Saxony issued manifesto for red dictatorship
- Zeigner declined Berlin's ultimatum to restore order
- Chancellor expressed doubts Rentenmark would be effective even as stop-gap
- "Most surely, the pips had squeaked"

### Five Simultaneous Crises—October 30

- Oct 30: mark at 310 milliards to pound
- Berlin government faced five immediate crises: **Bavaria, Saxony, Rhineland, Ruhr resumption, financial chaos**
- Successful Ruhr outcome depended on NY negotiations for credits to buy essential food/fuel imports
- If loan large enough with Germany's remaining reserves: might start new currency
- Otherwise: nowhere to look for oxygen

### Hitler's Putsch and Its Context

- Nov 1: Hitler's Bavarian levies mustering on Thuringia border (moral support from Brandenburg and Pomerania)
- Threatening Communist insurgents if Republic would not
- Military Commissioner-General in Saxony proceeded with force against Red Centuries
- Zeigner and ministers arrested—provoked adverse Socialist reaction in Reichstag, contributed to brewing Cabinet crisis
- Nov 2: violent panic on Berlin Bourse—not because Bavaria or Cabinet crisis or mark (just lost 4/5 value in three days)
- Rather: realization of **eight official kinds of paper** in circulation plus numberless emergency money issues
- Official tokens: Reichsbank notes, railway *Notgeld*, gold loan *coupures*, Reich dollars

> "Chaos the like of which had not been seen in economic history." — Lord D'Abernon

### Thuringia and Berlin Distress—Early November

- Nov 5: military action against Saxony complete, Reichswehr turned on Thuringia
- Protests from Socialist deputies whose constituents now in line of fire
- Nov 6: looting of foodshops with strong anti-Semitic overtones in poorer quarters of Berlin
- Population in acutest distress: farmers' reluctance to sell produce in cities
- **Mr J.C. Vaughan** (British businessman) passed through Berlin, wrote protest to Foreign Office:

> "I was sickened by the sights I saw. I happened to pass through the Arcade between the Friedrichstrasse and Unter den Linden, and in that small space I saw three almost moribund women. They were either in the last stages of decline or starvation, and I have no doubt it was the latter... I am no pro-German, but that we should tolerate such a state of things five years after the Armistice is to my mind appalling."

### Starvation Amidst Plenty

- Industrial areas and towns everywhere (except municipalities whose *Notgeld* based on gold): common lot
- Breslau: foreign businessman living since September largely on bread and weak tea, got one square meal daily by crowding into restaurant early morning, waiting hours for luncheon
- Had money to pay but went hungry to bed each night
- Farmers' barns bursting with unsold food—Germany suffering widespread famine
- Every Zurich provision shop: placard "Send food parcels to your friends in Germany"
- Conditions and prospects of middle and professional classes "fearsome"
- Two possible remedies: food from abroad, or stable medium persuading farmers to release food for paper

### The Beer Hall Putsch—November 8

- Thuringian action held lid down two more days on boiling Bavarian kettle
- Hitler's hopes for pitched battle with Communists or Bavarian troops marching on Berlin dashed
- Tension in Munich mounted hourly—Kahr and Lossow toyed with proclaiming Bavaria's secession as independent monarchy
- Danger plus necessity to ride revolutionary momentum persuaded Hitler to attempt *Putsch* night of Nov 8
- Course of **Bürgerbräukeller Putsch** and ignominious end next day not strictly part of this story

### Hitler and Nazi Exploitation of Inflation

- Important considerations: Hitler and Nazi Party able to use miseries of severe inflation to drum up nation-wide opposition to authority
- Persuaded many thousands fault and blame lay where it palpably did not: with Armistice signers, French, Jews, Bolsheviks
- Inflation played into Hitler's hands—no more invention of Communists (also taking advantage) than of Hitler and Nazis

> "Inflation is the ally of political extremism, the antithesis of order. At other times - in post-revolutionary Russia, in Kadar's Hungary - it may have been deliberately engendered in order to destroy the social order, for chaos is the very stuff of revolution."

- In Germany at this time: inflationary policy was consequence of financial ignorance, industrial greed, political cowardice
- Therefore produced hothouse conditions for greater/faster growth of reactionary or revolutionary crusades

> "Hitler set his hopes in 1923 on 'the revolt of starving billionaires'."

- Gave Bavarian authorities (and Berlin to lesser extent) very nasty turn during second week of November
- For 24 hours: real danger of civil war not confined to Bavaria
- Communist rising just suppressed in Hamburg regarded - at least until Hitler's trial February 1924 - as much more sinister and dangerous
- Danger of workers' revolution other than under Communist sponsorship was what hurried Communist Party into promoting ill-coordinated national insurrection

### Martial Law and Currency Stabilization—Post-Putsch

- Bloodletting in Bavaria (martial law declared) hardly served to cool passions or relieve unhappiness elsewhere
- Von Seeckt set about suppressing extreme parties armed with latest presidential decrees
- President and Chancellor issued proclamation condemning treasonable outbreak in south, pointing out latest currency measures improved mark manifold within 24 hours
- "Sumptuary triumph" short-lived
- First 100-billiard note already out
- Dr Havenstein's presses giving bounty to record tune: nearly 74 million million million marks/week
- Quadrupling in six days previous total circulation
- Cost-of-living index (1914 = 1): risen from September average of 15 million to 3,657 million in October
- Nov 12: 218,000 million

### Appeals from Occupied Territories

- Women of Cologne (nearly 100,000 work-less) sent appeal "To the Women of the British Empire":

> "During the times of passive resistance we existed, not by industry, but through the paper money doles sent from unoccupied country. Now these have ceased and we face starvation. Industry cannot recover, and there are millions, literally, out of work... tens of thousands of our leading citizens have been banished or imprisoned... our newspapers have been suppressed... armed hordes of adventurers have now been let loose on our disarmed and helpless population in the name of separatism and Republicanism... Winter is before us, and we have no coal."

### Abandoning the Occupied Zone

- German government preparing to leave occupied zone finances to their own fate
- Might have been done rather than suicidal passive resistance path
- Previous January: humanitarian and patriotic considerations made it impossible
- Danger now: end of financial aid would throw area into separatists' arms
- Proposal for new bank of issue for Ruhr and Rhineland viewed with great dismay unless absorbed into new Rentenbank when it came
- Negotiations between French and industrialists continued unavailing
- Certain Rentenmark would fail like paper mark if unproductive payments in subsidies and doles to Ruhr prolonged
- To avoid that: even old age pensions to be abandoned
- Still: paper sums (millions of gold marks) being despatched daily to occupied Germany to save population

### Local Currency Initiatives in Occupied Zone

- Industrial firms and municipalities in occupied areas cushioned effects of coming change
- District of Solingen: gold-based marks issue with cover from foreign exchange balances standing to credit of members of Solingen Chamber of Commerce
- Höchst dye works: second issue of gold-mark currency covered by deposit of 400,000+ Swiss francs in Zurich bank
- Several firms made large purchases of milk and potatoes to sell to own workers
- Could only afford to pay them 70 gold pfennigs (about 8½d or 20 cents) per hour
- Margin between skilled and unskilled labour reduced to ~10% throughout Germany
- Labour more demoralised than ever, output per working man less than pre-war

<!-- pp. 201-220 -->

## The Rentenmark's Paradoxical Success

### The Anomalous Currency

- **Rentenmark** not legal tender but "a legal means of payment"
- Not convertible to gold or agricultural/industrial assets backing it
- 500 Rentenmarks convertible to bond with nominal value of 500 gold marks
- Paper mark remained legal tender, "mummified" but still circulating
- Legal reduction of paper mark not sanctioned until Aug 30, 1924 law
- Conversion: "Eine Billion Mark" note (with clarifying inscription "1,000 Milliarden") → one Reichsmark

### The Psychology of Stabilization

- Success not from stopping printing presses, but from **fiscal discipline**
- Refusing further credit to government + fixed parity against gold/dollar
- The confidence trick worked because Rentenmark had different name from paper mark
- Public thought it was something different despite being unconvertible paper

> "On the basis, of the simple fact that the new paper money had a different name from the old, the public thought it was something different from the paper mark ... The new money was accepted, despite the fact that it was an unconvertible paper currency. It was held and not spent as rapidly." — **Constantino Bresciani-Turroni**

- Same experience in Austria with gold loan bonds labeled "stable-value"
- Velocity of circulation slowed from mad gallop to sedate walk
- Most important: prospect that food might flow back to cities, budget might balance

### Dr. Schacht's Two Immediate Problems

- **Black market**: dollar at 12,000 milliard marks (3x official rate) in late November
- **Notgeld** (emergency money): threat to continued stability
- "Everyone his own Reichsbank" system had to end
- Reichsbank announcement to stop accepting new Notgeld issues caused storm of protest

### Crushing the Black Market

- November 25 Cologne meeting: National Currency Commissioner resisted industrialists/municipal officials
- They wanted Notgeld acceptance restored
- Declared decisively that budgeting with stable figures had begun
- Black market dealt with automatically but brusquely
- Speculators closing books end of November lacked money to meet commitments
- Credits formerly gladly given by Reichsbank no longer available
- Those who bought dollars at 12,000 milliard marks forced to sell at 4,200 milliard
- Lost two-thirds of outlay
- Before Dec 1, £10 million in foreign currency returned to Bank
- Speculators fled to Paris, worked on franc — first signal stabilization was real

### Dr. Schacht's Operation

- Worked from single room, former charwoman's cupboard in Ministry of Finance
- Secretary **Fräulein Steffeck** later described his methods:

> "What did he do? He sat on his chair and smoked in his little dark room which still smelled of old floor cloths. Did he read letters? No, he read no letters. Did he write letters? No, he wrote no letters. He telephoned a great deal - he telephoned in every direction and to every German or foreign place that had anything to do with money and foreign exchange as well as with the Reichsbank and the Finance Minister. And he smoked. We did not eat much during that time. We usually went home late, often by the last suburban train, travelling third class. Apart from that he did nothing."

- Arcane financial manipulations passed unnoticed by most Germans
- Population's preoccupations: hunger, cold, mounting social unrest
- Rioting, highway robberies all around Berlin
- **Stresemann's Enabling Act** gave von Seeckt power to control food prices
- Even sent home female Reparations Commission staff

### Food Shortages Persist

- Three days after stabilization, no more food in markets than before
- Beef/mutton plentiful but expensive
- No pork delivered — farmers eating it themselves
- Shortage of cattle feed from abroad, milk yields falling
- Berlin's daily milk consumption: 1.8M litres → 130,000 litres
- Biggest dairy (Bollo): 25,000 litres/day vs. 1M+ before war
- Butter unobtainable, too expensive for most

### Political Crisis and Stresemann's Fall

- Socialist politicians worried by collapse of democracy
- Reichstag bubbling with indignation against Chancellor
- Nov 23: voted Ministry down on no-confidence motion
- Wouldn't end State of Emergency despite Ruhr concerns
- **Stresemann** came to office in August to stop inflation, depose **Dr. Havenstein**
- **Havenstein** died Nov 20 (stabilization day), resigned effective management only then
- **Hilferding** as Finance Minister achieved nothing
- Little sign **Dr. Luther** would achieve more
- Stresemann took office after British Note of Aug 11 declaring passive resistance would cease
- Personally stopped it, but no French settlement reached
- Ruhr was final sticking point — possibility of abandoning workers decided vote

### Signs of Sanity Returning

- Agreement between Ruhr mine-owners and **MICUM** (Franco-Belgian Commission)
- Mine-owners to make full deliveries of reparation coal/coke, pay $15M in coal tax arrears
- Poincaré's "productive pledges" secured
- Postal charges on gold basis
- 10% railway personnel dismissal announced within two months
- Miners: 8-hour day underground (vs. 7.5 hour)
- State officials/employees/iron & steel industry: back to 9-hour day
- Official salaries reduced below pre-war levels
- New cold winds of realism howling across country

### Cabinet Crisis

- **Dr. Marx** (Centre Party) formed Cabinet Nov 30, Stresemann as Minister of Foreign Affairs
- Reichstag adjourned until mid-January, ending Cabinet/parliamentary crisis begun in September

### Unemployment Explosion

- Overriding issue: swelling unemployment
- Extent stabilization contributed unclear
- Germany's finances/economy deteriorated too far for palliatives to help
- Choice: unemployment + financial chaos OR unemployment + monetary discipline
- Either alternative meant misery, but second offered food and way out
- Week of interregnum (Stresemann → Marx): recurrence of endemic disorders
- Düsseldorf, Essen, Gelsenkirchen: Communist-inspired armed fights, bloodshed
- Food was the problem

### The Cost of Stability

- Speculators fled to Paris (franc depression) — first sign of stabilization success
- Taxation began weighing heavily
- Interest rates high at 100%
- Capital/credit shortage meant high prices, factory closures
- Cost of living crept up in real terms
- University tuition fees rose suddenly, student enrollment fell
- State/municipal relief less adequate than before
- Trade unions in turmoil (funds vanished with paper mark)

### Workers' Hardship

- Earlier inflation: wages low but generally enough
- Stabilization shock brought intolerable strain
- Christmas 1923: registered unemployed total in unoccupied Germany 1.5M+
- Real total probably 1M more
- Majority on short-time or reduced pay
- **Arthur Rosenberg** (far Left) estimated only 30/100 workers in regular employment
- Workers accepted employment on any terms
- Employers took advantage, backed by government's benevolent neutrality

### Government's Limited Options

- Made **Schacht** President of Reichsbank for life
- Could only hope cure would work, prepare tax ordinances
- Trial by jury temporarily abolished (financial hardship to jurymen)
- Only half officials' salaries paid week ending Dec 17
- Balance made up when taxes furnished revenue
- Taxes quickly on gold basis
- Budgetary deficit: 99% pre-stabilization → 92% after Nov 20 → 44% last ten days Dec
- December revenue: 33M gold marks
- January to be 440M, or 95% of outgoings
- February 1924: budget finally balanced (after lapse) in March

### The Rentenmark's Greatest Triumph

- Most important immediate triumph: **shifting the harvest**
- 1922 medical reports: every German town had desperate undernourishment pockets
- Urban nation suffered lack of food, clothing, warmth
- All concomitant ailments: ulcers to rickets, pneumonia to tuberculosis
- Medicines/medical supplies soaring costs
- Another year of greater deprivation took terrible toll
- Certainty of prolonged unemployment's demoralization

### Food Returns to Cities

- Beginning to appear in towns mid-December
- To Rentenmark alone this was due
- Before November, only increase in animals slaughtered was dogs
- After stabilization: consumption of every daily need increased regularly except dogmeat

> "Not even the most fanatical advocate of stabilisation - and this title I yield to no one - could have anticipated more remarkable results from its attainment than those which are now manifest. Food has become abundant in the great towns; potatoes and cereals are brought to market in large quantities; while butter, which was obtainable only in the better quarters, is now offered at stable, if at high prices. Animals crowd the abattoirs and queues have disappeared from before the shops of butchers and provision merchants. The economic détente has brought in its train political pacification - dictatorship and Putsches are no longer discussed, and even the extreme parties have ceased, for the moment, from troubling." — **Lord D'Abernon**, Christmas Day 1923

### Euphoria Fades

- **Bresciani-Turroni** writing six years later on beneficial influence:

> "Commerce revived, the food situation in the cities was eased, the purchasing power of many classes was increased, the factories reopened, unemployment declined rapidly, and a refreshing wave of confidence revived the energies of the people."

- True for a space
- February 1924: **Dr. Kuczynski** (leading German statistical authority) confirmed sea-change

> "The difference in public feeling compared with two months ago [told British Ambassador] is absolutely astounding. Then everyone was depressed and thought a catastrophe imminent. Today they are full of confidence. There is no adequate physical or economic reason for this - the change is mainly psychological. You may say it is based upon the Rentenmark, but that is more or less a fraud, and it would be more correct to say that it is due to the moral effect of the mere cessation of printing banknotes, or more correctly to the belief by the public that printing has at last stopped. This has given them so much confidence that they keep the circulating medium in their pockets and tills - £125 million there today against £5 million last September."

### False Dawn

- Sanity returned to Germany's finances
- 1924: period of often extreme monetary stringency consolidated financial recovery
- Too much to hope after Dawes Plan (August) and unemployment dwindling that years of profligacy could be easily paid for
- What country passed through would have lasting effects on people's minds
- Destitution of middle classes — resilient would recover in due course — only part of price
- Economic reckoning still to come
- Some say political reckoning didn't come until 1933, when economic recovery had to begin again

## Chapter 14: Unemployment Breaks Out

### Schacht's Clear-Eyed Assessment

- Author of reform had no illusions about shortcomings
- Rentenmark could hold tide only so long
- New credits from abroad essential
- No departure from strictest discipline despite government pleading for money
- Nothing could be done that would risk currency stability or budgetary balance

> "After a long devaluation, stability can only be regained at the cost of a severe crisis. We are in the midst of this crisis. External commerce is at a standstill. The balance of trade is active [i.e. in Germany's favour] only because imports have ceased as importers have no means of paying. Industry is living on old stocks." — **Dr. Schacht**, Jan 24, 1924

### Seeking Foreign Support

- Saw **Lord Norman** (Governor of Bank of England) about funding his **Golddiskontbank**
- Project headed off establishment of French-backed Rhineland bank
- End of January: went to Paris for **Dawes Committee** hearings
- Icy meeting with **M. Poincaré** showed France still insisting on pound of flesh
- No less anxious to promote separatism in Rhineland

### Industrialists Turn to France

- Confidence returned to Germany hardly affected industrialists in western provinces
- Hard-pressed for funds from home and abroad
- Began turning to French for terms
- Considered (as Stresemann put it) patriot's first duty to make money, not become bankrupt
- Guiding thought for many years
- **Stinnes** more dangerously ready than most to agree to Paris proposals
- Little concerned that French-backed Rhenish bank opposing Reichsbank would boost separatism

### Stabilization's Devastating Effects on Food Trade

- Food importers especially hard hit
- When mark falling: merchants charged high prices justified by need to cover themselves
- Money received often converted to stable values — unhealthy business developed
- Merchants and farmers found hard to return to dull, small profits
- Many caught by cheaper imported food availability
- Left with large, expensive, perishable stocks
- Biggest importers ordered during depreciation hoping to repay in depreciated marks
- Found themselves threatened with bankruptcy, panicked, threw stocks on market

### January 1924: Glut Reports from Cologne

- "Abundant supplies" vegetables/fruit, domestic and foreign
- German potatoes, eggs, butter
- Italian cauliflower, Canary tomatoes, Spanish grapes, American apples, French nuts
- Fortnight later: abundance become glut
- People begged to buy milk at 36 pfennigs/litre (under 3d/pint)
- Mountains of Hawaiian pineapple, Colombian salmon, American corned beef
- Products of bankruptcy/near-bankruptcy
- Prices coming down 25% at time, goods remained unsold
- Mass of population simply unable to buy
- Much suffering from strikes over 10-hour day return
- Larger factories closed in Ruhr and Rhineland
- Unemployed seen in crowds every town

### Price Paradoxes

- Food cheaper but few earning/receiving enough to buy
- Rest of Germany: vegetables still at premium, prices coming down for orthodox reasons
- Christmas: 1 billion marks (1M million, Rentenmark equivalent) bought 2-3 oranges
- February: same sum bought 20-30 from unemployed hawking them in streets
- Margarine: 500 milliards/kilo (high as 800 milliards)
- Frozen meat: down from 600 to 450 milliards/pound (fine cuts still 4 billions/4s)

### British Embassy Assessment

> "The poor are not really getting a proper amount of food, as they haven't enough money to profit from the cheaper market - owing also to strikes and unrest, the stagnation of industry, and cessation of exports. There has been a general increase in the cost of living for such things as heat, light, and housing - all more than in Britain."

### Hitler's Trial and Bavaria

- People needed work, unemployment allowance insufficient
- Part-time workers' wages too low even for necessities
- Bavaria settled politically after **Hitler's 24-day trial** (started Feb 2, 1924)
- Trial gave national/international platform, ended in minimum sentences
- Many acquittals, including **Ludendorff** (whose own acquittal disgusted him)
- British Consul-General **Mr. Clive** in Munich noted end of year:

> "National Socialism had thrived in the existing depression of 1923. There was a don't-care feeling in the air. The greater fiasco of the trial disillusioned the minds of more reasonable people, although Hitler's party a little later got one-fifth of the Landtag votes ... Hitler's greatest enemy is the Rentenmark. It is impossible to overestimate the beneficial effect of the stabilisation of the currency on the Bavarian, and I suppose also on the whole German outlook. When the London Conference [on Dawes Plan implementation] assembled in July 1924, six months of stabilisation had already had a calming effect on the Nationalist hotheads."

- **Von Kahr** and **von Lossow** resigned mid-February
- Permitted re-establishment of agreement between Bavaria and Reich

### Middle Classes Destroyed

- Bavaria too: middle classes had gone to wall
- Story throughout urban Germany
- Whether hit harder (as well as hungrier and colder) at end of 1923 vs. end of 1922 hard to say
- Christmas 1919 brought destitution to many
- People on savings, pensions, war-disability grants, assurance payments, fixed incomes continued making do
- Sold chattels or small unaccustomed work
- Municipal soup kitchens often fed them
- Numbers amounted to millions
- Not on unemployed/short-time relief lists
- Had wealth shot away by war without knowing it
- Looked vainly for charity help
- Charitable institutions, religious societies, literary/scientific foundations, universities, hospitals had income fountains reduced to trickle
- Industrial debenture holders lost capital (industries redeemed debts with worthless paper)
- Industrial share holders in 1913: capital reduced by 3/4
- Pittance in dividend totals over years
- Most people panicked long since, sold bulk of shares for what they could get
- Industrial profiteers and speculators amassed nation's wealth, paid themselves not dividends but "fees"
- Germany's capital redistributed most cruelly
- No longer spread reasonably among millions
- Largely in coagulated blobs among new plutocracy

### Wealth Redistribution's Visible Evidence

- Destitution inflicted by inflation not general
- Great wealth evidence ostentatiously flaunted
- Misled many observers, including French
- Supposed Germany's reparations refusal was Teutonic knavery
- Until Ruhr invasion: full employment, prosperous working class, booming home market, strongly competitive foreign position, factories bursting with production
- All made possible by vast scale of Germany's borrowing
- Could have fooled anybody
- But inflation shed deadly rain discriminately
- For some, pauperization reality lay hardly below surface

### Professional Classes Suffer

- Rentier classes: people whose livelihoods depended on savings, annuities, pensions mentioned
- Included poorly paid professions: judges, army officers, parliamentary deputies
- Positions/dignity traditionally supplemented by private means
- Other groups: mainly professional people
- Services turned out expendable in short-term
- Civil litigation became luxury — who would buy books?
- Who in hurry for architectural advice?
- Art and tuition could wait
- No rush for emergency medical treatment
- Even that couldn't always be paid for as soon or in amounts doctors wished
- Private patients slow to come forward
- Health-insurance companies couldn't pay full fees (inflation damage to funds)
- No one could tell how many dependants of professional people went short

### The Partial Truth of Middle Class Destitution

- Common assessment: middle classes left destitute only part of story
- Certainly had savings to lose
- Lost them in paper form or as jewelry, silver, furniture, pictures, precious possessions
- Landlords reduced to beggary through rent restriction to nominal sums
- Or through selling property at knock-down prices to stay alive
- Some householders survived renting off apartments at realistic rates
- But not only middle classes going through mill
- Organized, unionised workers managed by and large to keep wage-packets acceptable (though scarcely opulent) until Ruhr struggle stifled national economy
- Unorganised workers gone down with middle classes
- Ranged from tailors and cab-drivers to chimney-sweeps and domestic servants
- Painters, gardeners, chauffeurs, carpenters, shop assistants, printers, laundrywomen, cabinet-makers, porters
- Skilled and unskilled, male and female, self-employed to sackable
- Third group: people receiving small subsidies/pensions from central or local governments
- Age and disability entitled them to income from public purse
- Social insurance contributions amounted to no assurance
- Public purse in 1923 paying at rates ranging upwards from insulting to disgraceful
- Numbers (excluding unemployed): reckoned at end of year at 5,600,000+

### Austrian Parallel

- Stabilisation brought as little relief for middle classes dependent on fixed incomes as for working classes without employment
- Year of stability in Austria proved inflation imposed deeper, more devastating social change than revolution achieved
- **Frau Eisenmenger's** diary closing entries give idea of what she underwent:

> "Foodstuffs which three years ago were entirely unobtainable in Vienna and the rest of Austria [she wrote in December 1923] can now be bought everywhere. But who can buy them? Whose income has kept pace with the tireless activities of the banknote printing-press? Although my holding in shares is worth at today's quotation more than 10 million kronen, I am at my wits end to know where to find money to buy food ... today the value of our krone is quoted in Zurich as 0.00705 centimes."

- January 2, 1924: full implications of Austrian currency reforms dawned:

> "The kronen and heller have been changed into schillings and groschen. It is a drastic change. For 15,000 kronen we get - one schilling! Thousands of Austrians have been reduced during the last days to beggary. All who were not clever enough to hoard the forbidden stable currencies or gold have, without exception, suffered losses. An old married couple with whom I have been friendly for years had a holding of government stock amounting to 2 million pre-war kronen which brought them in interest 80,000 pre-war kronen a year [more than £3,200]. They were rich people. Today their stock brings them in 8 new schillings a year. Panic has seized the Stock Exchange. My millions have dwindled to about a thousand new schillings. We belong to the new poor. The middle class has been reduced to the proletariate. More fighting - daily, repeated, exasperated, demoralising, offensive and defensive fighting of man against man. I feel that my strength is deserting me. I cannot go on."

### Hungary's Descent

- Times scarcely better in Hungary
- 1923 dismal year
- Began with severe anti-Semitism outbreak in January
- **Count Bethlen's** government coming more under Right-wing nationalist influence
- Numbers swelled as rumors of impending foreign interference gained ground
- "Move" and "Awakening Hungarians" run by **M. Gömbös** (Minister for War)
- Had students and ex-officers as main elements
- Country's finances went from bad to worse
- Government in many ways sharing (for want of notion how to put things right) view propounded by **M. Bruno Balogh** (British-Hungarian Bank director):

> "The only proper policy is that pursued by Germany where private undertakings are supported and developed without regard to the State finances. This is Germany's strongest point and France's greatest sorrow."

- Korona fell: 14,500 (March 1923) to 92,000 (August) to 120,000 to pound (October)
- Free rates always much higher, prices going at last to twice UK level
- Farmers long ceased hoarding currency, now hoarded corn and cattle
- Desperation of townspeople

### Hungary's Belated Rescue

- Year after **Dr. Seipel's** successful Europe tour for Austria
- **Count Bethlen** (Prime Minister of Hungary) set out cap in hand to ask for international charity
- October 1923: Reparations Commission did for Hungary what done year before for Austria
- Waived first lien on national assets
- December: more Protocols drawn up in Geneva to arrange international loan
- **Mr. Jeremiah Smith** (American financier) went to Budapest as League's Commissioner-General
- Carried out work on lines **Dr. Zimmermann** pioneered in Vienna
- No less than in Austria: population (especially public servants) suffered deprivations/ignominies of financial reconstruction
- To these miseries added during pre-slump years: great land hunger among peasantry
- Lack of strict democratic rights (including press freedom) which existed next door in Austria
- Currency reform of 1925 permitted 12,500 korona to be changed for one new pengo

### Germany's Minimal Restitution

- Few victims of inflation actually obtained minimal restitution
- By 1922: unfairness with which wealth and incomes redistributed became extremely noticeable
- More so as creditors' rights outrageously usurped by absurd distinction between nominal and market values
- Real value of mortgaged property no comfort to creditor accepting paper rather than gold while property remained securely in debtor's hands
- As clamour grew with Court support, government attempted redressing grievances it could
- **Decree of February 14, 1924** (Third Taxation Ordinance): industrial debentures and mortgages revalued at 15% of original gold price
- Mortgage bonds, savings bank deposits, other obligations revalued at slightly higher rates
- Meagre as terms were, meant nothing to people who had parted with securities or whose credits paid off in paper earlier
- Further law of July 1925 introduced retrospective element
- Covered extinct mortgages/debentures held in good faith at least five years before
- Raised mortgage revaluation rate to 25%

### Taxing Inflation's Beneficiaries

- 1924 decree imposed modest tax on grosser profits inflation made possible
- Example: through depreciation of industrial debentures
- Amounted to under 2% of original gold value
- Even smaller in respect of rural profits: 1.7% of original gold amount of mortgages whose shrinkage hugely contributed
- Taxes earmarked either for Reich or constituent states
- Move to revalue government's own loans became law in 1925
- Resulted in stockholders receiving 2½% of original investment
- Subject to reparations all being paid
- Annual lottery for long-term holders who with luck would have loans redeemed at 12½% without waiting for reparations settlement
- Public outcry led to slender satisfaction of creditors' demands
- Accompanied by violent speculative trading in government stocks/bonds on Bourse
- Practice already proceeding unhealthily in respect of plunging French franc

### Brief Economic Recovery

- Economic recovery, fall of interest rates from January's 100% to May's 30%
- Reduced unemployed number to half by April 1924
- Great increase in marks in circulation during this period led to dangerous Rentenmark weakness signs
- **Schacht** intervened at once with drastic credit restrictions
- **Reichsbankspräsident's** unpopularity enormous
- Stability immediately restored, but not without return to higher interest rates, more bankruptcies, more unemployment
- Marks became practically unobtainable
- At that juncture: Dawes Committee presented plan
- Adopted by Allies in August
- Reparations to be paid only to extent Germany's currency could stand strain
- New payments schedule (still without specification of total settlement)
- To be helped off ground with large foreign loan
- Evacuation at last of French and Belgians from Ruhr
- Dawes Plan provided for Reichsmark introduction to replace old currencies

### Second False Dawn

- Once more: immediate confidence return
- Dawes loan success followed by other foreign loans
- All helped revive trade, send shares up, unemployment figures back down
- By December 1924: figure for registered unemployed (about half real number) as low as 436,000
- Until Hitler's arrival in power in Berlin: would never be so few out of work again
- Once more: false dawn
- Germany's trouble: inflation boom never been liquidated
- Stabilisation ended period when entrepreneurs could borrow as much as wished at everyone else's expense
- Vast number of enterprises established/expanded during monetary plenty rapidly became unproductive when capital grew short

### Post-Stabilization Depression

- More realistic transport, fuel, food prices
- Return of rents to economic levels
- Meant wages too had to be raised substantially in real terms
- Firms that mushroomed during inflation now found real interest paid on loans for first time positive rather than negative
- Rates appeared lower though
- Perhaps most significant: for first time obliged to pay real taxes
- Many extremely high because of necessity to rapidly balance budget and bring official salaries (fallen disastrously) up to acceptable level
- Companies often unable to buy new machinery after stabilisation
- Huge stocks of unsold iron and coal began building up in Ruhr
- Not even foreign loans flowing in able to prevent seizing up once again of Ruhr mining industry
- Pit after pit (especially any producing poor quality coal) forced to close
- Workers flocked from pit to agriculture, from mines/quarries/engineering to food production/direct consumer goods/building
- **Hugo Stinnes** himself had been deceived by artificial prosperity of inflation into fanatical confidence in coal's future
- Post-stabilisation depression in coal, iron, steel industries (contriving even Ruhr townships depopulation) led eventually June 1925 to Stinnes empire collapse

### The Stinnes Débâcle

- That event finally pricked the abscess
- Great groups who resisted over-expansion during depreciation (Krupp, Thyssen, Gelsenkirchen) able to ride storm
- Others (Sichel and Kahn groups) foundered
- Defects of "vertical" industrial concentrations (embracing all manufacture stages from raw material to finished article) revealed
- Strength of horizontal combines confirmed
- Speculators found they had to pay for folly, improvidence, greed
- Old captains of industry resumed sway
- Stinnes débâcle demonstrated great industrial possessions couldn't be held without adequate liquid resources
- As early as June 1924: Stinnes trying to pledge Bochumer Verein and Gelsenkirchen shares against Dutch loans
- Vertical combines were inefficient and unprofitable except under exceptional conditions which bred them

### Final Collapse

- Germany underwent almost every conceivable collapse form during previous six years
- Military, political, social, financial, economic
- Now crashed downwards again just as many demoralised people supposed that with international help she was beginning to rise from knees
- Confidence was shattered
- Flow of foreign money slackened
- Reichsbank policy of credit restriction maintained firmly to counteract net outflow of gold and foreign exchange
- Working population shifting accompanied by new, terrifying unemployment/short-time working increase
- Because labour was buyers' market: those with work nonetheless often compelled to work 54-hour week
- Alarming rise in cost of living (to prevent agitation, index had to be cooked)
- New spectacular toll of bankruptcies
- Public works instituted to try mopping up labour
- Unemployed figure had passed 1,300,000 by December 1925
- Gathering pace daily
- Return of rational conditions brought necessary but brutal slimming of immensely swollen public services
- Those dismissed from posts and railways now joined not only by former miners/steel-workers but by many who'd started businesses on their own

### The Frozen Capital Problem

- Inflationary period: new factories built, old establishments reorganised/extended, new plant laid down
- Participations in all fields of industrial activity bought up
- Great amorphous concerns founded
- Too late found this process undermined country's capital structure
- Capital frozen in factories for which (because of rentier extermination and real wages reduction of so many consumer classes) there was no economic demand
- Once demand for goods shut off and flow of cash dammed: productive apparatus fate sealed
- Even in 1924: firms of undoubted solidity and large assets unable to pay out trifling money sums
- In 1926: apparatus still too great in relation to working capital and nation's consumption power
- Thus: 1913 had 7,700 bankruptcies; 1924 only 5,700; 1925 was 10,800

<!-- pp. 221-240 -->

## Post-Stabilization Crisis (1925-1926)

### Wave of Bankruptcies

- Between Q3 1925 and Q2 1927, **31,000 bankruptcies** occurred — rate of 15,000/year
- Many bankruptcies refused by courts due to absence of assets to meet claims
- Protested bills per week doubled from 2,691 to 5,406 between May-November 1925
- Banks immobilized by bad loans to industrial customers, unwilling to liquidate securities or take over bankrupt factories
- Stock market moribund with shares far below value, endless sellers and no buyers

### Mass Unemployment Returns

- December 1925: **genuine mass unemployment** emerged — the nightmare 1922's inflation policies sought to avoid
- **Krupp** dismissed 12,000 men; similar scale dismissals at **Mannesmann, Gelsenkirchen, Phoenix, Prussian State Mines**
- **Thyssen** restricted output; **Gasmotorenfabrik Deutz** sacked hundreds, closed December 15
- **Osram** on short-time; **Benz** closed for a month; **Opel** dismissed 5,000 of 7,000 workers
- Locomotive industry producing only 2% of pre-war output
- 145 bankruptcies in textile industry (first half November alone)
- 179 Saxon factories temporarily shut; Black Forest clockmakers 65% unemployed/short-time
- Shipbuilding at half pre-war employment, 4/5 of 1924 tonnage launched
- **February 1926**: registered unemployed exceeded **2 million**
- Average stayed above 2 million throughout 1926; still nearly 1.5 million in December

### Professional Class Recovery

- By May 1926, professional classes (doctors, lawyers, professors, writers) recovered radically
- Fees being paid, services required in full measure
- By 1927, living standards very high during national prosperity boom
- Physical exercise and gymnasticism widespread — Germany attempting to become "strong and beautiful"
- **Exception**: legions of unemployables whose subsistence dissipated, and hundreds of thousands without work bore "outward scars" of inflation

## Chapter 15: The Wounds are Bared

### Psychological Trauma of Inflation

- Inflation's scourge followed defeat's scourge — hesitation to attribute 1920s psychological trauma solely to economic insecurity
- **National disintegration and social upheavals** unconnected to money supply promote ethical degeneration, contempt for old behavioral standards
- Those who lived through/observed inflation attributed **fear, greed, immorality, demoralization, dishonor** primarily to inflation

### The Blame Game

- Shrill debate over who was to blame for the "unceasing, increasing financial crisis"
- Every excuse found except the fundamental one
- **Mirabeau's famous peroration** (year before Revolution's *assignats*, months before death): *"La banqueroute, la hideuse banqueroute, est là. Elle menace de consumer vous, vos propriétés, votre honneur - et vous délibérez!"*

### Judith Listowel on Hungary

- **Frau Eisenmenger** (Austria) and **Judith Listowel** (Hungary) observed how want and status loss led to:
  - Fall of ethical standards
  - Family quarrels
  - Communal hatred, especially **against Jews**
- Listowel rejects generalization that everyone spent whole time seeking material goods for reinvestment

> "My relations and friends were too stupid. They didn't understand what inflation meant. They didn't rush to get rid of their money (that was what the Jews and the Germans did). All my relations thought it would stop the next week - and they went on thinking so."

> "They woke up very late. They started selling their valuables because they couldn't buy food - the china from the mantelpiece, the furniture, the silver... And if you had to sell a valuable writing desk for money which was worth only half as much a week later, of course there was ill-feeling."

### Rise of Anti-Semitism

- **Anti-Semitism negligible before inflation**
- Though **Bela Kun's revolution** was mainly run by Jews, the White Terror had largely purged political resentment
- Jews badly treated in Hungary since 1860s, not received socially for many years
- Nine out of ten bore grudges; when immigrant gentiles arrived, who was to blame them for taking opportunities?
- When Jews made success of inflation, they were hated; when ostentatious about it, hated even more
- Wiser Jews, especially older ones, greatly upset and remonstrated with younger, foreseeing the antagonism their behavior would create

> "The Jews probably paid fair prices for what they bought - but that wasn't the point... My father realised that the fault did not lie with the Jews but somehow much higher up. Of course, it would be wrong to give the impression that there were not many impoverished Jews in Budapest and other places who had got things just as wrong as everybody else."

### Corruption in Hungarian Civil Service

- Elite branches (Army, diplomatic corps, financial administration) usually maintained old traditions of integrity — and suffered for it
- Families of senior civil servants trying to stick to **Austro-Hungarian Monarchy ethics** often met disaster unless they had land
- Young resented parents' maintenance of "uncomfortable principles" while friends' families made compromises

### New Forms of Corruption

- **Real corruption found less in central government than at county level** — entirely new phenomenon
- When father protested irregularities permitted — keeping two sets of books, accepting bribes, cash payments, extra jobs leaving less time for official work — reply was: *"Your Excellency, will you feed my children?"*
- **Communal hatred was new. Social resentment was new. Bribery and corruption: that was new.**
- Same in Austria and Poland: *"If you get the same fever, you get the same symptoms."*

### German Corruption

- **Lord D'Abernon** (1924): corruption among officials "appalling" — before war, bribery almost unknown, high degree of uncorruptibility evident
- Few in any class not infected by or prey to the pervasive, soul-destroying influence of constant capital erosion and future uncertainty
- From tax-evasion, food-hoarding, currency speculation, illegal exchange transactions — all crimes against State became survival matters
- Short step to breaching Commandments
- Where lower classes turned to theft and prostitution (figures up 50% in 1923 over 1913 and 1925), middle/upper classes resorted to graft and fraud
- Once bribery was the norm, normal people resorted to it — more so in months of abject scarcity
- **Corruption bred corruption**; Civil Service caught infection even in war years; **counterfeiting widespread**

### Moral Decay

- Old virtues of thrift, honesty, hard work lost appeal
- Speculation in currency or shares could yield far greater rewards than labor
- **Reichsbank** prepared to be dupe of borrowers; no industrialist/businessman/merchant would let enrichment opportunities slip by
- For less astute, it was incentive enough and arguably morally defensible to play markets and exploit unworkable fiscal system merely to maintain financial and social position
- As position slid away, **patriotism, social obligations, morals slid away with it**
- **The ethic cracked**
- Willingness to break rules reflected common attitude
- Not being able to hold what one had or what one had saved was real basis of human despair — jealousy, fear, outrage not far removed

### Share Capital Abuses

- Share capital abuses became common as shares concentrated in profiteers' hands
- **Stresemann** (*New York World*, summer 1923) defensively suggested: *"our whole business life has acquired the character of dishonesty and corruption because the value of the mark in June does not happen to be the same as the value in July"*
- Privately admitted substance and shadow of improbity were the same

### Personal Testimonies

- **Most people aware standards had fallen**
- **Erna von Pustau**: *"It is the ordinary conditions of our life that make a woman evil"* — supposed her callousness was just part of general moral decay
- **Frau von Eisenmenger's diary** equally contained repeated regrets about deceits life was forcing her into
- Her stock of good cigars enabled her to obtain transport permit from *Volkswehr*, normally forbidden to bourgeoisie — but business was done in transport permits as in anything else
- She shared philosophic resentment about others' behavior:

> "The growing lack of consideration for one's fellow men ... impresses me very painfully. I can understand, however, that the instinct of self-preservation in people whose very existence is threatened should overcome all moral laws ... It has become common for better and more warmly clad people to be robbed of their clothes in the street, and obliged to go home barefoot."

- Less sympathy for President of Salzburg Provincial Government arrested for illicit trading in government property (food, leather, clothes): *"These are the enemies in our camp, but how few of them are detected!"*

### 1924 Scandals

- Not until well after return to stability did corruption in high places become known
- March 1924 sentencing of **Dr Zeigner** (ex-Premier of Saxony) for corrupt practices and bribery raised scarcely a ripple
- End of year brought formidable array of financial scandals confirming old universal integrity had sunk in whirlpool of inflation, delivering stunning blow to nation's morale

### The Barmat Affair

- **Barmat and Kutisker affairs** rocked country and shocked world, unfolding backwards like Ibsen drama
- *Démenti* issued by incriminated declaring innocence, only to be confronted by irrefutable contrary evidence
- Nationalist newspapers tried making political capital until arrest of highly-placed Prussian officials showed corruption not a Republican monopoly

### Iwan Kutisker

- **Lithuanian Jew** who moved to Germany during German revolution, recognized inflation principles immediately
- Started with modest sum amassed in dollars during German occupation
- Acquired bank and directorships of well-known firms, became financially influential
- By 1923, bank hard hit by inflation but not so hard it couldn't accommodate Chief of Passport Office (Ministry of Interior), **Herr Bartels**
- Kutisker obliging to Bartels re: indicating which aliens should be expelled
- Fellow Lithuanian **Holzmann** (1924) couldn't repay Kutisker 200,000 gold marks advanced in heady inflation days despite providing security worth half a million gold marks
- Unwilling to be sent home on such pretext, Holzmann took public issue with his countryman
- From then on, inglorious tale of graft and blackmail began unfolding
- **November 1924**: Bartels arrested for bribery and corruption

### Julius Barmat

- **Notorious swindler**, Russian Jew of Lithuanian extraction
- 1921: acquired certificate from Prussian Ministry of Interior instructing Dutch frontier authorities that he and six other Barmat family members belonged to Dutch legation in Berlin, usual customs formalities waived
- Minister later asserted he acted only on direct request from Chancellor **Fehrenbach's** office

### The Barmat Brothers

- Four Barmat brothers directors of **Barmat Konzern** (interests in 45 industrial and banking businesses)
- One brother ostentatiously occupied mansion on lake-girt island of Schwanenwerder with flotilla of motor launches
- Each owned one or more palatial residences
- Vulgarity of all was byword, noted even by leading Social Democrat deputies who (according to Right-wing *Vorwärts*) frequently enjoyed their hospitality

### Profiteering Schemes

- **Inflation profiteering**: borrowing paper marks, converting to goods/factories, repaying lenders with depreciated paper
- **Deflation profiteering** (which Kutisker and Barmats rapidly saw): selling everything for new stable marks, lending proceeds at extravagant interest rates in period of tightest imaginable credit

### Barmat-Michael Dispute

- Not entirely necessary to sell something first
- **Julius Barmat** and **Jacob Michael** (Frankfurt Jew, postwar speculator who unloaded shares for cash early) found themselves in ostensible dispute about sum of money
- Together approached president and board of **Prussian State Bank** requesting arbitration for small percentage of money involved
- Bank among oldest and most respected in country, epitome of financial discipline and rectitude
- Because of strict avoidance of speculation, solidity not undermined by inflation
- Higher officers enjoyed very special confidence

### The Arbitration

- Bank president **Herr von Dombois** and two directors (**Geheimrat Rühe**, **Ministerial-Director Hellwig**) surprised to find:
  - Sum in dispute extraordinarily big
  - Percentage they eventually received amounted to nearly **40,000 gold marks**
- Large credits from *Seehandlung* (Prussian State Bank) began flowing to both Barmat and Kutisker
- At time when money so scarce Finance Minister and President of Reichsbank (Luther and Schacht) daily appealing to commerce and industry to respect restrictions
- When best securities wouldn't release a pfennig, two families of Lithuanian Jewish adventurers on most questionable securities borrowed **50 million gold marks** from *Seehandlung* at 10-18% and re-lent at 100-200%

### Unraveling the Scandal

- Following leads from Bartels arrest, bank president and two directors apprehended after Christmas 1924
- **Dr Rühe** (Financial Director of Prussian State) charged with conspiracy with Kutisker
- Bank president removed from post
- *Seehandlung* accounts showed loss of some **15 million marks**
- Kutisker and Barmats arrested

### Further Revelations

- *Seehandlung* not only concern enjoying Barmats' patronage
- **Reich Post Office** advanced Julius Barmat total of **15 million gold marks** during year
- Credits issued personally by Minister of Posts and Telegraphs (**Dr Höfle**), though three signatures officially required on cheques
- **Höfle resigned January 9**, suspended from Reichstag membership along with another prominent Centre Party member
- **300 police** took part in 30-40 arrests — 13 State officials
- Other *Seehandlung* bankers hauled in, including **Herr Kautz** (formerly councillor with Ministry of Finance)
- **Herr Richter** (Social Democrat President of Berlin Police) admitted opening account with Barmat bank in same circumstances as Bartels
- **Herr Friedländer** (old-established Hoffman and Friedländer bank) killed himself with Veronal overdose on learning of arrest of his stepson (director of one of Barmat's offshoots)

### High-Level Involvement

- Trail went along higher corridors of power
- Confidential report on Barmats disappeared from Foreign Office
- Minute to former Chancellor **Scheidemann** from **Reichspräsident Ebert** himself asking him to help Barmat
- Found Post Office lent **5 million more gold marks** to another unspecified client
- Bank loans to **Jacob Michael** discovered
- Though President **Ebert** only implicated by rumor, his son deeply involved

### Addison's Commentary

> "Our good friend 'der brave Joseph' [Dr Wirth, ex-Chancellor] who posed as embodiment of Parsifallike ignorance of wicked world and of transparent honesty, is said to be in it up to the hilt, in as much as through his agency his own company succeeded in extracting a trifle of 14 million gold marks out of the Post Office funds. To name the others would be to give a complete list of all the Social Democrat leaders and of the most highly placed officials ... The Right are biting their fists with rage that all this didn't come out before the December election."

### Nationalist Involvement

- Equally believed Nationalists involved
- Sums involved: upwards of **£2 million in bribes** over and above initial loans
- Venality of bank's permanent officials facilitated *Seehandlung* transaction
- Bribery or political influence enabled Post Office transactions
- **Subversion general**; no one questioned much of iceberg still lay below surface
- Miserable story echoed four years later in **Sklarek Brothers scandal** (massive bribery of Berlin municipality, including Chief Burgomaster, by tailors firm)
- Barmat-Kutisker episode indicated advanced state of corruption in higher official class, doubtless due to:
  - General demoralization from prolonged financial chaos
  - Inadequate salaries paid during months immediately following Germany's financial reconstruction

## Post-Stabilization Germany (1925-1927)

### Two Major Events (1925)

- **Hindenburg** succeeded as President of Reich (April)
- **Treaty of Locarno** signed (December)
- Neither viewed with more than minority approval

### American Loans and Extravagance

- Flow of American funds into country: **£200 million (1924-1926)**, £1,000 million by 1929
- Though interrupted periodically, induced spirit of state/municipal/personal extravagance
- **Parker Gilbert** (American Reparations Agent-General in Berlin) wondered:
  - How country's foreign debts ever going to be repaid
  - How much loans used to meet reparations payments under Dawes Plan as they became due
- **Dr Schacht** loudly critical of public spending policy
- **Dr Stresemann** (Foreign Minister) wrote to Mayor of Duisburg:

> "The fact that the Prussian State has granted 14 million marks for the rebuilding of the Berlin Opera House, and will perhaps raise it to 20 million, creates the impression in the world that we are rolling in money ... Dresden builds a Museum of Hygiene with the help of a Reich subsidy ... Please tell me what I am to say to the representatives of foreign powers when they tell me that all these things awaken the impression that Germany won rather than lost the war."

### Recovery and Confidence

- No one disposed to take much notice
- Traders asserted business unprofitable owing to heavy State charges
- But remained among survivors of 1925 shakeout:
  - Deep satisfaction at improvement in country's finances
  - Firm confidence life would henceforth be better
- In this mood, **savings habit returned** to people who learned hard way as individuals to rid themselves of cash at earliest opportunities
- **Habit of borrowing** acquired during inflationary period set in more fiercely than ever

### Public Spending Spree

- Federal states took lead (not unnatural with solid taxation system boosted by lavish foreign loans)
- Public spending sprees possible on scale unknown since before war
- States and municipalities making up for what missed during inflationary period when roles reversed, private industrial interests flourished at their expense
- Much expenditure on public building programs designed expressly to mop up unemployment

### Rationalization and Cartels

- High interest rates (1926) may have given businessmen cause to hesitate but hardly prevented wholesale "rationalization"
- To characterize pre-slump years: big industrialists formed cartels, first nationally then internationally, to keep prices high
- Federal states could only hope to make own interest payments on foreign loans if more loans kept coming
- Soon easy long-term loans replaced by stiffer short-term ones
- In borrowing practice, smaller firms and entrepreneurs obliged to follow big industrialists' and public bodies' lead
- Before long, even peasants as badly in debt as municipalities
- **Public and private light-headedness about money matters one of legacies of inflation** — deadly one to have acquired

### 1926 Prosperity Observations

- British Foreign Office staff member's travelling holiday all over Germany (August 1926)
- German middle and lower classes had money to spend freely
- Able to travel about in multitudes
- All well "decently" and newly (though hideously) clad in clothes dearer in Germany than Britain
- Cafés and places of amusement full to brim, though neither refreshments nor amusements noticeably cheap
- Museums, picture galleries, castles crowded with German trippers paying entrance money sometimes two or three marks a head
- Festivals of all kinds organized by municipal and state governments, putting up expensive new exhibition buildings, depending on German (not foreign) tourists to survive
- Observed many formerly well-off still in straitened circumstances
- Saw no reason to reduce annuities payable under Dawes Plan
- **Stresemann's fears of jaundiced foreign eyes entirely justified**

### False Prosperity as Prelude to Depression

- **False prosperity of post-inflation Germany** — second onset of massive economic self-deception within decade
- In this case flowering over great unemployment below
- Poor psychological prelude to slump conditions to come
- Inflation experience itself ensured human emergencies of economic depression couldn't be met by any German Government with even modicum of monetary flexibility
- **"It is easy enough to understand why the record of the sad years 1919-1923 always weighs like a nightmare on the German people"** — Bresciani-Turroni's summary

### Survival of Democracy and Rise of Authoritarianism

- Democracy may have survived inflation, but little evidence of universal gratitude for that deliverance
- **Monarchism more popular creed**
- Exposure to air of Germany's moral wounds (financial scandals of inflationary years) contributed greatly to strengthening disciplinarian side of nation's character
- **Lord D'Abernon** (with **Dr Stresemann**, principal architect of **Locarno Pact** to bring Germany back into civilized co-existence) viewed country through spectacles of bleakest realism:

> "If one drives on a Sunday afternoon through any German province there is always the same sight to be seen - men of every age and every corpulence, similarly dressed, marching rigidly in rank, accompanied by bands and banners, and the applause of their attendant womankind and youth. They represent every school of political thought, and one will see in the same hour companies of country squires with their tenants and retainers and 'proletarian centuries' performing the same evolutions and carrying with the same invincible solemnity the emblems of Imperial Germany and Revolutionary Russia. It is thus not astonishing that there are in this country great numbers of ordinary mankind - excellent fathers and husbands of families - who can think of foreign politics only in terms of war."

- Same atavism illustrated in treatment of treason cases in German courts
- Judges (ordinarily men of broad views and enlightened humanity) would inflict sentences of savagery that would leave Englishmen aghast
- **"It would be straining ambition too far to hope that in such a paste as this the leaven of Locarno will work anything but slowly."**

## Preparing for Future War

### Nationalist and Monarchist Movements

- Aggressive posturing of extreme, reactionary, militarist groups may have cooled somewhat since disappearance of inflationary conditions
- But party discipline still strong; political strength of Nationalist parties in and out of Reichstag grew steadily
- **Reparations, "war guilt lie," continued occupation of Rhineland** still targets and rallying causes of Right
- **Hindenburg's election** (perhaps primarily result of national sentimental sympathy for old field-marshal who lost great war, plus clever timing and ruthless machination) gave decided fillip to Nationalist and monarchist movements
- To some appeared to herald reversion to "Prussian" Germany

### General Wauchope's Warning

- **General Wauchope** (memorandum to London, beginning of 1927): Germany morally mobilized for war in future to right wrongs of Treaty of Versailles

> "The greatest loss which Germany suffered was the ruin of her middle classes. If her 'natural leaders' are now to be found in the present party of the Right, Germany may again become a danger. It is common knowledge that great numbers of factories could be rapidly reorganised as in 1914-1915 for the production of war material if the government wished. Many are so overbuilt at present that they could produce a large military as well as a large commercial output. The last war showed that in time of need output per man could be made to increase."

### German Productivity and Militarization

- **Wauchope** pointed out: output per man in Germany 40% below that in United States, only 90% of what had been achieved pre-war, but **40% above output per man in Britain**
- Deduced fair chance of fighting new war with Germany "within the life of this generation"
- Watched with awe great attempts at physical culture throughout Germany to prepare nation for future struggles

### The German Worker

- Matter of general remark among Allied observers: German laborer worked considerably longer for less than British counterpart, did so unremittingly except for usual pauses
- During whole working hours, unhampered by trade union restrictions as to quantity of output
- For French particularly, confinement in middle of disunited, work-shy, war-weary western nations of energetic, well-organised block of **60 million industrious and martially-minded people**, overflowing with self-justification and aspiring to position of pre-eminence they thought their due, constituted serious cause for alarm
- Existence of ill-suppressed revanchism and highly expert nuclear **Reichswehr** which **von Seeckt** salvaged from wreck of war were additional reasons for fears, which events fully to justify

<!-- pp. 241-260 -->

## Epilogue: Lessons from Hyperinflation

### The Pre-1914 Financial Mindset

- Recipients of financial largesse in Germany turned money to advantage: converting to material assets, foreign exchange, or using it to speculate against the mark
- **Havenstein** and the Reichsbank only understood financial conditions that prevailed before 1914
- Mild inflation has therapeutic advantages for democracies dealing with social and economic problems
- Most electorates accept politicians' pious statements about controlling prices, yet modern currencies lose significant value (Deutschmark lost 2/3 purchasing power 1948-1975; pound lost half 1970-1975)
- Neither case represented deliberate, cynical policy—would have been claimed by 1920s German authorities who looked for causes beyond their printing press and tax system

> "Once an inflation is well under way (as Schmölders has it) 'it develops a powerful lobby that has no interest in rational arguments.'"

### The Political Impossibility of Stopping Inflation

- No moment between 1914 and summer 1923 when currency stability could not theoretically have been secured through new bank of issue with sufficient backing
- Until late date, German gold and foreign currency reserves always constituted substantial proportion of circulating paper's exchange value
- After war ended, practical difficulties unrelated to Germany's refusal to see connection between depreciation and money supply

**Mid-1920 turning point:**
- After brief post-Kapp *Putsch* stability, German export competitiveness declined and unemployment began rising
- Recovery required immediate repercussions: bankruptcies, redundancies, short-time working, unemployment, strikes, hunger, demonstrations, Communist agitation, violence, civil disorder collapse, fear of insurrection and revolution
- The point not lost on inflators—stabilization postponed as prospective consequences became more frightening
- Day by day through 1920-1922, reckoning was postponed, more readily as consequences became more frightening
- Conflicting objectives of avoiding unemployment and avoiding insolvency ceased to conflict when Germany had both

> "The longer the delay, the more savage the cure."

### The Pattern Across Austria, Hungary, and Germany

**Austria by end of 1922:**
- In hands of receivers, regained stable currency only under absolute direction of foreigner
- **Hungary** passed chance of self-redemption, later underwent equal hardship and suffering for public servants
- **Germany** returned under military dictatorship with much of constitution suspended—State of Emergency only indirectly necessitated by financial destruction

**Common pattern:**
- All three countries required bailout by others
- Each accepted greater economic disruption and unemployment than feared when excessive printing might have been stopped
- In all three cases, after inflation reached advanced stage, financial and economic disaster became prerequisite of recovery

### The Take-Off Point into Hyperinflation

- Take-off point in inflationary progress (when it became self-generating and politically irreducible except for short periods) not found on graphs of currency depreciation, circulation velocity, or balance of payments deficit
- Nor did it coincide with ultimate crisis of confidence (Rathenau's murder, Rhine ports occupation, London Ultimatum)—all had immediate seismic effects but lay on falling curve of political possibility

**What really broke Germany:**
- Constant taking of soft political option on money
- Take-off point was moral, not financial
- Political excuse was despicable—no imaginable circumstances more unsuited to imposing new financial order than November 1923

> "Inflation was no longer an option. The Rentenmark was itself hardly more than an expedient then, and could scarcely have been introduced successfully had not the mark lost its entire meaning."

- Stability came only when abyss had been plumbed, credible mark could fall no more
- When everything four years of financial cowardice, wrong-headedness and mismanagement had fashioned to avoid had taken place
- When inconceivable had ineluctably arrived

### The Nature of Money and Value

**Money as medium of exchange:**
- Only useful when acknowledged by more than one person
- More general the acknowledgement, more useful it is
- Once no one acknowledged it, Germans learned their paper money had no value or use—save for papering walls or making darts

**The discovery that shattered society:**
- Traditional repository of purchasing power had disappeared
- No means left of measuring worth of anything
- For many, life became obsessional search for *Sachwerte* (things of 'real', constant value)
- **Stinnes** bought factories, mines, newspapers
- Railway workers bought gewgaws
- Degree of necessity became sole criterion of value, basis of everything from barter to behaviour
- Man's values became animal values

> "Contrary to any philosophic assumption, it was not a salutary experience."

### Hierarchy of Human Needs

**What is precious sustains life:**
- When life secure, society acknowledges value of luxuries—objects, materials, services, enjoyments (civilised or extravagant) without which life proceeds but is less pleasant
- When life insecure or conditions harsh, values change
- Without warmth, adequate clothing, roof over head, life may be difficult to sustain for more than few weeks
- Without food, life shorter still
- At top of scale: most valuable commodities perhaps water, most precious of all air (life lasts only minutes without)

**For the destitute in Germany and Austria:**
- Existence came very near these metaphysical conceptions
- Reference to Müller in *All Quiet on the Western Front*: 'and bequeathed me his boots—the same that he once inherited from Kemmerick. I wear them, for they fit me quite well. After me Tjaden will get them: I have promised them to him.'

**In hyperinflation:**
- In war, boots or seat in boat more vital than untold millions
- In hyperinflation, kilo of potatoes worth more than family silver; side of pork more than grand piano
- Prostitute in family better than infant corpse
- Theft preferable to starvation
- Warmth finer than honour
- Clothing more essential than democracy
- Food more needed than freedom

<!-- pp. 261-273 -->

## Notes and References Section

### Historical Sources and Documentation

- **The Nemesis of Power** by Macmillan (1953), Part I, Chapter I (vii) - referenced as key source on power dynamics
- Germany's WWI casualties: 1.6 million dead, 3.5 million total casualties (excluding labor force losses from confiscated territories)
- **21st Earl of Erroll** (1876-1941) - British High Commissioner of Inter-Allied Rhineland High Commission, 1921-1928
- **M. Poincaré** (soon to become Prime Minister of France) - skeptical of fixed reparations sum, resigned commission chairmanship
- Great Britain's national debt: £8,075 million at war's end

### Treaty of Versailles and Political Commentary

- **Lord Curzon's** skeptical notation on treaty readership: "The idea of the 'lower classes' 'reading' the treaty is humorous"
- Voting paradox in territorial disputes: more heads voted for Germany, more communes for Poland
- Oxford historian **A.L. Rowse** (Provost of Queen's College, 1937-1946) cited as authority
- **Berliner Tageblatt** (February 9, 1921) - key German newspaper source

### British Diplomatic and Financial Figures

- **Sir William Seeds** - later British Ambassador at Moscow (1939-1940)
- **Sir Joseph Addison** - Chargé d'Affaires in Berlin (1879-1953)
- Director of Bank of England - joined Treasury in 1904 (1882-1935)
- Lord Curzon's Foreign Office document comment marked "Amusing" - suggested sending to the King

### German Economic Collapse Indicators

- Share price collapse examples (Dec 1920 to Dec 22, 1921):
  - Daimler: 295 → 800
  - Allgemeine Elektrizitatsges: 319 → 1,100 → 657
  - Deutsche Bank: 327 → 701 → 475
- Annual bankruptcy figures from 1912: 9,218 → 9,725 → 7,739 → 4,594 → 2,279 → 1,240 → 807 → 1,015 → 1,324 → 2,975
- Reference to **David Lloyd George** and **Heinemann** in "The Truth about Reparations and War-debts"

### Defining Hyperinflation

- **Phillip Cagan** definition: hyperinflation begins when monthly price rises first exceed 50% (equivalent to 600% annual rate)
- Source: essay in "Studies in the Quantity Theory of Money" (edited by **Milton Friedman**, University of Chicago Press, 1956)

### Austrian Crisis Context

- **Owen Phillpotts** - extensive country experience as Vice-Consul then Consul in Vienna (1906-1914)
- Author of "Austria of Today" (Macmillan, 1932)
- **Dr A.R. Zimmermann** - formerly Burgomaster of Rotterdam

### Hungary's Post-War Territorial Losses

- Hungary lost all best territory under Treaty of Trianon, retaining only 14 comitats out of 64
- British Foreign Office privately admitted "reparations on top of that are a bit much" (though not stated publicly)
- **Sir Thomas Hohler** (1871-1946) - diplomat referenced

### Comparative Price Examples

- French coke prices doubled from January to March figures
- **Baldwin** succeeded **Bonar Law** as Prime Minister in April (month before Curzon's chagrin)
  - Source: Harold Nicolson, "Curzon: the Last Phase," Chapter XII
- **Judith, Countess of Listowel** (formerly Judith de Marffy-Mantuano)

### Infrastructure and Employment Crisis

- Quote: "Earth's little lordling stays to his casting true, As odd as on the day when he was new"
- **Sir William Acworth** - technical adviser for railways, November 1923 report recommended dispensing with one man out of four
- Reference to **Bresciani-Turroni**, "The Economics of Inflation" (originally "Le Vicende del Marco Tedesco," 1931), pp 253-285 for detailed discussion of shares under inflation

### International Incidents and Political Tensions

- Measure taken in retaliation for shooting of Italian commission member on Greek soil (Greece-Albania border delimitation)
- **Stresemann** heard new National Anthem verse: "Deutschland, Deutschland, über alles, und im Unglück nun erst recht, Erst im Unglück lässt's sich sagen ob die Liebe frei und echt"
  - Translation: "Germany, Germany, above all, and more than ever in distress: to be first in misfortune lets one say whether charity is free and true"

### British Observer Accounts

- **Later 1st Lord Killearn** - just returned to Foreign Office from Siberia
- Wine pricing: bottle of good claret at Savoy Hotel in 1923 cost ~10 shillings (10-12 times London price)
- **Sir Alexander Cadogan, O.M.** - Permanent Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs (1938-1946)

### Anti-Semitism and Political Extremism

- **The Post** characterized as unfair to **Kahr** - pietist, difficult to deal with, saw himself as Providential instrument to deliver Germany from Socialists and Jews
- **Elphick's letter to London** (postmarked October 22) bore stamps with face value of 148,000,000 marks

### Gresham's Law and Currency Depreciation

- **Professor J. Shield Nicholson** article in **The Scotsman** (February 10, 1923):

> "After a point in the depreciation of paper money the reverse of what is called Gresham's Law comes into play: the legal tender in spite of penalties loses its purchasing power. The better money drives out the worse ... The feeble efforts of the German Government to restrain speculation in paper marks are as useless as the chains and death penalties decreed to support the Assignats [of the French Revolution, which were made legal tender in 1790 but abandoned in 1796 as unworkable]."

- Curzon's response to this commentary detailed in **Harold Nicolson**, "Curzon: The Last Phase," Chapter XII

### Tax System Dysfunctions

- Taxation system based on paper values until December 1923
- October example: passport at Polish border still cost 2 paper marks, tariff unchanged since the war

### Hitler's Rise to Power

- Accounts in **Wheeler-Bennett's** "The Nemesis of Power" and **Bullock's** "Hitler: A Study in Tyranny" cited as requiring no embellishment
- **Konrad Heiden** in "Der Führer: Hitler's Rise to Power" explains how Hitler exploited economic fears across all classes

### Peak Hyperinflation Statistics

- Highest denomination ever printed: **100,000,000,000,000 marks** (one hundred billion/trillion) - referred to as "one hundred billion" in Germany and Britain
- Government expenditure: 6 quintillions (US notation, with 18 noughts)
- Revenue contributed: mere 6 quadrillions (one-thousandth as much)

### Currency Stabilization Mechanics

- Had mark been stabilized at November 15 rate, conversion coefficient of 1.66 recurring would have been needed for all conversions
- **Philip Snowden** (Chancellor of the Exchequer, 1930) estimated war cost Great Britain identical sum to Germany's debt
- British and German "trillion" (1,000,000³) caused international confusion - British Embassy adopted American/French notation style for larger amounts

### Social Disruption and Political Consequences

- Introduction of half-starved poor into Reichstag precincts in August contributed to **Cuno's** fall
- Bacon imports mainly used to supply pork deficiency
- Issue of silver/copper coins (not paper) intended to encourage thrift and restore confidence
- Style change aimed at eliminating large figures

### Legal and Constitutional Changes

- **Supreme Tribunal at Leipzig** judgment (November 23, 1923) most notable in legal revaluation
- Reference to **Bresciani-Turroni**, Chapters VII & VIII for fuller account of restitution programme, stock/share behavior and revaluation

### Employment and Labor Statistics

- Average unemployment 1927-1928: 1.4 million
- 1926 figure seriously under-represents true workless total - would have been much greater without British miners' prolongation of General Strike boosting Ruhr mine fortunes
- **Hugo Stinnes** - sometime owner of notorious Hanau war material dump, used as collateral for massive loans

### Crime and Social Order

- Observation: crimes threatening society's survival found more odious than those threatening individual members
- In many communities including Britain, treason remained capital offense where murder was not
- **General Sir Arthur Wauchope** - commanded 2nd Bn Black Watch, Chief of British Section Military Inter-Allied Commission of Control, Berlin (1924-1927)

### Expert Analysis and Commentary

- **General Wauchope** essay "The German Experience" in "Inflation" (Ed. C. Lowell Harriss, Academy of Political Science, New York, vol 31, IV, 1975)
- **Schacht** in "My First Seventy-Six Years," Chapter 21, reports **Reginald McKenna** (formerly Asquith's Chancellor of the Exchequer, then 1923 Chairman of Midland Bank):

> "Since Germany can only make payments by means of exports, she would be compelled to export to such an extent that British industry would suffer intolerably."

